<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UrbanMountRushmore 1stLd-Writethru a0772 02-19 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Urban Mount Rushmore, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0772,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faces of Passersby Projected Over Mount Rushmore Faces on Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with show taking place. Picks
up 12th graf pvs, `Fitzgerald has...'
^By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artist's attempt to project the image of Mount
Rushmore onto the side of a Chicago building, with the faces of
passers-by playing the parts of the four presidents, didn't quite
come off as planned Friday.
   But some residents still gave David Fitzgerald high marks for
attempting his ``Urban Mount Rushmore'' video display, though the
images were much less clear than he had planned.
   ``It's a good way to start,'' said David Harris, 23, of Chicago,
who was among a handful of people who stopped through the Chicago
Loop on his way home to watch the show.
   Harris and his friend, Mark Flower, also 23, said that even
though they expected the images to be larger and easier to see, it
probably was the closest they would get to Mount Rushmore.
   Fitzgerald said that, overall, he wasn't disappointed by his
photographic blending of the faces of passers-by with the figures
of George Washington, Abraham Lincoln, Thomas Jefferson and Teddy
Roosevelt.
   ``We thought the glass would reflect better,'' said Fitzgerald,
24, a graduate student at the School of the Art Institute of
Chicago. ``But the glass is reflecting so much that it's acting
like a mirror.''
   Images of Washington and Lincoln, about 20 feet wide and 16 feet
tall, flashed onto the windows on the side of the Kluczinski
Federal Building. But while Fitzgerald said they were clearly
visible to the people attending a private dinner on the sixth floor
of the Union League Building across the street, they were harder
for street-level pedestrians to recognize.
   Fitzgerald's idea was to take snapshots of as many as 40 people
walking by the Union League Building. Powerful video equipment was
set up to project the images of those photos combined with images
of the figures on Mount Rushmore on the side of the Federal
Building.
   ``The federal building is this city's urban Mount Rushmore and
seemed like the obvious place that we should project them,'' said
Fitzgerald.
   The project was designed to give urban dwellers the chance to
see the historic granite carvings at almost actual size _ a sight
usually reserved for tourists who make the trek to the Black Hills
of South Dakota.
   The Union League, a civic foundation founded while Lincoln was
president, decided to sponsor the event as the centerpiece of a
private dinner.
   Fitzgerald has brought images of other gigantic historic statues
to the city.
   For the Fourth of July in 1986, he used 12 projectors to
recreate a lifesize image of the face of the Statue of iberty on a
wall of the Art Institute, he said.
   During a Chicago Bears game in 1985, Fitzgerald projected a
mammoth ``Bears No. 1'' across the Prudential, CNA Insurance and
Standard Oil buildings.
   ``Art should be for all the people all the time. I really want
to bring my art to the common people,'' Fitzgerald said.
   ``And along the way, I hope to make a couple of people smile.''
</TEXT>
