<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-Education-Social     02-19 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Education-Social,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School, Social Spending Hikes Welcomed, But More Needed, Lawmakers
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's modest proposals for
education and social spending next year drew a relatively warm
reception on Capitol Hill, but two committee chairmen said his
budget requests still aren't high enough.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, chairman of the House Education and Labor
Committee, said the extra spending authority sought for education
programs will not enable more children to participate in Head Start
or Chapter 1, the federal tutoring program for academically
disadvantaged children.
   ``We intend to press for funding over and above the president's
request'' to meet and surpass inflation, Hawkins, D-Calif., said in
a statement following the unveiling Thursday of Reagan's $1.1
trillion fiscal 1989 spending blueprint.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, chairman of the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee, said ``crucial domestic programs'' are
shortchanged in the Reagan budget despite its education increases.
   ``I am concerned that overall spending for social programs will
not even keep up with inflation,'' said Kennedy, D-Mass.
   Reagan just last year asked for cuts of nearly $5 billion in the
education budget. This year he is seeking an 8 percent or $1.5
billion increase for a total of $20.3 billion in expected spending
during fiscal 1989.
   About a third of the money would be added to the Pell grant
program for needy college and trade school students. Grants would
rise from $2,200 to $2,300 a year for total Pell grant spending of
nearly $5 billion.
   Another third would be spent on Chapter 1, bringing that
spending total to nearly $4.4 billion. The program serves 5.6
million students at academic risk.
   The rest would fund modest expansions of a number of programs,
including magnet schools, drug education, adult literacy and
handicapped education. The administration also is proposing a
college savings bond program under which interest on bonds used for
tuition would be tax-free.
   The administration requested modest increases in several social
programs, including rental vouchers for low-income families, drug
abuse prevention, foster care and adoption assistance, and prenatal
care for pregnant women.
   But some programs for the needy would suffer cuts under the
proposal, including a $400 million, 25 percent drop in help for the
poor to pay heating and cooling bills. Head Start would be frozen
at $1.2 billion, and other social programs would be left with no
increases or small ones lagging behind inflation.
   ``The areas still targeted for critical cuts, such as emergency
food and shelter for the homeless, child abuse, discretionary
grants and schooling for migrants, show that the administration
still wants to save money at the expense of the most vulnerable
Americans,'' said Marian Wright Edelman, president of the
Children's Defense Fund.
   The National Council on Senior Citizens condemned the cuts in
heating and cooling bill subsidies and in housing programs for
low-income elderly and rural residents. They constitute ``a grim
reminder that the Reagan administration does not now, nor has it
ever had, compassion for the neediest citizens in our society,''
the group said.
   Many reacted with amusement and skepticism to the
administration's reversal on education, pointing out that the only
other time the president asked for an education budget increase was
in 1984.
   ``We shouldn't be surprised. This is an election year,'' said
Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National Education
Association. ``In election years, the Reagan administration
`supports' education.''
   Education Secretary William Bennett said the turnaround came
because ``the president has decided to make education a priority''
and because the administration realized after several rebuffs that
it was a waste of time to present cuts to Congress.
   He added: ``It's not politically dumb, that's for certain.''
</TEXT>
