<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-ForeignAid     02-19 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Foreign Aid,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Proposing Aid Boost to Trio of Strategic Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, concerned about
threats to U.S rights to overseas military bases, is proposing a
$150 million increase in aid to three strategic allies _ Greece,
Turkey and Portugal.
   The administration also is seeking a slight increase in relief
funds, enough to settle 68,500 refugees in the United States next
year. But officials expressed concern that it won't be enough to
cope with an expected new influx of Vietnamese boat people and
others.
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead outlined Thursday
what he termed a ``bare bones'' request for $18.1 billion in
spending authority for foreign aid and State Department operations
in the fiscal year starting next Oct. 1.
   The total includes $14.3 billion in overseas economic and
military aid commitments and $3.8 billion for the State Department,
the U.S. Information Agency and other foreign affairs operations,
including embassies and consulates.
   The figures would not represent actual outlays, because some of
the money will be spent on projects extending over several years.
The outlay figure for foreign aid is expected to be several billion
dollars less than the $14.3 billion request.
   The budget had few surprises, but some of the requests reflected
new U.S. concerns about conditions abroad.
   The plan calls for a combined commitment of $1.12 billion in
assistance to Turkey, Greece and Portugal, an increase of $150
million over the current allocation.
   All three countries provide bases for U.S. forces, and have said
their willingness to play host depends on how well Washington
assists them.
   Portugal and the United States are reviewing an agreement that
permits American use of Lajes Air Base in the Azores through 1991.
That country would get a $163 million commitment next year,
compared with $117 million this year.
   Turkey would get $623.5 million, up from $525.3 million, and
Greece would get $351.1 million, compared with $344.1 million this
year.
   Negotiations with Greece for renewal of base rights that expire
next year are about to begin. Turkey and the United States recently
signed a base rights agreement, but the Turkish government has
frozen ratification proceedings partly to protest U.S. aid levels.
   Congress traditionally has ignored State Department aid requests
for Greece and Turkey and recalculated assistance to comply with an
unwritten practice of giving Greece $7 for every $10 given to its
bigger and poorer rival, Turkey.
   Reagan's budget plan calls for $340 million in refugee
assistance to allow 68,500 displaced people to enter the United
States. That is about the same number resettled in the current year.
   ``It is not as large an increase as we need, in view of our
estimates of refugee flows,'' Whitehead said, adding that there
will be more Vietnamese boat people and an higher level of Soviet
Jews and Armenians.
   ``We're not really sure just where the money will come from to
cope with the refugees that will be coming out,'' Whitehead said.
   As usual, Israel and Egypt would be the major beneficiaries of
U.S. foreign aid next year, with combined commitments of $5.3
billion in economic and military assistance.
   The more than 40 aid recipients in sub-Saharan Africa, the
world's poorest region, would share $733 million in economic
assistance commitments.
   Military aid to eight Latin-American nations that were cut out
of the 1988 program would be reinstated. Latin America as a whole
would get $90 million more in projected economic assistance and $55
million more in military aid than current levels.
   The administration proposed to eliminate aid to Ireland, which
received $35 million in commitments this year. Whitehead said the
decision was based on a perception that the United States ``does
not receive a real return'' on its investment there.
</TEXT>
