<DOCNO> AP880219-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-What'sNew     02-19 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-What's New,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Older Programs Do Well in Restrained Reagan Budget Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restraint is the note struck by President
Reagan's 1989 budget proposal, but the administration still found
room in the $1.1 trillion spending plan for new projects and hefty
increases in old programs.
   Much of the budget, the last of Reagan's presidency, has been
pre-ordained by a deficit-cutting deal he cut with Congress in
negotiations spurred by the October stock market crash.
   It offers few new ways to spend money and retreats from the
administration's favorite use of tax dollars: the military. The
Pentagon would get only a $9 billion boost to $294 billion. It's
the smallest ever proposed by Reagan and doesn't even keep up with
inflation.
   However there were some winners, including the agency that
regulates the stock market. The Securities and Exchange Commission
would get a 19 percent budget increase and 153 new employees.
   Science and space programs are among the biggest beneficiaries.
While domestic programs overall will increase by only 2 percent,
spending on science will increase 20 percent to $13.1 billion.
   Leading the list is a huge new atomic research facility to study
the building blocks of matter. The Energy Department would get $363
million next year to start construction of the superconducting
super collider at a site yet to be chosen.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration Administrator
James Fletcher says the president's budget establishes, for the
first time, the goal of putting astronauts on other planets. It
provides start-up money for the Pathfinder Project, a research
program designed to put an American astronaut on Mars early in the
next century.
   It also earmarks nearly $1 billion for a permanent manned space
station to orbit the Earth by the mid-1990s and more than $1
billion in added funds to help get the space shuttle off the ground.
   The budget devotes $1.3 billion to research into preventing and
treating acquired immune deficiency syndrome, a 38 percent boost.
   Another new element in the Reagan budget is its treatment of
education. Last year the president proposed a $5 billion cut. This
year he calls for a $1.5 billion increase to $20.3 billion.
   And, the president proposes a new program to help low- and
middle-income parents save for their children's education.
Purchasers of U.S. savings bonds wouldn't have to pay taxes on the
interest if they're cashed to pay for college tuition.
   On the revenue side of the budget, Reagan reprises many of his
``privatization'' proposals of the past: sale of government loans;
sale of Amtrak, the government-owned passenger rail service; and
sale of military housing. One new proposal is a private plan to
mediate disputes that now choke the U.S. Tax Court.
   Among other highlights of the budget, released Thursday, were:
   _$3.9 billion, a 13 percent boost, for drug law enforcement and
treatment.
   _$2.5 billion over five years to fight acid rain.
   _$1.6 billion, a 44 percent increase, to improve the air traffic
control system.
   _Nearly $1 billion for the new Worker Readjustment Program
(WRAP).
   WRAP will provide counseling, job search assistance, education
and training aimed at helping displaced workers move into new
careers. It replaces two other federal programs: one which provides
unemployment benefits after unemployment insurance runs out and a
second that pays states to help dislocated workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
