<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Owens-Illinois     02-19 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Owens-Illinois,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Refuses to Block Owens-Illinois Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has until the end of
today to appeal a court decision that paves the way for a merger
between two of the nation's largest manufacturers of glass
containers.
   On Thursday, U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green rejected the
Federal Trade Commission's request for a preliminary injunction to
block the merger between Toledo, Ohio-based Owens-Illinois Inc. and
Brockway Inc. of Jacksonville, Fla., ruling that the FTC had not
proven the deal would hurt competition.
   The FTC had sought to stop the merger while it conducts
administrative proceedings on its complaint that the combination of
the nation's second- and third-largest glass-container makers
threatened to violate antitrust laws by reducing competition.
   But the judge rejected the agency's claims, saying: ``The FTC
has not shown the possibility of harm to competition that would
occur between the denial of the preliminary injunction and final
adjudication.''
   Green accepted the argument advanced by the two manufacturers
that competition from the plastics and metal-packaging industry
will keep down prices.
   ``The trend in packaging is definitely toward a greater variety
of container alternatives rather than fewer,'' the judge said.
``Counterbalancing the potential for direct impact on glass prices
through price discrimination, the other relevant effect on price
and supply would be efficiencies to be gained from the merger.''
   Last month, the judge concluded four days of hearings on the
FTC's motion to block the merger. She had issued a temporary
restraining order stopping the deal, but it expires today.
   Last September, Owens-Illinois proposed to buy Brockway for $750
million, or $60 per share.
   The merger would make the combined company the largest
manufacturer in the industry. The nation's top manufacturer is
Anchor Glass Container Corp., which controls 23.7 percent of the
market.
   Owens-Illinois has a 22.7 percent share of the market, while
Brockway controls 15 percent of sales.
   The FTC has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws
by substantially reducing competition in the glass container
industry and creating conditions for price discrimination.
   But attorneys for Owens-Illinois said the purpose of the merger
is to achieve cost savings and efficiencies that will enable the
combined companies to vigorously compete against the producers of
plastics, metal and other types of packaging materials.
</TEXT>
