<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-Infiltration     02-19 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Infiltration,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Demand Public Explanation of FBI Domestic Spy Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI officials will report publicly to senators
next week on the conduct of agents who spied on and infiltrated an
organization opposed to President Reagan's policies in Central
America.
   The Senate Intelligence Committee asked for an internal probe
after publicly released documents showed the bureau conducted a
broad investigation of the Committee In Solidarity with the People
of El Salvador.
   The group, known as CISPES, contends that the FBI's motives were
political and that it was targeted because it opposes Reagan's
policies. CISPES pointed out the March 1983-June 1985 investigation
was closed down without any charges filed.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions was asked by the committee in
closed session Feb. 2 to conduct an internal probe of the bureau
operation. Although top FBI officials will present their interim
findings Tuesday, Sessions will not appear until a later session,
the committee said.
   Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla. and Vice Chairman
William Cohen, R-Maine, said in a joint statement that ``while we
will not draw any conclusions prematurely,'' they viewed
``violations of the civil rights of individual Americans as an
extremely serious matter.''
   The hearing also will focus on the FBI's justification for
conducting the investigation under broad guidelines that are
supposed to be used when acts of international terrorism are
carried out or planned.
   Use of those guidelines gave the FBI more leeway to investigate
CISPES; the bureau has other guidelines for conducting domestic
investigations which would have placed far more restrictions on
agents' activities.
   The FBI has said it conducted a legitimate investigation into
allegations that certain leaders and key members of CISPES were
covertly giving money and materials to a foreign terrorist
organization. The FBI identified the group as the FMLN, which is
fighting the U.S.-backed government of El Salvador.
   Thursday, the FBI gave the committee more than 3,000 pages of
still-classified documents on the investigation.
   Another 2,000 documents have been released under the Freedom of
Information Act, and they show the FBI was concerned that some of
its field offices were investigating protected political acts.
   Representing the FBI Tuesday will be Executive Assistant
Director Oliver B. Revell; Bill Gavin, assistant director in charge
of the inspection division; Bob Ricks, deputy assistant director,
criminal investigation division; and Steve Pomerantz, chief of the
terrorism section of the criminal investigative division.
</TEXT>
