<DOCNO> AP880219-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NationalParks     02-19 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-National Parks,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Says Stop Political Interference in Parks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The effectiveness of the National Park Service
is threatened by political interference, a problem that is getting
worse and can only be solved by making the agency independent,
according to the nation's principal park advocacy organization.
   ``The popularity of the national parks inspires political
appointees to curb the National Park Service's independence and
limit its clout,'' said the National Parks and Conservation
Association in a set of recommendations released Thursday.
   ``There is an urgent need to make the National Park Service an
independent agency, responsible directly to the Congress and the
president'' because of ``increasing politicization,'' the
association said.
   The recommendations ranged over a wide field, calling for, among
other things, establishment of 75 new park units in the 340-unit
system and expansion of 200 existing units.
   The report also urged the service to end the physical and
administrative isolation of researchers; to install a systematic,
understandable recruitment and hiring procedure; and to provide the
chance for employees to move back and forth between general
positions like ranger and specialist jobs like historian.
   Conservationists have continually criticized the three interior
secretaries of the Reagan administration for their tight control
over the service and their reluctance to seek funds for land
acquisition. But Paul Pritchard, president of the association, said
at the news conference introducing the report: ``It's not just this
administration. The process doesn't work.''
   Defenders of the present system say the Cabinet-rank interior
secretary carries clout for the service in the White House. The
association says it doesn't work that way:
   ``More often, the service has taken its concern to the public
and the Congress, either publicly or privately, to overcome
obstacles placed before it by political appointees of the
department.''
   If independent, ``the service would still have to compete
against all other federal agencies for funding, (but) it would be
able to compete without the filters and constraints of interior
secretaries, who historically have reduced National Park Service
funding requests to fit their own priorities.''
   The service was founded in 1916 in the Interior Department to
take care of the parks, the first of which was established in 1872.
The service now has 340 national parks, monuments, battlefields,
recreation areas, seashores and other units.
   Many were added in the 1960s and 1970s by a Congress delighted
to discover a new political currency that won favor with
constituents. Only four units have been added under the Reagan
administration.
   All directors have been professional park managers with one
exception: Ron Walker, a former campaign aide for President Nixon.
The current director, William Penn Mott, began his career with the
service in the 1930s and served as state parks director in
California under then-Gov. Ronald Reagan before being appointed to
his current job by Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel.
   ``I don't think he's free to advocate,'' said Rep. Bruce Vento,
D-Minn., chairman of the parks subcommittee of the House Interior
Committee, at the news conference.
   Vento said he was introducing a bill to transfer all the
secretary's legal responsibilities for the parks to the director
and to make the directorship a five-year presidential appointment.
The director would have to be a professional parks manager
confirmed by the Senate and subject to removal only for cause. The
bill also would establish a three-member board to advise Congress
on the parks.
   Complaints about political direction are common in the
government, but until recently have been rare in the park service.
Interior secretaries have tended to keep the directors they
inherit, but there have been reports that some have not been above
making it clear they'd like to see an early retirement.
   Current employees say they are under tighter political rein than
ever.
   Vento's bill would not actually take the service out of the
Interior Department, but he said it would accomplish the objectives
the association seeks and ``be more acceptable by my colleagues.''
   He said the association report ``sets forth a damning case
against the politicization of one of the finest professional
organizations in government.''
   Mott, said spokesman George Berklacy, ``does not support the
removal of the service from interior. He does not believe there is
anything advantageous to that. He feels very strongly that the
director of the National Park Service should be a professional park
manager. A five-year presidential appointment is OK with him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
