<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-NoHints     02-19 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-No Hints,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Issues Wordy Marching Orders on Budget Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department issued some wordy
marching orders this week for reporters preparing stories on its
$299.5 billion budget request for next year.
   The aim was to prevent publication of budget details until noon
Thursday.
   In official Washington, copies of complicated documents are
routinely made available to journalists in advance of publication
to give them time to absorb the complexities and write informed
stories.
   The agency that issues the document sets the day and hour when
the information can be released. In journalistic parlance, that's
called an embargo.
   But the Pentagon's budget embargo warning was more emphatic _
and a lot wordier _ than most.
   Its budget embargo was to be a ``total embargo,'' no ifs, ands
or buts.
   ``Until release, NONE of this material may be paraphrased,
hinted at or alluded to in any way,'' the Pentagon declared.
   ``This material must NOT be discussed with or provided to others
who have not accepted the package on an embargoed basis.''
   The Pentagon also laid out the rules under which it would
discuss the contents of the budget.
   ``In advance of release, no telephone inquiries on this material
will be accepted by Defense Department personnel,'' the department
said. ``Questions from news media correspondents must be asked in
person and the requester must acknowledge acceptance of this
embargo.''
   Just to make sure the message got across, the Pentagon directive
_ stamped top and bottom with the words _ HOLD FOR RELEASE _ added
the following:
   ``There is a total embargo on this budget, as stated above,
which includes any and all references to any material in the budget
or the budget appendix.''
</TEXT>
