<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChiliFracas     02-19 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chili Fracas,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chili War Winds Up in Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PECOS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rival groups that sponsor chili
cook-offs have removed a simmering dispute from the back burner and
taken it into the courtroom.
   The Chili Appreciation Society International Inc. has been
judging the fiery merits of this Southwestern specialty since 1967.
Five years ago, an unincorporated spinoff group took the same name
and started its own cookoff.
   Both groups hold an annual championship cookoff each November
near the west Texas ghost town of Terlingua.
   The older group has mounted a court challenge seeking to force
the newer one to change its name. U.S. District Judge Lucius Bunton
said he would decide within 20 days which group will get to keep
the Chili Appreciation Society International name.
   Frank X. Tolbert, now deceased, helped organize the first
cookoff in 1967 to publicize this ghost town.
   One of Tolbert's early partners, Ray King, testified Wednesday
that Tolbert agreed in 1980 to incorporate the group, but later
backed out because ``he didn't care much for rules and
organization. He liked it like it started out.''
   King and others incorporated the group, and Tolbert accepted the
organization's honorary title of ``Supreme Pepper.''
   But in 1983, Tolbert broke from the society and started a rival
cookoff across the road from the original site at the vacant Chisos
Saloon.
   The older, larger group has since moved its cookoff eight miles
down the road to Villa de la Mina, where 2,500 participated last
year.
   Bunton likened the argument to the child-custody dispute King
Solomon resolved by ordering the baby cut in half.
   ``That's exactly what's happened to Terlingua,'' Bunton said.
``The baby is split. Terlingua doesn't need two cookoffs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
