<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-Farm     02-19 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Farm,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Chill Greets Reagan Farm Budget on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan administration plans to overhaul the
U.S. sugar support system and drastically cut rural housing and
telephone programs are headed for the same chilly reception that
Congress gave them in past years, farm-state Democrats say.
   ``They were dead on arrival and will remain dead on arrival,''
Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said after President Reagan submitted
his proposed fiscal 1989 farm budget on Thursday.
   Panetta, a member of the House Agriculture Committee,
characterized Reagan's spending plan as ``a no-news budget'' and
``a rehash of old proposals.''
   In any case, he said, legislators are in no mood to revamp farm
programs so soon after approving a full-scale overhaul in the 1985
farm law.
   Food programs, including food stamps and school lunches,
remained largely untouched under Reagan's proposed budget. There
were no changes in most farm commodity programs except for the
sugar program, which includes protective import quotas and price
supports.
   The Agriculture Department wants to reduce the sugar price
support from 18 cents a pound to 12 cents to make domestic sugar
more competitive with imports. It contends that high supports
artificially stimulate domestic production and forces the United
States to impose tighter quotas on imports.
   Most of the major decisions embodied in the proposed budget
resulted from a summit agreement between Congress and the White
House on $76 billion in deficit-reducing savings over two years.
   Accordingly, the administration proposed to cut overall farm
spending by 5 percent, but dropped previous proposals for new user
fees, changes in Forest Service payments to states, alterations in
food assistance programs and turning the federal crop insurance
program over to private enterprise.
   The 5 percent cut included a proposed reduction in Farmers Home
Administration rural housing programs from more than $3.3 billion
this year to less than $1.4 billion in fiscal 1989, which starts
Oct. 1.
   Also, 70 percent of Rural Electrification Administration loans
to rural telephone companies and cooperatives would be transformed
into guaranteed loans from private lenders at an estimated
government savings of $478 million.
   But Congress has tossed these same proposals in the wastebasket
in the past, and seems likely to do the same this year.
   ``This is not the leadership required to address the need for
economic recovery in the thousands of rural communities that have
been bypassed by the economic recovery,'' said Sen. Patrick J.
Leahy, D-Vt., the chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee.
   Said Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., a member of the House
Agriculture Committee: ``This is not a budget that attempts to deal
with real numbers. It is a philosophical budget, an attempt to use
the budget in obtaining the Reagan administration's philosophical
goals.''
   ``We recognize the need for budget discipline,'' said Rep. E
``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, chairman of the House panel. But he
said Congress ``would remind the administration and the public that
over recent years, agriculture has taken more than its fair share
of budget cuts.''
   According to the House Budget Committee, agriculture spending
after inflation increased 109.8 percent from fiscal 1981 until
fiscal 1987. The increase was caused largely by huge subsidy
programs under the 1985 law that were intended to spur exports and
revitalize the depressed farm economy.
   Net outlays for farm payments by the Agriculture Department's
Commodity Credit Corp. peaked in 1986 at $25.8 billion. They have
been falling since then to $17.7 billion currently, and are
projected at $17.1 billion next year.
   Reagan's budget proposed no new types of price-support payments,
although some lawmakers have begun to push for new subsidies for
soybeans and possibly other crops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0214EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pollard-OtherSpy     02-19 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pollard-Other Spy,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Investigators Believe Israel Had Second Spy in United
States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials have drawn up a list of
suspects in their search for a ``Mr. X'' inside the government who
they believe helped Israel direct convicted spy Jonathan Jay
Pollard to critical secret documents, The Washington Post reported
today.
   The Post reported that Justice Department officials believe
Israel almost certainly had another espionage agent spying against
the United States in addition to Pollard, who has been sentenced to
life in prison.
   However, no evidence has been developed yet that points to the
specific identity of this second person, who has been dubbed ``Mr.
X,'' the Post said, citing unidentified sources for its information.
   ``As we have indicated previously, there are unanswered
questions in the case and the investigation continues,'' Justice
Department spokesman Terry Eastland said.
   An Israeli Embassy spokesman, Yossi Gal, said the Pollard case
was an aberration and that the Israeli government has no more spies
in the United States.
   Pollard was a Navy intelligence analyst who was working at the
Navy's new Antiterrorism Alert Center during the 17 months when he
spied for Israel. He was sentenced in March 1987 to life
imprisonment after pleading guilty to selling secrets to Israel. He
was arrested in November 1985 outside the Israeli Embassy in
Washington and is imprisoned in Springfield, Mo.
   Pollard's wife, Anne Henderson-Pollard, was sentenced in March
1987 to five years imprisonment after she pleaded guilty to
conspiracy to receive embezzled government property and being an
accessory after the fact to possession of state secrets. She has
been moved to the Federal Medical Center in Rochester, Minn., where
she is suffering from a digestive tract disease.
   The Post, quoting unidentified sources, said the belief that a
Mr. X must exist grew out of a massive debriefing and polygraphing
of Pollard over many months.
   Pollard told authorities that his Israeli handlers often
specified by date and document control number the highly sensitive
U.S. documents they wanted him to acquire, the newspaper said.
   The handlers once showed him a top secret U.S. document to which
Pollard himself did not have access, the Post said, identifying the
document as an index or catalog that Pollard then could use to
obtain other documents from U.S. intelligence agencies.
   Investigators concluded that another American _ Mr. X _ had
provided that index and other specific information on U.S. secrets
that Pollard learned from his Israeli handlers, the newspaper said.
   Prosecutors have said Pollard sold Israel enough classified
documents to fill a large, walk-in closet and called the spy case
one of the nation's worst.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
