<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-MilitaryConstruction     02-19 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Military Construction,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Asks $9 Billion for Construction in U.S., Overseas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department wants to spend $9
billion on military construction projects in fiscal 1989, including
more than $1 billion for work outside the United States.
   Of the $9 billion, more than $200 million has already been
authorized, meaning that about $8.8 billion in new funds is being
sought.
   Within the United States, the biggest winners would be
California, New York, Texas, Alaska and Washington state, primarily
because of work on new bases or seaports.
   Abroad, the Pentagon plans to spend the most in West Germany,
South Korea, the Philippines, England and Italy, in that order.
   The $81.4 million request for construction work in the
Philippines comes at a time of instability in that country and
uncertainty over whether the government of President Corazon Aquino
will approve extension of leases for the Subic Naval Base and Clark
Air Base beyond 1991.
   The Pentagon has said it expects to negotiate new leases for the
bases and will continue improving them in the meantime.
   Also contained in President Reagan's fiscal 1989 budget request,
sent to Congress on Thursday, is $3 million to ``upgrade
facilities'' in Honduras, where U.S. forces regularly engage in
maneuvers as part of a U.S. campaign to deter Nicaraguan expansion.
   The budget plan also includes $9.9 million to improve air fields
in Oman near the Persian Gulf and $16 million for a missile range
complex in the Kwajalein Islands in the Pacific Ocean for
experiments on Reagan's Star Wars missile defense system.
   The funds for more than 1,100 construction projects at more than
600 sites were contained in Reagan's request for $299.5 billion in
Pentagon spending authority for the budget year starting Oct. 1,
compared with $291.4 billion this year.
   The administration initially had planned to spend more than
$10.6 billion for construction next year, but was forced to trim
back because of a deficit-reduction agreement with Congress last
November.
   Of the $9 billion construction total, the Pentagon said it would
spend nearly $5.8 billion on military facilities and nearly $3.3
billion on housing. By contrast, the department plans to spend $8.7
billion this year, including $5.5 billion on new facilities and
$3.2 billion on housing.
   Nearly $600 million would be spent next year to build 3,226 new
housing units and improve 16,900 existing units. The remaining $2.7
billion would be for operating and maintaining the 413,000 existing
family units, the Pentagon said.
   The military facility projects include work to support the B-1
bomber, the MX missile, the ``Stealth'' bomber and new ports for
ships joining the Navy's fleet.
   Among the larger individual projects are $56.3 million for a new
naval submarine base at Kings Bay, Ga.; $214 million in previouly
authorized money for the new home of a light infantry division at
Fort Drum, N.Y.; $72.5 million for a major Star Wars test facility
at Falcon Air Station, Colo., and $53 million for a new aircraft
carrier base at Everett, Wash.
   Including family housing funds and previously authorized
projects, the Pentagon said it planned to spend $666 million in
California, $309.5 million in New York, $217.6 million in Texas,
$202.2 million in Alaska and $201.2 million in Washington state.
   Besides the Philippines, foreign spending would include $421.1
million in West Germany, $133.6 million in South Korea, $77.7
million in England and $50.4 million in Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
