<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Babbitt-Style     02-19 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Babbitt-Style,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Babbitt Maintains Grace, Wit, in Bowing Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Babbitt closed the doors on his
presidential race in the same way that he campaigned _ with grace
and humor, and a pledge to continue to keep fighting for his vision
of America.
   The former Arizona governor stood before a roomful of
supporters, TV lights and reporters on Thursday to announce what
had become apparent since his dismal sixth-place showing in New
Hampshire on Tuesday: that he was ending the marathon he had
officially started on March 10.
   But there was hopeful news for the Babbitt faithful _ their
champion said he wasn't bowing out of the political arena
completely.
   Indeed, staffers at his New Hampshire campaign office were
answering the phone on Thursday with the words, ``Babbitt in '92.''
   Babbitt said he's making no plans for 1992, and hopes to be
supporting an incumbent Democratic president. Nonetheless, he
stated:
   ``I want to be a positive part of this process. I'm not leaving
_ it's too much fun, and I am too much an optimist, and too much an
American who believes in the process to walk away from it or to say
anything negative about the candidates.''
   With an endorsement of the campaign process, if not of any rival
candidate, Babbitt said he intends to continue speaking out and
``chiding'' the other candidates because ``there's room for
improvement'' in the field.
   Babbitt's departure was relaxed, upbeat and laughter-filled,
with no trace of bitterness that his long quest had ended so early
in the 1988 primary season.
   The tall, lanky 49-year-old, flanked by his wife Hattie and two
young sons, cracked jokes, often as not poking fun at himself and
the campaign that never caught fire. It was a Babbitt typical of
the man reporters covering him had grown to expect.
   Babbitt seemed to have general affection for the press corps,
which had bolstered his cash-poor campaign with a spate of positive
articles highlighting his frankness, his willingness to take
unpopular stands such as his call for a national sales tax, and his
quotable and colorful remarks.
   At one point, the favorable publicity before the Iowa caucuses ,
which never quite coincided with Babbitt's low poll standings, came
to be known as the ``Babbitt boomlet.''
   On Thursday, Babbitt kiddingly accused the media of a conspiracy
to discredit him with the public by ``making me into kind of a
house pet.''
   As he left the podium, Babbitt closed his news conference by
saying, ``Thank you very much, it's been an honor and a privilege.''
   Campaign manager Fred DuVal said one supporter remarked to him
afterward, ``That wasn't a press conference. That was an encounter
group.''
   In contrast to the rancorous withdrawals by past candidates who
blamed press scrutiny for their troubles, DuVal said that one line
that had been suggested to Babbitt to use as he exited the race
was, ``After this you won't have Bruce Babbitt to puff any more.''
   The line was a parody of Richard Nixon's 1962 remark that he was
leaving politics and the press wouldn't have him to ``kick around''
any more.
   Babbitt seemed genuinely reluctant to leave the final press
conference of his campaign, modestly stating that he had
monopolized a half hour of reporters' time but would take a couple
more questions, and then, ``I'll stay around for a while. ... As
vicious and unprincipled as you've been, I hate to let loose,'' he
joked.
   Later at a farewell luncheon for his staff, the mood was teary
and affectionate as loyalists recounted what the campaign had meant
to them.
   ``There's been tears ... equal doses of disappointment and
affection,'' said DuVal. ``Everybody feels as if they've just
tasted an extraordinary experience.''
   Even on the night of the New Hampshire debacle, Babbitt and his
supporters partied as if they were at a victory celebration, the
candidate and his wife dancing the twist until 1:30 a.m.
   They cheered every percentage point as a victory of sorts _ this
collection of salesmen, students, writers, politicians and lawyers
turned envelope stuffers, telephone operators and chauffeurs. And
they left convinced they had done the right thing.
   Babbitt compared traveling the debate circuit with his
Democratic rivals to going to summer camp ``when all of a sudden
you're living in the same cabin with a bunch of guys that you never
knew before.''
   But he said he would be happy to back any one of the Democrats
who gets the nomination.
   One of them, Sen. Paul Simon, on Thursday, said, ``Seeing Bruce
leave the campaign trail is like seeing an Army buddy ship out to
go home. He has contributed much to this campaign.''
</TEXT>
