<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AFL-CIO-UPI     02-19 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AFL-CIO-UPI,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Accuses UPI Of Attempting Union-Busting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO has accused United Press
International of attempting to ``bust'' the union representing the
news service's writers, editors and photographers.
   The labor federation, in a statement issued by its executive
council on Thursday, condemned UPI's ``callous treatment of its
employees'' in declaring an impasse last October in negotiations on
a new contract and unilaterally imposing ``harsh new work rules.''
   ``Members of The Newspaper Guild ... are fighting to save their
union and their jobs from efforts by UPI's owner to bust the union
and shut down many of the news service's operations,'' the
36-member council of union presidents said.
   AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Thomas R. Donahue called the dispute
between the Guild's Wire Service Local 222 and UPI ``the latest
struggle in a decade of employee sacrifice to keep the financially
troubled news service afloat.''
   The labor federation said UPI employees have agreed to major
concessions including pay, pension and benefit cuts since 1978, and
stayed on the job despite bounced paychecks when the company sought
bankruptcy protection in 1985.
   Newspaper Guild President Charles Dale said the company's last
contract proposal would ``eliminate job security and allow UPI to
subcontract all bargaining unit work to itself for the sole purpose
of cutting wages again and the destruction of the union.''
   Dale said UPI has fired 112 employees and put no money into its
employee pension plan since Nov. 12.
   Chris Smith, a UPI spokesman at its headquarters in Washington,
said the company's last offer and imposed work rules include a 16
percent pay raise over the next two years for top-scale editorial
workers.
   Smith said 181 employees have left the company's payroll since
Oct. 1 but that 70 of them have been replaced.
   UPI has ``never made an expression to use its subcontracting
power to replace existing full-time news staff,'' Smith said. ``It
hasn't happened and we don't anticipate it happening.''
</TEXT>
