<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru f0312 02-19 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0312,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures. PICKS up
4th graf pvs bgng, ``There's absolutely ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
in Tokyo Friday, while stock prices rallied for the seventh
consecutive trading day.
   The dollar closed at 130.53 yen, up 0.53 yen from Thursday's
close of 130.00 yen. It had opened at 130.33 yen and traded in a
narrow range of 130.30-130.55 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 245.41-point winner Thursday, added another
98.05 points to close the week's trading at 24,773.41.
   ``There's absolutely nothing to move the market, no
market-motivating news, and the dollar is dead,'' said a trader
with a major commercial bank.
   The dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said currency
trading was also dampened by a holiday in Hong Kong and the slow
start-up of trading in Singapore after a holiday.
   Japanese housing and retail shares posted gains along with
high-technology issues and those of importers.
   ``These sectors are moving the market as the country seems
determined to address the trade imbalance problem and expand
domestic demand,'' said Yoshio Ogawa of Nikko Securities.
</TEXT>
