<2ND_LINE>AM-Four Dead, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0445,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Found Slain In House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to make it `ax,' sted `hatchet,' UPDATES
throughout with teen-ager turning up at school with head shaved,
telling friends he was having trouble with parents, family van
found and car stolen. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple and two of their children were
slain in their nightclothes with a hatchet Thursday, and the
couple's 16-year-old son was being sought for questioning,
authorities said.
   The bodies of Bernard Brom, his wife, Paullette, and children
Diane, 14, and Rick, 9 were found Thursday night at their home in
suburban Cascade Township, said Olmsted County Sheriff Charles Von
Wald.
   A bloody ax 2 to 3 feet long was found in the basement, Von Wald
said.
   The sheriff said a nationwide bulletin was issued for the Broms'
16-year-old son and the family van. The boy was at Lourdes High
School on Thursday morning but did not attend classes, the sheriff
said.
   Friends at the school said the boy had dyed his hair black,
shaved the sides of his head and spiked the hair in back, Von Wald
said. The youth also bought a wig and makeup.
   ``He indicated he was having some trouble with his parents,''
Von Wald said. ``One student said he was having trouble with his
dad because of a tape he had bought and he didn't want him
listening to it.
   Bernard and Rick Brom's bodies were found in their upstairs
bedrooms, and Paullette and Diane Brom's bodies were in an upstairs
hallway, the sheriff said. He said they were slain early in the
morning.
   The house is among four on a road in a quiet, well-to-do area of
Cascade Township.
   Von Wald said the sheriff's department received a call at about
5:30 p.m. from an unidentified school official about a possible
problem at the house.
   The family van had been missing but was found late Thursday, Von
Wald said. A car and another car's license plates were reported
stolen from the vicinity of the high school.
</TEXT>
