<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaGOP     02-19 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada GOP,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Backers Said To Cast Undecided Votes In Takeover
Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush won a
presidential straw poll of Nevada Republicans, but his tally was
nearly equaled by undecided votes _ many of which were believed to
have been cast by supporters of Pat Robertson in a bid to control
later balloting.
   With only a tiny fraction of returns still unreported from
caucuses around the state Thursday night, Bush had 1,341 votes in
the non-binding straw poll, and undecided votes totaled 1,146.
   Steve Wark, Robertson coordinator in Nevada, said many Robertson
voters cast undecided ballots as part of a strategy to win in later
voting for delegates to the upcoming county conventions.
   ``They did that to protect their (convention) delegates,'' said
state GOP Chairwoman Sally Vitkus-McKinney. ``That's politics.''
   ``We knew that the Dole and Bush people would get together to
try and squash us if we came out strong in the straw poll,'' Wark
said. Even so, Robertson, a former television evangelist, had 733
votes outright.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 1,130 votes, officially finishing ahead
of Robertson but lagging behind the undecided tally. Rep. Jack Kemp
had 644 votes.
   Former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont, who dropped out of the GOP
race on Thursday, got 39 votes and former Secretary of State
Alexander Haig, who called it quits last week, got six votes.
   The caucuses were open only to registered Nevada Republicans,
and the straw poll was conducted by secret ballot.
   The caucuses drew several thousand of the more than 120,000
Republicans registered to vote in Nevada. The registration total
has gone up several thousand since Jan. 1, but exact numbers
weren't available.
   Ms. Vitkus-McKinney said the increase was due both to state GOP
registration efforts and to separate efforts by the Robertson camp.
   Whether the Robertson strategy in the straw poll worked remains
to be seen. The makeup of the delegations to the county conventions
won't be known for several more days and even then delegates won't
have to publicly declare their presidential preferences.
   The straw poll was developed last summer, before former Nevada
Sen. Paul Laxalt announced in September that he wouldn't seek the
GOP presidential nomination. He would have been the probable Nevada
poll winner had he stayed in the running, Ms. Vitkus-McKinney said.
</TEXT>
