<HEAD>Viewers Complain After Game Show Interrupted For Crash Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television station that pre-empted two
minutes of ``Jeopardy'' to report on a plane crash later broadcast
the missing game-show footage during its news programs after
viewers complained, station officials said.
   ``Viewers missed less than two minutes of `Jeopardy.' But those
were the final minutes, and so we replayed them,'' said WXFL-TV
general manager Jim Saunders.
   Two people were killed Tuesday when a twin-engine plane slammed
into a house in Dunedin.
   On Wednesday, WXFL broadcast the end of ``Jeopardy'' twice, once
during the station's noon and 6 p.m. news shows.
   Saunders said he did not know how many complaint calls were
received Tuesday, but a source at the station told the Tampa
Tribune the number was ``well over 300.''
