<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--CholesterolSurvey     02-19 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cholesterol Survey,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Americans Know Their Cholesterol Levels, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans don't know the recommended blood
cholesterol levels, but do have a general knowledge of what
cholesterol is, according to a Louis Harris poll sponsored by the
maker of a cholesterol-lowering drug.
   Seventy-nine percent of those asked didn't know the recommended
cholesterol levels, according to the survey sponsored by Bristol
Laboratories, makers of the cholesterol-lowering drug Questran.
   However, most had general knowledge of cholesterol, the survey
showed. Eighty-three percent identified it as a fatty substance,
and 96 percent said they knew that eating fatty foods can elevate
cholesterol levels.
   Cholesterol has been linked to heart disease.
   The survey was based on telephone interviews with 1,438
Americans over age 18 conducted between Dec. 22, 1987 and Jan. 14,
1988.
</TEXT>
