<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-19 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally, Dollar Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rallied for the seventh consecutive
day in active trading in Tokyo today, while the U.S. dollar climbed
slightly.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected shares, a 245.41-point winner Thursday, added another
98.05 points or 0.4 percent and closed the week's trading at
24,773.41.
   ``Share prices rose almost across the board. We expect the stock
average to top the 25,000-level pretty soon,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama
of Wako Securities.
   He said institutional investors were especially active in areas
such as steel and shipbuilding. Volume of the first-section trade
reached the 1 billion-share mark for the first time in six weeks,
up from 750 million shares Thursday.
   Electrical issues scored strong gains, while automobiles and
steel also rose.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed the
week's trading at 130.53 yen, up 0.53 yen from Thursday's close of
130.00. It had opened at 130.33 yen and traded in a narrow range of
130.30-130.55 yen.
   Ken Iio of the Bank of Tokyo said trading was quiet ahead of the
weekend with no major news affecting dealing today.
   The influential Hong Kong and Singapore markets, which were
closed part of this week due to the Chinese New Year's holiday,
also made the dealing sluggish, he said. The volume of trade was a
moderate $2.296 billion.
</TEXT>
