<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Budget-At-A-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0482hefollowinggraphicsareavailamatteratendofa0482.
02-19 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Budget-At-A-Glance, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0394</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES extraneous matter at end of a0482.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is an overview of the
proposed budget for fiscal year 1989 that President Reagan
submitted to Congress:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OVERALL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Spending is projected at $1.09 trillion, up from $1.05 trillion
in 1988.
   _Receipts are estimated at $964.7 billion, $55.5 billion more
than in 1988. Income taxes provide 55 percent of receipts, followed
by 36.8 percent from social insurance taxes.
   _The budget would reduce the federal deficit from an estimated
$146.7 billion in 1988 to $129.5 billion in the fiscal year that
begins next Oct. 1. That's below the target of $136 billion called
for in the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>INCREASES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Military spending would be $294 billion, up from $285.4 billion
in 1988, but the smallest military spending increase Reagan has
ever sent to Congress. The 3 percent increase is less than needed
to keep pace with inflation, projected at 4.3 percent this year.
   _The plan calls for nearly $2 billion in spending authority to
combat Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome, a 38 percent increase
over 1988 levels.
   _Education spending would rise 8 percent, or $1.5 billion. The
biggest gain would be in the Pell grant program for needy college
students.
   _About $10.9 billion is included for space programs, with almost
$1 billion of that going to the start of construction of a manned
space station and another $1 billion for the space shuttle.
   _About $363 million for the start of construction of the
superconducting super collider, a machine designed to study the
nature of matter.
   _About $1.6 billion is earmarked for upgrading the nation's air
traffic control system.
   _Included is a request for $437 million, more than double last
year's budget, for federal prison construction to relieve
overcrowding.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SAVINGS OR CUTS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _The plan renews a number of previous administration proposals
for reducing government programs, including abolition of the
Interstate Commerce Commission, the Economic Development
Administration, Small Business Administration direct loans, urban
development action grants and public subsidies for Amtrak rail
passenger service and mass transit systems.
   _The budget suggsts ``possible privatization'' of some Postal
Service operations and the government's uranium enrichment
facilities.
   _Dropped were some of the more politically controversial
proposals of past Reagan budgets, including abolition of the Legal
Services Corp.
</TEXT>
