<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Society,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Society Breaks Ground For New Atlanta Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Cancer Society has broken ground for
a new headquarters next to Emory University and across the street
from the headquarters of the federal Centers for Disease Control.
   ``I'm hopeful that this headquarters will be successful,'' Gov.
Joe Frank Harris said at groundbreaking ceremonies Thursday.
   Harris said he would like to see the new building ``phased out
of existence (someday) ... because a total cure for cancer has been
found and announced here.''
   The Cancer Society has had its headquarters in New York City the
last 75 years. It hopes to move next January to the $12 million,
six-floor building. The society estimated that 125 or more of its
300-person staff will make the move south.
   ``We are now moving at top speed into the future, toward
advancements that would have seemed like science-fiction fantasies
a few years ago,'' said Dr. Harmon J. Eyre, a Salt Lake City
oncologist and president of the Cancer Society. ``Amazing and
wonderful things will happen at this place.''
   The Cancer Society, the world's largest volunteer health agency,
said it wanted to escape high operating costs in New York.
   Emory sold the four-acre site to the society for $1 million. The
college had purchased the tract, worth $2.5 million, with
assistance from a foundation, and wanted to add the society's
headquarters to a growing cluster of health and science centers
near its campus.
</TEXT>
