<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KidnappedMarine     02-19 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnapped Marine,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Offers Support To Family Of Abducted Marine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan called to console the
family of Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, stung by the double
blow of Higgins' abduction in Lebanon and the death of his father a
day later.
   ``The President telephoned the colonel's wife this afternoon and
offered all the support he knew how to give her ... I think it
helped her tremendously,'' Harold Fisher, Higgins' brother-in-law,
said Thursday.
   Fisher, noting that eight other Americans are being held in
Lebanon, said, ``one of the hardest parts is seeing how they are
held captive, with no resolution in sight. Being the ninth, you
just don't know.''
   The family learned of Higgins' kidnapping by Islamic
revolutionaries Wednesday when they telephoned his wife, Marine
Maj. Robin Higgins, who works in the Pentagon's public affairs
office, with news of the elder Higgins' imminent death.
   William F. Higgins, 72, died from cardiopulmonary arrest and
kidney failure Thursday morning without knowing of his son's
ordeal. The last time father and son saw each other was in
September 1987, when Higgins came home on emergency leave from the
Middle East.
   ``He never knew that his son had been taken captive. It was a
blessing that he didn't know,'' Fisher told a news conference.
Fisher is married to Higgins' sister, Mary, who did not attend the
news conference.
   Fisher said the family was doing well, considering the ordeal.
   ``It's difficult to accept the death of a father and then at the
same time something that's so unknown as what's really taking
place'' with the lieutenant colonel.
   Fisher said the family was happy that Higgins had chosen to
serve his country as a United Nations observer. ``We have
confidence that our government will do what is best and necessary
for our country and for his safety,'' he said.
   Higgins, 43, was abducted as he returned from a meeting in Tyre
with officials of Lebanese Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Shiite
Amal militia to discuss efforts to free foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   ``It could be two days, two years or never. It's a sad
situation,'' Fisher said of prospects for Higgins' release.
   He said, however, that Higgins ``will handle the situation
better than most people because of the training he has had. He is a
very strong individual.''
   Fisher said the military had also been in touch with the family
and ``given us some telephone numbers to call for information. We
are comfortable with the arrangements they have provided.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
