<DOCNO> AP880219-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0506EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     02-19 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Cabinet Has Holdovers, Hardliners in Key Posts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Roh Tae-woo unveiled a
new Cabinet today in which several key posts went to hardliners and
holdovers from the old government. Widespread hopes for major
changes were unfulfilled.
   Roh, who takes office Feb. 25, has pledged to end South Korea's
long tradition of authoritarian rule and restore full democracy.
   But Cabinet security posts went to hardliners. Technocrats,
civil servants and academics took most other posts.
   The naming of the 23-member Cabinet was closely watched for
evidence Roh would follow through on promises for sweeping reforms.
Many of the new ministers are politically unknown.
   Political observers said the new Cabinet was little different
from the one it will replace and does not appear to contain
independents or reformers.
   Roh stressed the need for stability in making the appointments,
saying the government had to ensure political and economic calm. He
also underlined the need to guarantee the success of the 1988
Olympic Games, which are scheduled for September in Seoul.
   ``I call on you new ministers to make maximum efforts to turn
the nation into an advanced country by enhancing the people's
capability and integrating national strength,'' Roh told them.
   Opposition parties charged that Roh is determined to continue
the authoritarian rule of outgoing President Chun Doo-hwan.
   ``Despite much talk, the new Cabinet falls far short of
expectations,'' said an opposition statement.
   However, the main opposition Reunification Democratic Party and
the Party for Peace and Democracy had rejected Roh's invitation to
nominate candidates for the Cabinet, saying they doubted Roh's
ability to bring about reform.
   Roh retained seven ministers from the Chun government, including
those holding the key posts of foreign affairs, home affairs and
justice.
   Home Minister Lee Sang-hee heads the police and Justice Minister
Chung Hae-chang supervised recent crackdowns on political
dissidents. The foreign minister is Choi Kwang-soo.
   New Defense Minister Oh Ja-Bok, a recently retired general and
armed forces commander, is a hardliner who has attacked opposition
parties in the past.
   Oh is expected to be Roh's link to the powerful military, which
has long dominated the country. He supported Chun and Roh and other
young generals who took power in 1980 with military backing.
   Ahn Moo-hyuk was retained as head of South Korea's powerful
intelligence agency, the Agency for National Security Planning. The
director works with the Cabinet, but is not a member.
   Roh had pledged to increase substantially the power of the
Cabinet as part of his promises to usher in full democracy.
Traditionally, ministers have had little power, with most decisions
being made by the presidency.
   The appointment Feb. 11 of noted moderate Lee Hyun-jae as prime
minister had spurred hope the new Cabinet would include people with
new outlooks.
   Roh said the new government would seek to end the political,
regional and social divisions that have long troubled South Korea.
   ``The new government should stand in the vanguard to create
conditions under which the entire people would be willing to
participate,'' he said.
   Roh won the presidential elections on Dec. 16 with 36.7 percent
of the vote. Chun had agreed to elections after huge protests for
democractic government last summer.
   Roh, saying he is determined to maintain the country's rapid
economic growth and massive exports drive, held over some key
economic experts, including Finance Minister Sakong Il.
   Outgoing Trade Minister Rha Woong-bae was promoted to the joint
post of deputy prime minister and economic planning minister.
   Business and trade groups applauded the makeup of the Cabinet,
saying it would help to bolster economic growth while stabilizing
prices and other economic factors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
