<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Drugs     02-19 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Drugs,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Asks U.S. To Turn Over Names of Sources Of Drug
Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government asked the U.S.
ambassador for the names of U.S. officials who were the sources for
a newspaper report alleging links between the Honduran military and
Colombian drug traffickers.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said in a statement
Thursday that the government also wants the names of members of the
Honduran military who were accused of involvement in the narcotics
trade and details of the illegal acts they purportedly committed.
   ``Notwithstanding the seriousness of the charges formulated
(against Honduras), for the moment what most displeases and
disturbs my government is that these are attributed to (high-level
U.S. officials),'' Lopez Contreras said.
   He said that if the names were not forthcoming, ``then we await
the satisfactions (consequences) that the case warrants.'' He did
not elaborate.
   ``This is not the appropriate moment to get into analyzing the
truthfulness or falseness of the charges provided by anonymous but
identifiable sources,'' the statement said.
   A story in The New York Times last week quoted unidentified U.S.
and Honduran officials as saying Honduras was in danger of being
overrun by Colombian drug dealers.
   The newspaper reported the sources as saying narcotics
traffickers had corrupted Honduran army officers, offered money to
political parties and bought businesses and land to launder drug
profits.
   The Honduran military denied the charges and demanded that the
government of President Jose Azcona Hoyo file lawsuits against
newspapers that report such accounts.
   Both Azcona Hoyo and U.S. Ambassador Everett Briggs held news
conferences on Tuesday at which they called the reports untrue.
   Briggs said the stories were ``very imaginative and inventive.''
   ``I am the principal and highest official of the United States
in Honduras and I totally disavow this situation that has appeared
in the newspapers of my country,'' Briggs said.
</TEXT>
