<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Toy-GunShooting     02-19 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toy-Gun Shooting,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Shoot 13-Year-Old Retarded Boy Who Aimed Toy Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every day, neighbors say, a retarded
13-year-old boy would go behind his house and play with a toy gun.
   Silvielo Grohse's youthful game turned into tragedy when two
officers mistook his plaything for the real thing and fatally shot
him.
   ``He was such a sweet boy,'' said Steve Diamond, the
seventh-grader's teacher. ``He loved to be hugged. He would come up
and put his head on your shoulder and just hug you.''
   The youngster was shot Wednesday by the officers after they
ordered him to drop the weapon and he instead spun around toward
them, police said Thursday.
   ``The boy is retarded, and he played back here every day because
it's not safe in front of the projects,'' said neighbor Debra
Judkins. ``The cops should know better than to gun down a child.''
   Grohse was dead on arrival at San Francisco General Hospital,
said Dr. Richard Cales. The boy stood 5-foot-8 and weighed about
190 pounds.
   Police spokesman Jerry Senkir said there was no evidence the
officers, Michael Huddleston and Janet Campbell, acted improperly.
He said Grohse's toy gun resembled a .22-caliber revolver.
   According to Senkir, the officers were answering a call of shots
being fired in the drug-plagued area when they spotted the youth
walking with the toy gun in his hand. They pulled within 40 feet of
him, got out of their patrol car and crouched behind open doors
with guns drawn, ordering the youth to drop his gun.
   ``The suspect then turned and pointed the gun at the officers,''
Senkir said. ``At the same time, he crouched down and let out a
yell. Both officers immediately opened fire.''
   The officers fired four shots from their .357-caliber Magnum
service revolvers, he said.
   ``Weren't they supposed to give him a warning or something, like
`freeze?''' asked Grohse's 12-year-old cousin. ``Couldn't they have
shot in the air first instead of killing him?''
   Police union officials have called for community meetings
between residents and police to defuse the tension surrounding the
shooting.
</TEXT>
