<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-19 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against major foreign
currencies in Europe early today in lackluster trading. Gold prices
fell.
   The dollar was underpinned by recent signs of U.S. economic
expansion, said a trader in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Although the dollar shed some early gains, it was holding fairly
steady in the absence of market-moving news, traders said.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe compared with rates late
Thursday:
   _1.7080 West German marks, up from 1.7040
   _1.4035 Swiss francs, up from 1.4010
   _5.7735 French francs, up from 5.7555
   _1.9236 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9130
   _1,257.15 Italian lire, up from 1,254.63
   _1.2715 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2690
   The British pound fell to $1.7460 from $1.7508.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 130.53 Japanese yen, up from
130.00 yen on Thursday. In later London trading today, the dollar
was quoted at 130.35 yen.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $443.45 a troy ounce, down from $444 late Thursday.
   The metal traded at a bid of $443.30 in Zurich, down from
$447.50.
   Hong Kong markets were closed for the Chinese New Year.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.37 a troy ounce,
down from $6.43.
</TEXT>
