<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-NorCalQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0448 02-19 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-NorCal Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Temblor Hits Near Lawrence Livermore Labs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores start of second graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake struck near the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratories, but there were no reports
of damage or injury.
   Thursday's quake had a magnitude estimated at 3.3 on the Richter
scale, meaning it was capable of causing slight damage, said Rick
McKenzie, a staff research associate at the University of
California Seismographic Stations at Berkeley.
   The quake was centered about seven miles northeast of the
laboratories, where research is conducted on nuclear weapons and
the ``Star Wars'' defense system, said McKenzie. The lab is about
40 miles east of San Francisco.
   Every increase of one number on the open-ended Richter scale
means a tenfold increase in the strenth of the quake. A quake of
magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans, while one of
magnitude 8 can cause tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
