<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ONA-Mears     02-19 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ONA-Mears,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Editor: Presidential Coverage `Out of Control'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0518 to fix category code.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential campaign is out of
control, said the executive editor of The Associated Press, placing
part of the blame on the media.
   The candidates, some of whom have been campaigning for two
years, can also accept blame for overexposure that has bored the
voters, Walter Mears, AP vice president and executive editor, said
Thursday in a speech to the Ohio Newspaper Association.
   ``They tend to neutralize each other ... and they tend to wear
out their public welcome'' by the time the polls open, Mears said.
Candidates have also ``debated themselves hoarse. There have been
more than 30 debates so far, which may be why nobody is listening
anymore.''
   Mears said there are too many reporters covering the race and
too little substantive reporting.
   ``There were 3,000 reporters in New Hampshire,'' he said. ``The
numbers themselves are absurd.''
   But the immediacy of television and the speed with which news is
transmitted across the nation also has played a role.
   ``The Gary Hart story was in print before Donna Rice even got
home,'' he said.
   Mears covered presidential campaigns from 1960 through 1980 for
The AP, and won a Pulitzer Prize for his reporting on the 1976
campaign.
</TEXT>
