<DOCNO> AP880219-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reporter-Contempt     02-19 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reporter-Contempt,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Globe Reporter Faces Jailing For Protecting Sources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for The Boston Globe was ordered jailed
for contempt of court after repeatedly refusing to reveal the
identities of confidential sources cited in a 1982 story about a
former city official.
   Suffolk Superior Court Judge John P. Sullivan issued the order
Thursday but said he would allow Charles A. Radin to remain free
for at least a week so he could appeal to a higher court.
   Radin on Thursday refused to answer 28 questions about the
sources quoted in the story, citing First Amendment protections of
a free press and similar provisions of the state constitution.
   After Sullivan issued his order Thursday, E. Susan Garsh, an
attorney for the Globe and Radin, appealed the contempt finding to
the Appeals Court. No hearing date was set.
   In the April 1982 story, Radin said Richard J. Sinnott, a former
city licensing chief, had applied for a disability pension claiming
emotional stress suffered while attending a licensing board meeting
and two rock concerts.
   Sinnott withdrew his application shortly after the Globe
detailed his request.
   Sinnott then filed an invasion of privacy suit against several
city officials, accusing them of violating his rights by releasing
the contents of his application. Neither Radin nor the Globe are
defendants in the suit, but Sinnott's attorneys want information
about the sources to help them prepare for trial.
   Regina L. Quinlan, and attorney for Sinnott, has argued that the
right of Sinnott and others to privacy outweighs any right Radin or
the newspaper might have to conceal the names of anonymous sources.
   A state Appeals Court judge earlier this month agreed and
ordered Radin to disclose his sources.
</TEXT>
