<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-19 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. CLEMENTS ISLAND, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Civil War-era cannonball that
was a boon to a Maryland museum might have become a boom if the
museum manager had not been suspicious and called authorities,
police said.
   The bomb squad from the Maryland Fire Marshal's Office was
called to defuse the six-inch, rusty-brown cannonball, estimated to
be about 120 years old, said Bob Thomas, a spokesman for the office.
   A clammer found the cannonball in his net in the Potomac River.
He turned it over to the St. Clements Island Museum in southern
Maryland, Thomas said.
   The museum, which collects state artifacts, displayed the
cannonball until a museum manager, whose name was not released,
``became concerned that it was live,'' Thomas said.
   The bomb squad determined the cannonball was indeed live, with
its fuse intact and apparently containing explosive black powder
ignitable by friction or a spark, Thomas said.
   The bomb squad removed the cannonball and planned to defuse it
and return the shell to the museum, Thomas said. The cannonball
would have been lethal had it exploded, he said.
   Thomas did not know when the cannonball was found or how long it
was displayed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two state legislators defiantly munched cookies in
a Capitol committee room to protest a policy banning food in the
Colorado House of Representatives.
   The cookie rebellion was staged Thursday by Rep. Bill Owens and
Rep. Danny Williams. They ate while a photographer snapped pictures
and their committee deliberated a firearms bill.
   ``Excuse me,'' Owens told a witness. ``We're being photographed
breaking the law.''
   Besides prompting Thursday's cookie revolt, the decision caused
Republicans to interrupt work on one of their busiest days to
caucus for 30 minutes and discuss the subject. The matter will be
taken up again today, legislators said.
   House Speaker Carl ``Bev'' Bledsoe proposed the controversial
no-food policy after outside groups began offering legislators
breakfast in the Capitol before each morning's session. He said
crumbs and debris from the meals had gotten out of hand.
   The House Services Committee, which decides such matters,
inaugurated the ban Tuesday in the House and in House committee
rooms. The policy forced minority Democrats to abandon their
luncheon caucus that day and move it into the governor's office.
   Rep. Bonnie Allison, a Republican who opposes the ban, said
committees frequently are in session during lunch. She said it is
better to eat on the job than to leave the committee to eat ``while
your constituents are not being represented.''
   Rep. Carole Taylor-Little, another Republican, said it improves
mental health ``to have an ability to graze.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
