<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0257</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds Stivers. No separates moved for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Martha Granger Krock</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha Granger Krock, a former newspaper
society columnist, died Thursday. She was 87.
   The widow of former New York Times bureau chief Arthur Krock
wrote a society column for the Hearst newspapers in Chicago in the
early 1930s. After moving to Washington in 1933 and before marrying
Krock in 1939, she wrote a column called ``These Charming People''
for Hearst's Washington Times-Herald newspaper.
   During World War II she headed the American Women's Volunteer
Services, was a volunteer with the American Red Cross and was
decorated by Belgium for her war relief work.
   Her marriage to William Mitchell Blair of Chicago ended in
divorce. Krock died in 1974.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Stivers, TV special producer of such
shows as ``Circus of the Stars,'' ``Celebrity Daredevils'' and
``Stars Salute to the U.S. Olympic Team,'' died of cancer
Wednesday, a day before his 67th birthday.
   Stivers created the 1969 celebrity contest show ``The Movie
Game,'' featuring John Wayne, Bob Hope, Jimmy Stewart, Carol
Burnett and Burt Reynolds.
   The previous year he produced a nationwide talent search for
NBC-TV, ``Showcase '68,'' which introduced Linda Ronstadt to
network television, as well as Sly and the Family Stone and others.
In 1975 he created ``The People's Choice Awards,'' now in its 14th
year.
   Stivers is survived by his wife, Bunny; son Robert Jr., stepsons
Tom and Larry Hendel; and two granddaughters.
</TEXT>
