<DOCNO> AP880219-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0808EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Germany 1stLd-Writethru a0442 02-19 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 3 grafs new with Kohl comments today. Picks up 2nd graf
pvs, When the. Meeting scheduled 11:30 a.m. EST; top planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today said
his visit to Washington is primarily aimed at pressing for Senate
ratification of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty
without any strings attached.
   ``I came here particularly to make it clear in the Senate that
the INF treaty should be ratified without any amendments,'' Kohl
said.
   ``I am very pleased and very happy that the day yesterday has
made it very clear that there are no differences between the
(Reagan) administration and between us,'' he added in an interview
on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   When the United States and the Soviet Union were negotiating the
treaty, there was some opposition from officials in Bonn worried it
would leave the Soviets with a military advantage.
   Kohl erased doubts about West German support on Thursday when he
went to Capitol Hill and lobbied for speedy Senate ratification of
the pact, which would eliminate missiles with ranges between 300
and 3,000 miles.
   ``He put his wholehearted support behind the INF treaty,
indubitably, unquestionably and without any reservation, saying
that there should be no amendments to it,'' Senate Majority Leader
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said after the private meeting.
   Kohl's spokesman, Friedhelm Ost, confirmed Byrd's account and
said the chancellor told Congress the treaty is necessary to
maintain momentum in the drive for disarmament.
   Kohl was due to meet with President Reagan today with both
military and money matters on the agenda.
   Among those Kohl saw on Thursday was Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
who has argued against the treaty on grounds it will hurt European
security. Helms did not relent in his opposition to the pact, but
said of Kohl, ``he's the most impressive head of state that we've
had in a long time. He gives detailed answers to every question.''
   West Germany is intensely active in efforts to shape U.S. arms
control strategy because its location on the frontier with Soviet
bloc nations gives it special interests and special fears about
military arrangements on both sides.
   Kohl was the last Western European leader to see Secretary of
State George P. Shultz before the secretary's departure today for
Moscow and more arms control negotiations with the Soviets.
   Highest on Shultz's arms control agenda is a U.S.-Soviet effort
to reach an agreement by a late spring summit in Moscow to cut
arsenals of intercontinental ballistic missiles and other strategic
nuclear arms by 50 percent.
   NATO has agreed the strategic arms talks are the first priority.
But West German politicians, particularly the opposition Social
Democrats, have sought more of an emphasis in negotiations on
reducing short-range systems _ the type of weapons that could be
used on German soil if a conventional war broke out and escalated
quickly.
   Officials in Bonn also have been questioning how quickly NATO
should implement a 1983 decision to modernize its force of
short-range nuclear weapons _ those with ranges below 300 miles.
   The Germans are particularly concerned about deployment of a new
generation of ground-launched rockets to replace NATO's aged force
of 75-mile-range Lance missiles with rockets capable of hitting
targets more than 100 miles away.
   A senior administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, issued assurances that though the modernization will
proceed, there is no rush.
   Deployment of missiles to replace the Lance may not occur before
1995, the official said.
   ``There are no major decisions facing the alliance and so
there's not an issue here in the day-to-day working of the
alliance,'' the official said.
   Much more study of the weaponry that would replace the Lance
missile is required by the Defense Department before the new
weapons are produced, the official said.
   The view was echoed by Wim van Eekelen, the Netherlands' defense
minister and chairman of the Eurogroup _ the European members of
the NATO alliance.
   Van Eekelen, whose visit to Washington coincided with Kohl's
trip, said at a news conference that NATO should adhere to its
agreement on modernizing short-range missiles, while delaying a
final decision to deploy until the weapons are produced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
