<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Police-Discrimination     02-19 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police-Discrimination,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settles Dispute Between Naperville, Pregnant Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers who were suspended
after they became pregnant will be able to return to work and
receive back pay, in a settlement of their sex discrimination
complaint.
   ``You can only sew so many baby clothes. It tends to get
monotonous,'' one of the officers, Juliet Fabbri, 25, said Thursday.
   ``I just want to go back,'' said Ms. Fabbri, who is five months
pregnant.
   Lisa M. Brogan, 27, who gave birth Sunday to a son, Daniel
Patrick, said she probably will wait six to weeks to return to her
job.
   The women were suspended Jan. 19 by officials of this western
Chicago suburb. They filed complaints 10 days later with the U.S.
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, charging they had been
discriminated against because they were pregnant.
   The women had requested ``light duty'' or desk jobs, given to
employees while they recuperate from sickness or injuries.
Naperville officials first said the light-duty jobs had been
eliminated, then said they never had been sanctioned in the first
place.
   ``There may have been times in the past when it was done, but it
wasn't city policy,'' said city spokesman Charlie Pajor.
   Under the agreement disclosed Thursday by the EEOC, the
suspensions will be lifted and they will be reinstated.
   The women were receiving sick pay during the suspensions, city
attorney Eric Margolis said, but the sick pay will be credited and
full monetary relief and other benefits will be provided.
   ``The city's feeling was to settle this and move on to establish
policy for the city as a whole,'' Margolis said.
   Police Chief James Teal said he was pleased an agreement was
reached.
</TEXT>
