<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GaTech-Nuclear     02-19 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ga Tech-Nuclear,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Tech `Whistle-Blowers' Must Await Trial To Get Jobs Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to order the
immediate reinstatement of two nuclear technicians who contend they
were fired for ``whistle-blowing'' on safety problems at the
school's reactor.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans on Thursday denied a request
for a temporary restraining order by Paul B. Sharpe and Steven N.
Millspaugh, who wanted their jobs back while awaiting a trial of
their suit for permanent reinstatement and unspecified monetary
damages.
   Georgia Tech President John P. Crecine on Monday ordered the
school's 24-year-old reactor shut down indefinitely. Last month,
federal regulators had curtailed operations at the reactor because
of safety violations.
   School officials said Sharpe and Millspaugh were dismissed under
a reorganization plan under discussion since May and not because of
the safety violations.
   ``If they blew the whistle, who did they blow it to? They didn't
blow it to me, and they're required to blow it to me,'' said
Crecine.
   The university says it has a policy of finding new jobs on the
campus for people whose posts are eliminated and has admitted the
firings were mistakes. Tech offered the two other jobs on the
campus pending administrative hearings but Sharpe and Millspaugh
want their original positions back.
   Ken Clark of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's Southeast
Regional Office said the organization is investigating the
possibility that reprisals may have been taken against the two but
declined further comment.
   Clark said the NRC also was checking possible procedural
problems at the reactor, which is small by commercial standards but
among the larger of about 60 research reactors in the country.
   Tech's device is used to test reactions of materials to
radioactive particles. One company is testing treatments for brain
cancer, said Robert MacDonald, associate director of Tech's Neely
Nuclear Research Center.
   In December, the NRC learned of an unreported spill of
radioactive cadmium. The substance has a half-life of 53 hours and
quickly became harmless, Clark said. Crecine and Clark said that
type of spill does not need to be reported.
   However, because of the spill, the NRC ordered a halt to
irradiation experiments in January and Crecine ordered the reactor
shut down Monday.
</TEXT>
