<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     02-19 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party to Boycott Council Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's largest opposition party
said today it will boycott provincial elections that the government
had hoped would help resolve the island's four-year ethnic conflict.
   The party believes general elections should be held before any
local contests are considered, said Somasara Dassanayake, general
secretary of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party.
   The decision was made Thursday night at a meeting chaired by
Sirimavo Bandaranaike, party leader and former prime minister, he
said. The party is dominated by the island's majority Sinhalese.
   On Thursday, a moderate Tamil party appealed to the Indian
government to halt the Sri Lankan government's call for provincial
council nominations, saying that continued turbulance on the island
would prevent free and fair elections.
   The Sri Lanka Election Commission on Wednesday announced that
nominations for the nine provincial councils would be accepted
March 2-9.
   The councils are designed to appease Tamil militants by giving
Tamils greater say in local government. The militants have been
calling for self-rule or independence in northern and eastern areas.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million population. They claim they are discriminated against by
the majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the central
government and army.
   India last July signed a peace accord with Sri Lanka aimed at
ending the four-year guerrilla war for an independent Tamil
homeland. But the largest rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, has rejected the pact, and India has sent more than
42,000 troops to the island to curb the Tigers.
   India became involved because it has 60 million ethnic Tamils in
its southern states who are sympathetic with the Sri Lankan Tamils.
   On Thursday, members of the moderate Tamil United Liberation
Front said in the southern Indian city of Madras that the call for
provincial council nominations was premature.
   They noted that the peace accord calls for unification of
administration in the northern and eastern provinces. Front leaders
said the two regions should be formally merged before council
nominations and elections are held.
   The leaders have taken refuge in Madras because of threats from
militant Tamils.

</TEXT>
