<HEAD>Separated Twin Undergoes Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-year-old Patrick Binder was doing well
after surgery to implant a metal plate over the hole in his skull
where he was attached to Siamese twin brother, Benjamin, the
hospital said.
   The West German infants, whose heads were separated in an
historic operation last fall, were listed in stable condition at
Johns Hopkins Hospital, said spokeswoman Lisa Hillman.
   Patrick's surgery was Thursday, and Benjamin underwent an
identical six-hour operation Wednesday.
   Doctors also said the twins appeared to be making better
neurological progress since the separation, Ms. Hillman said.
Doctors had feared they might suffer vision loss as a result of the
surgery, in which surgeons cut a major vein supplying blood to
their separate brains.
   Bone will grow over the titanium mesh plates, which remain in
their heads permanently, doctors said.
