<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SunnyvaleShooting     02-19 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunnyvale Shooting,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Will Seek Death Penalty Against Gunman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer whiz may face the death
penalty if convicted of any of seven murder charges stemming from a
shooting rampage through the Silicon Valley plant where he once
worked.
   Richard Wade Farley, 39, was arraigned Thursday in San Jose
Municipal Court on the homicide charges, three counts of attempted
murder and a count each of felony vandalism and second-degree
burglary. He did not enter a plea.
   After the two-minute hearing, Santa Clara County Deputy District
Attorney Alan Nudelman said he will seek capital punishment in the
murder cases.
   About 200 employees at ESL Inc. on Thursday toured the building
where the attack occurred two days earlier as ``part of the healing
process,'' said company spokeswoman Edie Cartwright.
   The employees saw walls, floors and furniture riddled with
bullet holes and dozens of computer terminals with screens shot
out, Cartwright said. Many windows were shattered. Bloodstains were
painted over and most rugs removed.
   The building, where 300 of the company's 2,200 employees mainly
work on classified defense projects, was to reopen its first floor
today. Employees will return Monday to the second floor, where most
of the damage occurred.
   The first funeral for victims of the attack was scheduled later
today for Glenda Moritz, a 27-year-old planner.
   Farley was brought to court in handcuffs and shackles from an
isolation cell where guards said he has been quiet and apparently
writing letters.
   It was with rambling and threatening notes sent through the mail
that the software engineer harassed former co-worker Laura Black
before finally wounding her and two others and killing seven people
Tuesday in a six-hour siege at ESL in Sunnyvale, 40 miles south of
San Francisco.
   Investigators and colleagues said Farley apparently had no
criminal record, was honorably discharged after 11 years in the
Navy, was intelligent and had held several high-security defense
jobs.
   While in jail, Farley ``has been kind of pondering his
thoughts,'' said sheriff's Sgt. Cary Colla, who added he had asked
for envelopes to mail letters. Farley, Colla said, also inquired
about phone privileges.
   Wearing glasses and a red jumpsuit, Farley looked around the
courtroom during arraignment before Judge Hugh Mullin III, who
ordered that he continue to be held without bail. He is to return
to court March 4 to enter a plea.
   Gregory C. Paraskou, a deputy county public defender appointed
to represent Farley, said he had not spoken to his client about a
plea.
   Farley is being held in a isolation cell reserved for high-risk
inmates. It is outfitted with a large observation window which
allows guards close supervision.
   Still recovering Thursday were the four ESL employees injured in
the attack, including Black, who was in stable condition with a
gunshot wound to her shoulder.
   The 26-year-old electrical engineer, called the main target of
the shootings, said she was haunted for four years by strange
gifts, threatening letters and obsessive behavior involving a man
she never dated.
</TEXT>
