<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistClan     02-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Clan,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Teen-Ager Held in Contempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A son of polygamist matriarch Vickie
Singer has been found in contempt for refusing to answer a grand
jury's questions about the bombing of a Mormon chapel and
subsequent two-week standoff with police.
   After a brief closed hearing, U.S. District Judge J. Thomas
Greene opened the courtroom Thursday while arguments were presented
on the government's motion seeking the contempt citation against
Hans Benjamin Singer, 15.
   Greene ordered the teen-ager under house arrest at the Fairview
home of Ramon and Harriett Swapp while the matter is under appeal
to the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The Swapps are the parents of Addam Swapp, who is married to two
daughters of Mrs. Singer.
   Earlier this month, four members of the clan _ including Mrs.
Singer, widow of slain polygamist John Singer _ pleaded innocent to
federal charges stemming from the bombing of a Mormon chapel in
Marion and the 13-day siege that followed at the clan's nearby farm.
   The standoff ended Jan. 28 when Corrections Lt. Fred House was
killed and clan patriarch Addam Swapp was wounded. Swapp, 26; his
brother Jonathan, 21; Mrs. Singer, 44, and her son, John Timothy
Singer, 21, were indicted on counts ranging from conspiracy,
possession and use of a bomb and firearms violations to assault and
attempting to kill federal agents.
   A homicide charge is expected to be filed by prosecutors later
this month.
   On Feb. 5 and again Wednesday, Hans Singer refused to answer
questions from the grand jury. The boy refused to give information
on matters about which he had ``personal, eyewitness knowledge,''
Greene said.
   Greene said he had granted the youth immunity from prosecution,
a move authorized by the Department of Justice so that there could
be no question of his incriminating himself.
   Singer's refusal to answer questions from the panel came in the
wake of Greene's ruling that the boy had no rights to
``parent-child privilege.''
   The youth's attorney, Steven Kuhnhausen, argued that his client
``has deeply held religious beliefs that he believes preclude him
from being compelled to testify against his mother or members of
his extended family.''
   U.S. Attorney Brent Ward argued that there was every indication
that the boy could be a competent witness possessing first-hand
knowledge of crimes ``by persons already indicted and persons not
yet indicted.''
   According to Mrs. Singer's diary, used as evidence at a previous
hearing, the youth accompanied Addam and Jonathan Swapp when they
bombed the chapel.
</TEXT>
