<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSInstitutes 1stLd-Writethru a0515 02-19 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Institutes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0515,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multidisciplinary Institutes Proposed To Study AIDS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 pvs, `But lack...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
morning news show comment from AIDS coordinator, transition. ADDS 1
graf at end with more comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS should be attacked by creating a series of
specialized institutes that bring together key scientific
disciplines, medical experts told the president's AIDS commission.
   The strategy, modeled after the comprehensive cancer center
program of the early 1970s, would provide a useful
cross-fertilization of ideas for dealing with the complex disease,
they said.
   Medical schools and universities would be logical places to
build four or five such comprehensive centers, Richard Ross, dean
of the medical faculty at the Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine in Baltimore, said Thursday.
   The centers could combine such disciplines as prevention,
education, patient care, studies in humans and basic research into
the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, he said
Thursday.
   Ideas developed in the laboratory could then be tested quickly
in patients, he said.
   Another AIDS expert, Dr. Anthony Fauci, coordinator of federal
AIDS research for the National Institutes of Health, defended today
the rigorous testing process promising AIDS treatments must undergo
before approval.
   ``The reason that only one drug has been made available, AZT, is
because it is the only drug that thus far has been shown in
scientifically controlled trials to be safe and effective. It isn't
a question of there are a lot of drugs around and only one is being
released. That's the only one that has been shown to be
effective,'' Fauci said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   Ross told the Presidential Commission on the Human
Immunodeficiency Virus Epidemic that lack of space is one obstacle
in developing comprehensive AIDS centers.
   ``We have the people, we have the interest, we have the
commitment, but we don't have the space,'' he said. ``And we need
your help in getting the space.''
   Retired Adm. James D. Watkins, chairman of the commission, asked
Ross to develop details of his proposal and supply them to the
commission later.
   In an interview, Ross said he did not know how much the proposed
centers would cost. He estimated the buildings alone would cost
some $75 million to $100 million apiece, but said he did not know
what an annual operating budget would be.
   In his testimony, he also urged that about an equal amount of
money as would go to the comprehensive centers be earmarked for
institutions proposing research in one or more subject areas, short
of the comprehensive approach.
   The idea of comprehensive centers was also proposed by AIDS
researcher Jerome Groopman of Deaconess Hospital in Boston, who
urged consideration of establishing 10 to 15 such centers.
   He also suggested federal AIDS research grants be extended
beyond the traditional three-year or five-year terms because
research toward a vaccine or cure could well take far longer.
   On testing drugs for AIDS treatment, Fauci, who also is director
of National Institue of Allergies and Infectious Disease, said in
the ABC interview, ``If you look at the clinical trials that are
going on now, there are a number of drugs that are in clinical
trial, hopefully they will be expeditiously shown to either be safe
and effective or will be discarded because they have been proven
not to be safe and effective.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
