<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-IndividualImpact 1stLd-Writethru NewOrleanspolicehaveissuedanarrestwarrantforTomKatsikis
02-19 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Individual Impact, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,590</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs graf 2 to clarify that increase due to economic growth.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If President Reagan's proposed budget actually
becomes America's budget for 1989, it will mean that the federal
government will collect $1,687 in individual income taxes for every
man, woman and child in the country.
   That's an increase of $65 from the budget he presented a year
ago, due almost entirely to economic growth.
   The mathematics are straightforward. Divide the $412.4 billion
expected through individual income taxes during the year by 244.4
million people, the U.S. population as of Jan. 1. Last year, when
the total population was 242.1 million, the assumption was that
individual income taxes would bring in $392.8 billion.
   According to the budget proposal Reagan sent to Capitol Hill on
Thursday, the federal government expects its total receipts in 1989
to be $964.7 billion. Besides the personal income tax, the sum
includes corporate income taxes of $117.7 billion and Social
Security taxes of $354.6 billion. The rest will come from estate
and gift taxes, customs duties, excise taxes and the like.
   Using the same population formula for this year, the total
receipts represent $3,947 for everyone from the tiniest to the
oldest centenarian.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The source of money flowing in to the government has changed
greatly in the Reagan years, the administration points out. The
individual and corporate income tax share of total receipts in 1989
is expected to be 4.7 percentage points less than 1980 when three
out of every five dollars came from income taxes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The administration tagged two displaced worker programs for
extinction because they have not ``operated efficiently to help
workers adjust.''
   One provides unemployment benefit payments when unemployment
insurance runs out. The administration feels those additional weeks
of payments ``encourage workers to delay efforts to seek new
opportunities in the hope that somehow their old jobs will
reappear.'' In the current year, the program cost $48 million in
federal money.
   The second program, costing $287 million in 1988, pays states
for helping dislocated workers find new occupations that use their
skills, get training in new skills or meet the cost of looking for
jobs. That money, says the budget, should go into a new Worker
Readjustment Program.
   The administration also wants to drop a work incentive program
that provided job services, training and public service employment
to welfare recipients.
   ``Although its aim is to help curb welfare dependency, it has
not proved successful or cost-effective,'' the proposal said. The
government budgeted $93 million for the program this year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Reagan's budget proposal for 1988 asked Congress to tack on $1
for every ticket for international travel to and from the United
States to be used for a government program that encourages foreign
travel to the United States.
   Congress did not pass the legislation last year and the
administration wants it brought up again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Money for recreation is to be cut back under the proposal from
$1.7 billion this year to $1.4 billion.
   To make that cut, the administration wants to reduce the amount
spent for buying land from $232 million to $51 million. And it
proposes a halt in buying some land for park and refuge purposes
through 1993 _ except for wetlands acquired with revenue from sale
of duck hunting stamps and the like.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The budget also makes clear that pardons are on the increase.
Last year, there were only 23 pardons granted by the president.
That number is estimated to increase to 50 this fiscal year and 50
again in the next. There was no explanation. The number of
``denials and no actions,'' _ 290 in 1987 _ is expected to increase
slightly to 300 this year and next.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1000EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 02-19 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Urge Federal Crackdown After String of Officer Deaths</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB grasf 12-13, `Four other...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
arrest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a police detective was fatally shot in a
drug raid, Mayor Raymond Flynn criticized the federal government as
a missing partner in the fight against ``America's vicious cycle of
drugs and guns.''
   Detective Sherman C. Griffiths, 36, died Thursday of a head
wound suffered Wednesday night. His death and those of two other
officers since October were related to drug or weapon violations.
   Flynn and Police Commissioner Francis M. Roache on Thursday
claimed Washington is relaxing handgun controls and drug
enforcement and rehabilitation programs just when tougher measures
are needed.
   ``They've almost given up at the federal government,'' said
Roache. ``But we haven't given up in Boston. We're doing everything
humanly possible to protect our neighborhoods.''
   ``This is a very, very sad day for the Boston Police
Department,'' Flynn said. ``America's vicious cycle of drugs and
guns has claimed another victim.
   ``Great efforts are being made by our police department. They're
out there doing their job every day, but there's a partner that's
missing,'' said Flynn. ``We need allies on the federal level.''
   ``We're not satisfied here with nice catchwords about drugs, we
want good solid programs,'' said Flynn. ``At least we shouldn't
throw up our hands at our border and say nothing can be done.''
   Griffiths was shot when he and five other plainclothes officers,
armed with a search warrant, tried to force their way into an
apartment in the Dorchester section to look for illegal drugs.
   Two shots were fired from inside, and one bullet hit Griffiths.
One officer returned fire, but did not wound anyone in the
apartment.
   Griffiths, who was married and the father of two, died at Boston
City Hospital.
   Albert Lewin, 33, of Boston, pleaded innocent to a murder charge
and four other related weapons and assault charges at his
arraignment Thursday. He was ordered held without bail, a court
clerk said.
   Four other people pleaded innocent to charges of conspiracy to
violate drug laws, said police spokesman James Jordan. Trial was
scheduled Feb. 29. A sixth person was arrested today and also is
accused of murder and related offenses.
   The first of the three officers to die since Oct. 26 was
Detective Roy Sergei, 42, who died three weeks after being wounded
in a shootout. His partner was also wounded but survived.
   The suspect in that shooting, Ted Otsuki, is on the FBI's most
wanted list.
   On Feb. 10, Detective Thomas J. Gill, 38, died after he was
struck by an Amtrak train while searching for guns taken in a
housebreak.
   Two officers, one on the Boston force and one with the
Metropolitan District Police, were wounded during a drug bust last
month. An alleged cocaine dealer turned a shotgun on an undercover
officer in the Jan. 29 incident and was killed in the ensuing
shootout.
</TEXT>
