<DOCNO> AP880219-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-Defense     02-19 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Defense,1st ld-writethru, a0425,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new to update with Carlucci quotes. Picks up 2nd
graf pvs, Sen. Sam Nunn. Edits throughout to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said today
America faces higher risks because of President Reagan's military
budget, which kills some weapons and reduces troop strength.
   The reductions were sent to Congress on Thursday as part of the
budget's military spending package, which was cut in the effort to
reduce federal deficits.
   Carlucci said he chose to cut by eliminating some older weapons
and by small decreases in troop strength, rather than by wholesale
reductions.
   ``What it translates into is a smaller military force,''
Carlucci said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``It clearly means higher
risks. But we have elected to do this rather than hollow out the
force.''
   ``We want to maintain good people, adequate readiness, good
sustainability and we want to continue the modernization program of
those weapons that we consider absolutely essential and we want to
do so in the most cost-effective way,'' he said.
   Reagan's military budget was praised by lawmakers.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, told Carlucci on Thursday that he made ``exactly the
right choices.''
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., a critic of past Pentagon budgets,
praised Carlucci for a ``very helpful'' budget.
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., said, ``the Pentagon appears to have
taken its responsibility for budget cutting more seriously in this
proposed budget than in those of the past years.''
   The budget proposed to authorize $299.5 billion in Pentagon
spending for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, including $294
billion that would actually be paid out during the 12-month period.
That compares with $291.4 billion authorized for the current year.
   The overall Pentagon budget level had been set during talks
between the administration and Congress last November, when Reagan
approved the $299.5 billion level.
   He originally had wanted $332.4 billion, which would have been
an increase after three years of decreased spending. Those
reductions followed large buildups during Reagan's first four years
in office, when the Pentagon budget doubled as part of Reagan's
pledge to ``rearm America.''
   In the past eight weeks, Carlucci said, civilian and military
leaders have made ``hard choices'' to reduce spending by the $33
billion needed to reach the $299.5 billion level.
   Carlucci said he chose ``a smaller force that was fully ready to
perform its mission as opposed to a large force that was not ready.
The priorities in this budget were straightforward _ people,
readiness and efficient acquisition.''
   ``I believe these choices to be not in the best interest of our
national security posture,'' said Carlucci. ``However, I have made
them. They reflect the fiscal realities we face today and my
assessment of the direction'' the Pentagon should go.
   Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said ``in a fiscally constrained environment, we had to borrow
somewhat against the future to nourish the deterrent stance we have
today.''
   Among the choices:
   _The total strength of the four uniformed services will drop by
34,000 men and women, to a total of 2,138,000. The Air Force will
take the largest reduction, accounting for 23,000 of the total
cuts. But Carlucci also called for a 4.3 percent pay hike for the
troops and said the money is needed to keep up the high quality of
recruits and re-enlistments.
   To meet the reductions, the Army plans to cut its brigade of
motorized infantry at Fort Lewis, Wash., and cancel a previously
scheduled activation of two light infantry battalions in Alaska.
   The Navy will scrap plans to establish a 14th air wing at the
Miramar, Calif., Naval Air Station. Sixteen frigates and a
missile-firing submarine will be retired and the sailors will be
sent to other ships. The Air Force will deactivate two fighter
wings and start deactivating a third.
   Other reductions include Army plans to retire 450 Vietnam-era
utility helicopters and 170 scout copters; cancel the troubled
Aquila surveillance drone program and stop production of Copperhead
laser-guided artillery shells; cancel development of the
Anti-Tactical Missile; and develop only one new light helicopter
instead of two.
   _Delay development of the single-warhead Midgetman
nuclear-tipped missile, but include $200 million to keep the
program alive until a new administration can decide its fate. Nunn
is a supporter of the weapon. Carlucci also proposed putting all
100 MX weapons aboard trains, rather than having 50 of the
10-warhead weapons aboard trains and the other 50 in land-based
silos in Wyoming.
   _Kill the Air Force anti-satellite weapon, which Congress had
banned for two years from final-stage testing. The Pentagon had
pushed for continued development of the weapon, but Carlucci said
it was dropped this year because of the continued opposition from
Capitol Hill.
</TEXT>
