<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Cuba     02-19 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Cuba,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Said to Indicate Serious Human Rights Abuses in Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry said the regime of
Cuban President Fidel Castro violates most civil and political
rights and that hundreds of thousands of people want to leave the
nation, a newspaper reported.
   The right-wing Madrid daily ABC also quoted the confidential
report as saying the United States was hoping to persuade the
United Nations to include Cuba among nations periodically studied
for possible human rights violations.
   Susana Ansorena, a Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, today confirmed
that a report on the overall situation in Cuba had been compiled,
but she refused to reveal its contents and described it as a
``normal, confidential ministry document.''
   ``Spain has been consistently concerned with human rights in
Cuba and has done everything within its possibilities to defend
them,'' she added.
   As reported Thursday in ABC, the document stated that, ``given
the characteristics of the Cuban regime, the number of people that
seek to leave the country is estimated at between 200,000 and
500,000.''
   ABC quoted the report as saying the Castro regime ``violates
most civil and political rights, including the rights of free
speech and assembly, has a judicial system that fails to protect
rights and currently has between 1,000 and 10,000 political
prisoners.''
   The newspaper said the Foreign Ministry also found that ``a
campaign to rectify errors'' under way for more than a year in
Cuba, had led to ``a serious economic and ideological crisis.''
   ABC said the document went on to add that ``the line adopted by
Cuba to overcome its crisis does not coincide with _ and in fact is
contrary to _ that which (Soviet leader Mikhail) Gorbachev
envisions for the Soviet Union and the Socialist bloc.''
   Ms. Ansorena said the government of Socialist Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez saw the publication of the confidential report ``as
an attempt to prejudge its position and thus pressure it into
condemning the human rights situation in Cuba'' in an upcoming
meeting of the U.N. Human Rights Commission in Geneva.
</TEXT>
