<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra-Walsh     02-19 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra-Walsh,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Counsl Hires Own Counsel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The independent counsel investigating the
Iran-Contra affair has retained noted constitutional scholar
Laurence Tribe to represent his office during an expected Supreme
Court review of the special prosecutor law.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh on Thursday asked the high
court for permission to allow Tribe, a Harvard University law
professor, to file a friend-of-the court brief to defend the
constitutionality of the special prosecutor law.
   Another independent counsel, Alexia Morrison, has asked the
court to review last month's decision by the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals here that struck down the contitutionality of judicial
appointment of special prosecutors to investigate alleged
wrongdoing by high government officials.
   The divided appellate panel ruled that court appointment of
special prosecutors, or independent counsels as they are formally
called, encroaches on the president's exclusive consstitutional
authority to enforce the law.
   The court could agree to take the case as early as Monday.
   Unlike Morrison, Walsh has a parallel appointment from the
Justice Department to investigate the Iran-Contra affair, so the
appeals court decision does not threaten his prosecutorial
authority.
   But his office participated as a friend of the court in
appellate court arguments last year on the challenge to the law.
</TEXT>
