<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalWeather     02-19 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Weather,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Desert Winds Return To Wreak New Havoc</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Includes PM-Yosemite Death, a0554</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second round of high wind blowing across
Southern California killed a child, left a boater missing and
fanned two fires that injured six people and left at least 55
homeless today, officials said.
   Hundreds of campers were evacuated from Yosemite National Park
late Thursday and early today when wind topping 60 mph knocked down
trees up to 100 feet tall, park spokeswoman Mallory Smith said.
   One tree crashed through a cabin and crushed 9-year-old Jasmine
Bitts of Garden Grove, who was staying with her mother and a
companion, who suffered minor injuries.
   At sea, the Coast Guard resumed an air-sea search today for a
lone sailor reported missing Thursday on a 30-foot boat.
   The boater, Chris Dodd, 28, of Los Altos, set sail for the
mainland Tuesday from Santa Catalina Island in 12-foot seas. He had
been rescued by the Coast Guard once before this week, when a
galley water hose broke Monday and his boat swamped, Avalon Harbor
Patrol Officer John Bray said.
   In Los Angeles, the dry Santa Ana wind blowing down out of the
Great Basin in Nevada and western Utah spread flames to houses in
two separate blazes today.
   Six people, including a firefighter, were injured when an
unfinished apartment building caught fire shortly after midnight,
and wind-swept embers spread the blaze to a 10-unit apartment
complex and four other buildings.
   Twenty-five to 30 people were left homeless and damage was
estimated at $345,000, fire spokesman Jim Williamson said.
   In East Los Angeles, a fire in a commercial building spread to
three houses early today, said Los Angeles County fire spokesman
Bob Haskell. More than 20 people were left homeless.
   That fire was blamed on electrical wires that were blown into
contact over a roofing company, sending sparks into two propane
tanks. Damage was estimated at $500,000.
   Late Thursday, the Santa Ana wind knocked out power to about
2,000 Southern California Edison Co. customers and an additional
estimated 1,500 city Department of Water and Power customers,
officials said.
   Earlier this week, in the first blast of blustery weather, wind
was blamed for four deaths.
   One man was electrocuted when a power line was blown down, and
three were killed in a highway accident triggered when a
tractor-trailer rig buffeted by wind slewed off the highway and
into two cars.
</TEXT>
