<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Jansen'sFall 1stLd-Writethru a0486 02-19 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jansen's Fall, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hometown Fans Witness Skater's Latest Misfortune</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT to Jansen, sted Jensen. Version
moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one moment, the shouts of happiness
turned to groans of sorrow and golden hopes became dashed dreams.
   ``Oh no, not again,'' exclaimed one hometown fan as he watched
Olympic speed skater Dan Jansen fall to the ice with about 200
meters left in the 1000-meter race at the Calgary games.
   ``He's got too much hurt,'' said another. ``He's trying too bad
to win something for his sister.''
   Jansen's friends and fans had gathered Thursday night to watch
the televised race at a tavern next to the state fairgrounds, where
earlier this month he won the world sprint speed skating
championship.
   On this night, however, they saw Jansen lose his balance just as
he did four nights earlier, trying to carry the hope for an Olympic
medal and the burden of his sister's death.
   ``Danny comes in here all the time,'' said Randy Strumberger, a
bartender at the tavern. ``When he comes in again, I'll run around
the bar and hug him and buy him his first drink.''
   For Jansen's friends and family in this Milwaukee suburb of
nearly 64,000, Thursday's race was another chapter in a week of
tragedy. On Sunday, Jansen's sister, Jane, died of leukemia. Hours
later, Jansen fell in the first turn of the 500-meter race, in
which he was favored for a medal. He did not finish.
   Between then and Thursday, the community rallied behind their
hometown hero, and thousands of people signed a banner that was
sent to Jansen in Calgary.
   The banner proclaimed: ``Dan be strong. Keep the faith.
Wisconsin is with you all the way.''
   ``It's amazing the number of people I run into who know the
Jansen family,'' said Jim Hill, a customer at the tavern. ``This is
a small community.''
   But the dreams of Jansen overcoming his emotional turmoil and
skating to victory and gold were shattered in an instant once again.
   ``It was horrifying,'' said his father, Harry Jansen, who
watched the race at home with other family members. ``It was
unbelievable, especially that it happened like that on a
straightaway.''
   Jansen spoke with his son earlier in the day. ``I asked him how
he was doing, and he said he was feeling pretty good. But then he
would read some of the nice telegrams he got and he said would
start feeling down again.
   ``I told him he's a champion in my book.''
   But while Jansen believed his son fell in the earlier race
because of pressures from the sister's death, he doubted the same
was true for Thursday's fall.
   ``He was skating too good,'' Jansen said. ``His concentration
looked good. His stamina was good. I thought he was going to skate
a good race, and he did.''
   Jansen said he would offer his son encouragement when he arrived
home today for his sister's funeral on Saturday.
   ``I'm proud of him,'' he said. ``He did well just to get out
there and set an example for everyone else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
