<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Trade     02-19 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Trade,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tariffs To Be Lowered For Passenger Cars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea said today it plans to
lower import tariffs between 2 percent and 20 percent on cars and
more than 400 other products next month.
   The Ministry of Finance said the decision was part of efforts to
help curb inflation and reduce the country's trade surplus.
   A year ago, the United States formally asked South Korea to cut
tariffs and dismantle other import barriers for 982 items as a way
to correct the trade imbalance between the two countries. As a
result, South Korea slashed import tariffs between 5 percent and 20
percent on 266 items.
   Under the latest action, tariff rates for passenger cars will go
down from the current 50 percent to 30 percent.
   Some of the other 435 tariff cuts include: pianos, to 15 percent
from 20 percent; color TV sets to 15 percent from 30 percent;
computers, to 15 percent from 20 percent; film to 15 percent from
20 percent; cosmetics, to 25 percent from 30 percent; tiles, to 10
from 20 percent; and wheat and corn to 5 percent from 10 percent.
</TEXT>
