<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Arafat     02-19 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Arafat,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leader Addresses Human Rights Panel, U.S. Walkout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat made his debut before the
U.N. Human Rights Commission today and likened Israeli practices in
the occupied territories to the Nazi extermination campaign.
   Arafat also called for the formation of an ``international
force'' to protect Palestinian residents.
   The United States, he said, was encouraging Israel to ``carry on
with aggression and crimes'' by giving the Jewish state ``unlimited
support.''
   The U.S. delegation left the crowded conference hall before
Arafat began to speak from the dais.
   A member of the U.S. delegation, Marshall Breger, declined to
call it a walkout, saying only: ``We are not present.''
   The seat of the Israeli delegate, who has observer status in the
43-nation commission, remained empty. The delegate, Ambassador
Pinhas Eliav, said in a press statement that Arafat's presence at
the commission ``makes a mockery of everything that body stands
for.''
   In his speech, Arafat said the Israeli methods of dealing with
the recent Arab unrest in Gaza and the West Bank were ``operations
of collective extermination''.
   He said Israel was carrying out ``heinous massacres and crimes''
and was ``repeating today the same crimes committed against
humanity at the hands of the Fascists and the Nazis.''
   Arafat said more than 120 Palestinians had been killed in the
recent waves of unrests and more than 3,000 wounded. In addition,
he charged, 7,000 others were held in ``six new concentration
camps'' set up by the Israeli authorities.
   U.N. officials say Israeli gunfire has killed at least 55 Arabs
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip since protests began Dec. 8. Israel
seized the territories during the 1967 Middle East war.
   Arafat charged that arms used by Israel in quelling the unrest
included ``internationally prohibited gases.'' He said he was
calling on the world to ``guarantee international protection for
our people'' against a ``terrorist and racist enemy who is
indifferent to international law.''
   Such protection could be assured, he said, through the formation
of an international force to enable the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state ``with Jerusalem as its capital.''
   When asked at a press conference to clarify his call for an
international force, he said no new forces would be needed because
U.N. peacekeeping troops were already in the area.
   Arafat reacted heatedly when another questioner asked him
whether he was hurting the situation by comparing Israeli practices
to the extermination of 6 million Jews by the Nazis.
   ``Have you been commissioned by Israel to ask the question?'' he
countered.
   Arafat said the U.S. threat to close the Palestine Liberation
Organization mission to the United Nations in New York was a
``threat against any other state that may have views divergent from
those of the United States.''
   He said a closure would be a violation of international law. As
a last resort the case should be taken to the International Court
of Justice, he said.
</TEXT>
