<1ST_LINE>r i BC-EncyclicalHighlights     02-19 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Encyclical Highlights,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights of Pope's Encyclical on Social Justice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of Pope John Paul II's
social encyclical released by the Vatican Friday:
   _ Problems caused by the East and West:
   ``Each of the two blocs harbors in its own way a tendency toward
imperialism ... or toward forms of neo-colonialism. ... Conflicts
... between East and West (are) an important cause of the
retardation or stagnation of the South.''
   _ Reforms of international economic and financial systems:
   ``The world monetary and financial system is marked by an
excessive fluctuation or exchange rates and interest rates, to the
detriment of the balance of payments and the debt situation of the
poorer countries.''
   _ The church's role:
   ``The church's social doctrine is not a `third way' between
liberal capitalism and Marxist collectivism, nor even a possible
alternative to other solutions less radically opposed to one
another.''
   _ Church property:
   ``Faced by cases of need, one cannot ignore (necessities) in
favor of superfluous church ornaments and costly furnishings for
divine worship; on the contrary, it could be obligatory to sell
these goods in order to provide food, drink, clothing and shelter
for those who lack these things.''
   _ Dangers of totalitarianism:
   ``No social group, for example a political party, has the right
to upsurp the role of sole leader, since this brings about the
destruction of the true subjectivity of society and of the
individual citizens.''
</TEXT>
