<HEAD>Central Bank Says Robbery Of $8 Million Was Insured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central Bank officials said today
the $8 million stolen from a U.S. currency shipment to the bank was
insured, and its loss won't hurt the country.
   The money, stolen in Brazil on Feb. 4, was part of $52 million
the United States had sent to help Argentina pay foreign bonds.
Argentina is the developing world's third largest debtor after
Brazil and Mexico.
   Thirteen sacks stuffed with $4 million dollars cash each were en
route from Kennedy International Airport in New York to Buenos
Aires on Brazil's carrier Varig when the flight made a stop in Rio
de Janeiro, Brazil.
   Police say two of the sacks were stolen during the stopover, but
that the remaining $44 million arrived without problem at Buenos
Aires' airport.
   The cash was being shipped by the Federal Reserve Bank in New
York.
</TEXT>
