<HEAD>Teen Accused In Fatal School Shooting Considered Suicide Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old accused of fatally
shooting a high school official and wounding two teachers has been
moved to a medical unit because a psychologist termed him a suicide
risk.
   ``In my opinion, at this time, Jason Harless presents an
increased suicidal risk. I am recommending that the necessary
protective measures be taken,'' psychologist Robert Clapp wrote in
a report.
   Juvenile court administrative Judge Jack Page ordered Harless
moved Thursday from a juvenile detention center to the medical wing
of the Pinellas County Jail.
   Clapp said Harless became more despondent after learning of the
Wednesday death of Richard Allen, 53, assistant principal at
Pinellas Park High School.
   Allen was shot in the head when he and two teachers tried to
break up a fight between Harless and another youth in the high
school's packed cafeteria on Feb. 11.
   The teachers also were shot; both have been treated and released
from a hospital.
   Harless has been charged with five counts of attempted
first-degree murder, for the shootings in the lunchroom and shots
fired at two policemen. His friend Jason McCoy was charged with
three counts of the same offense although he is not accused of
firing a weapon.
   A grand jury that meets March 1 will consider charges against
the youths. If indicted, they will be tried as adults, said Richard
Mensh, Pinellas-Pasco chief assistant state attorney.
