<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabyHeart     02-19 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Heart,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Infants Evaluated for Liver Transplant from Brain-Dead Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four infants in need of livers are
being evaluated for transplant after a baby kept on life-support
systems as a potential organ donor was declared brain dead, a
hospital official said.
   The brain-dead diagnosis for the 7-pound infant born Tuesday,
was confirmed Thursday after examinations by three neurologists,
said Joyce Peabody, chief of neonatology at Loma Linda University
Medical Center.
   The boy's heart was beating, and a respirator supplied oxygen to
his organs, but he had no higher brain activity, she said. The
child was born Tuesday.
   The boy's condition, known as anencephaly, kills most babies
within days after birth. Their healthy organs can be transplanted
if organ damage is prevented by maintaining the infants on
life-support.
   The Southern California Organ Procurement Center would choose
organ recipients, Ms. Peabody said. Liver and heart were the most
likely organs for transplant, she said, adding that Loma Linda
officials know of one baby in need of a heart but not of the right
blood type.
   The names of the baby's parents were withheld to protect their
privacy, but Ms. Peabody said the mother had expressed satisfaction
with the procedure.
   The National Right to Life Committee, which accused Loma Linda
of going beyond prevailing medical ethics, denounced the procedure.
Protesters said doctors at the hospital hadn't done enough to
ensure that organs weren't removed from live children.
   However, Ms. Peabody said, the case may have answered several
medical and ethical questions about the practice of maintaining
anencephalics in order to use their organs.
   It demonstrated that the baby didn't suffer discomfort or
distress, she said. It also indicated organs can be kept in
condition suitable for transplant, and that the life-support
apparatus didn't artificially prolong the time until the baby
suffered brain death.
   One of the hospital's 13 heart transplant patients under age 4
received the heart of an anencephalic baby earlier this year from a
donor child in Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
