<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-AIDSandHealth 1stLd-Writethru a0456 02-19 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-AIDS and Health, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Spending Hike Would Be Biggest of Any Federal Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds. Subs graf 18, If projections, to CORRECT both figures to
billions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $1.3 billion that President Reagan
proposes to spend fighting AIDS next year _ his ``highest public
health priority'' _ would be by far the largest percentage increase
in any major federal program.
   But the 38 percent boost over current AIDS spending of $951
million approved by Congress would pale if compared with the $534
million that the president initially requested last year.
   By that measure, Reagan could just as well have boasted that he
was more than doubling his AIDS request. But that would have drawn
attention to the reality that Congress has consistently voted much
more for AIDS research and education than the president has
requested.
   For fiscal 1987, for example, Reagan sought $213 million and
Congress appropriated $502 million.
   With the White House calling for a drastic increase in AIDS
spending next year, Congress is considered unlikely to approve any
significant increase on top of that, as it has in the past.
   One reason is that the overall fiscal 1989 budget plan was
written in consultation with congressional leaders in
deficit-reduction negotiations prompted by the October stock market
crash.
   Another is that both administration and congressional leaders
have said the proposed budget is calculated in part to avoid a
knock-down fight in an election year.
   But a high-ranking administration official said Reagan gave a
hint of his plans for a dramatic increase in AIDS spending during a
meeting last summer when the president decided to appoint a White
House commission on the deadly disease.
   This official, who discussed the budget only on condition that
he not be identified, quoted Reagan as saying, ``I want it (the
commission) to have whatever money it needs.''
   The official, who helps referee spending fights among federal
health agencies, remembered thinking at that moment: ``There goes
my budget.''
   The 38 percent rise in AIDS spending compares with a net
proposed increase of 5.8 percent for the 250 programs administered
by the Department of Health and Human Services under the fiscal
1989 budget plan that Reagan sent Thursday to Congress.
   Nearly 95 percent of the huge department's proposed $396.8
billion budget, which represents about one-third of all federal
spending, goes for so-called entitlement programs such as Social
Security, Medicare and Medicaid.
   The administration has relatively little control over
entitlement programs because eligiblity criteria are fixed by law.
   Social Security spending alone is expected to grow by $14
billion, or 6.4 percent, to $233.8 billion during the new fiscal
year which starts Oct. 1.
   Medicaid, the state-federal health program for poor people, will
cost the federal government $32.7 billion in 1989, up 7 percent
from the current $30.7 billion. Much of the increase is attributed
to heavier spending on AIDS patients, from $375 million to $600
million.
   Medicare spending for 33 million retirees and disabled workers
is projected to rise to $84 billion from $78.9 billion this year.
   The most controversial part of the HHS spending plan is likely
to be Reagan's request for $1.2 billion in Medicare cuts which he
says are required to meet an agreed target of a $3.5 million
reduction.
   If projections of overall Medicare spending by the Congressional
Budget Office are correct, the $3.5 billion reduction target
already has been met. If the administration is correct, an
additional $1.2 billion in cuts would be needed.
   Of that $1.2 billion, the administration proposes to cover about
$1 billion by reducing payments to large teaching hospitals that
help them with educational costs.
   HHS chief of staff Thomas Burke said a recent internal study
showed that the Medicare profits of teaching hospitals are 2{ times
higher than those of non-teaching hospitals.
   ``It would seem these hospitals are going to be able to absorb
this reduction,'' Burke said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
