<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Robodoc     02-19 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robodoc,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Developing Robotic Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAVIS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computerized robot named Robodoc may one
day help surgeons perform hip replacements in an operating room of
the future, University of California researchers say.
   Orthopedic surgeon William L. Bargar and veterinarian Howard
Paul said Robodoc's ability to drill and measure precisely will
prove valuable in assisting physicians in hip replacements and
other types of surgery.
   Bargar and Paul showed off the machine Thursday at a news
conference at the university's Davis campus, about 15 miles west of
Sacramento, where Bargar is an assistant clinical professor and
Paul is an assistant research veterinarian.
   The robot, which was billed as the first of its kind and is at
least five years from use in hospitals, looks and sounds in its
current phase much like a giant dentist's drill.
   Bargar and Paul developed the computerized mechanical arm to
drill deep holes down through thighbones during hip replacement
surgery so they could slip artificial hip joints inside.
   Currently, surgeons must use a mallet and metal rasp to bore
holes under the socket, at the risk of cracking the leg bone and
getting a poor fit.
   In 1985, Bargar began testing custom-made hip implants that
eliminate the need to take several standard sizes of artificial hip
joints into the operating room and fit the patient during surgery.
   ``So we thought, if a machine can make a prosthesis accurately,
why can't a machine make the same envelope so that (the joint) will
just press in,'' said Paul, who replaces hips in one to two
arthritic dogs every week.
   The better the fit, the surgeons reasoned, the easier the bone
will grow onto the artificial joint and the longer it will last.
   Traditional hip surgery is fine for older, sedentary people, but
younger, active or overweight patients face a 40 percent risk of
having their implants loosen within five years, Bargar said.
   About 120,000 people undergo hip replacement surgery every year.
   In early laboratory tests, Bargar said, the robot drilled with
accuracy up to seven-thousands of an inch, nearly 60 times as
accurate as the hand-held rasp and mallet.
   Such accuracy could be a boon to other surgery, such as removal
of brain tumors or implanting of teeth in the jaw, he said.
   ``We hope it's going to be picked up by oral surgery,
opthmology, neurosurgery,'' said Bargar. ``Each of these
disciplines has some procedure where the accuracy they need is
better than what they can achieve.''
   The researchers stressed that the robot is intended to assist
human surgeons, not replace them.
   ``I initially didn't even want to use the word `robot,' because
I was afraid it would scare people,'' Bargar said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessCelebrity     02-19 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Celebrity,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celebrated Formerly Homeless Woman Lashes Out At New York City
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A formerly homeless woman who challenged
New York City's policy of forcibly hospitalizing mentally ill
street people told a Harvard Law School audience the policy was
more humiliating than helpful.
   ``I will never, never, ever forget what happened to me and what
Mayor (Edward) Koch's program did to me,'' Joyce Brown, 40, said at
a Harvard Law forum.
   Ms. Brown, who also has called herself Billie Boggs, called for
more affordable housing and criticized government programs for the
homeless, particularly New York's Project Help.
   Ms. Brown was the first homeless person picked up under Koch's
program to remove the mentally ill from the streets for treatment.
   A former secretary in New Jersey, Ms. Brown lived for months on
a sidewalk in Manhattan until Oct. 28, when city workers took her
to Bellevue Hospital, where she was kept in a locked psychiatric
ward.
   She protested in court, and on Jan. 19 she was released after a
judge ruled she could not be treated with drugs against her will.
   Ms. Brown said programs like Project Help only exacerbate the
problem of the homeless.
   ``Mayor Koch wants to pick you up, humiliate you, degrade you
and embarrass you by taking you to the hospital and forcing you to
take medication,'' she said.
   Since being released from the hospital, Ms. Brown has moved to a
New York hotel for formerly homeless women where she receives meals
and social services and says she is looking for work. She was
accompanied to Harvard by her two lawyers from the New York Civil
Liberties Union.
   She urged governments to build more housing for people with low
and moderate incomes and described her experiences in shelters for
the homeless as ``not good at all.''
   ``There are murders, theft, rapings,'' she said. ``It is a very
dangerous place to live.''
   Before her speech, she told the New York Post she wishes she had
a family.
   ``If I could pick anything I want to be right now, I'd be
married with children,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
