<DOCNO> AP880219-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessCensus     02-19 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Census,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volunteers Comb Alleys, Check Trash Bins to Count Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed with flashlights, walkie-talkies, and in
some cases, police escorts, more than 100 volunteers took to the
streets and alleys of Boston today to count the number of homeless.
   The 117 census-takers were instructed to look behind buildings
and trash bins, in doorways and all-night movies.
   ``We just about walked every street in the city,'' said Allan
Stern, the city's director of data processing, who will tally the
findings.
   The homeless were recorded by gender and whether adult or child,
but names were not taken. Totals, which will include the number of
homeless who spent the night in shelters and detoxification units,
were to be calculated during the day, with a final analysis
expected in about one week, said Stern.
   The city's first census, conducted last year, found about 2,860
homeless, Stern said.
   Drinking coffee to help them stay awake, the census-takers
gathered before midnight at City Hall. Temperatures hovered around
freezing outside.
   ``It's important to be able to speak with authority,'' Mayor
Raymond Flynn told the group. ``People rely on the city of Boston
for these kinds of figures. When we start making statements about
the homeless population in America, we can speak about it with
actual statistics.''
   Boston is the only city in the country which takes to the
streets to count the homeless, Stern said.
   ``It shows the concern for the issue to have so many people come
out here between the hours of 1 and 3,'' said Richard Weintraub,
34, director of the 360-bed Long Island shelter.
   Most of the volunteers were homeless workers or advocates,
recruited through word-of-mouth and posters. The Boston Fire
Department donated two cars and two drivers, and police escorted
some groups.
   In the Boston's South End, a book and sweater scrunched on top
of a stove in an alcove built of discarded appliances alerted
Weintraub's three-person group to signs of occupancy.
   A quick hop up on the stove and a peek into the makeshift
dwelling found two people fast asleep.
   ``We still don't get all the homeless. There are people hidden
away in buildings we'll just never find,'' Weintraub said.
   The volunteers were told to be inconspicuous and not to disturb
the homeless unless they were in need of assistance.
   At 3 a.m. a man was spotted hobbling on crutches, and the group
radioed for a rescue van, which took him to a shelter, Weintraub
said.
   Weintraub's group finished searching its 30-block area in the
South End at 4 a.m., finding 10 men and one woman.
   ``If we don't find a lot of people on the street, that's
successful,'' he said.
   The city uses the statistics to help determine the number of
beds, resuce vans, food and medical supplies needed to care for the
homeless, said Ann Maquire, executive director of the city's
Emergency Shelter Commission, which organized the survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
