<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Chrysler-Wisconsin     02-19 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Wisconsin,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Will Consider Extending Production At Wisconsin Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp., under fire for planning to
close a plant it acquired in its buyout of American Motors, will
consider a ``modest, short'' extension of production there,
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca says.
   He made the announcement after meeting Thursday in Washington
with Gov. Tommy G. Thompson, who has threatened to have the state
sue Chrysler.
   The meeting ``got very heated'' while Wisconsin officials gave
Iacocca their opinion of Chrysler's plans to close the factory in
Kenosha on Sept. 30 and throw 5,500 people out of work, Thompson
said.
   The state accuses the company of violating a 1987 promise to
maintain production for five years in exchange for $5 million in
job-training funds.
   ``I had some things I wanted to get off my chest,'' the governor
said.
   Iacocca said after the meeting he had agreed to requests by Rep.
Les Aspin, D-Wis., to look elsewhere in the company for work that
might be transferred to Kenosha when production of Omni and Horizon
models ends there.
   ``We don't hold hopes too high but they specifically asked if we
could have a modest, short extension,'' Iacocca said. ``We're going
to look and see if we can seriously do that.''
   Asked if Iacocca meant weeks or months with the term ``modest,
short extension,'' the governor said, ``He didn't put it in those
kinds of terms.''
   While talking to reporters, Iacocca mentioned ``a couple
months.''
   Thompson said talks will continue with Chrysler in hope of
averting a breach-of-contract suit against Chrysler.
   Thompson said he hopes Iacocca's promise to look for new work
for Kenosha can prolong operations for more than a month or two but
realizes ``it's not going to be five years.''
   In a telephone interview from Washington, the governor said the
meeting ``started out very rocky. It got very heated. At times we
thought the meeting was going to break up.''
   ``I reiterated my positions to him about how they treated the
state, the city, the county and the union,'' Thompson said. ``We
are a long way from reaching an agreement (but) it was a positive
meeting.''
   Chrysler denies making a written commitment to maintain
production for five years. Iacocca says company officials are
guilty of nothing more than being ``cockeyed optimists'' in
originally planning to keep the plant open that long.
   When the 86-year-old factory closes, about 1,800 workers would
be eligible for pensions, leaving 3,700 facing unemployment. State
officials say the unemployment rate in the city of 75,000 could
rise past 20 percent.
</TEXT>
