<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Co-Defendant,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Davidow Pleads Innocent in Noriega Drug Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only defendant in U.S. custody of those named
in the drug indictment of Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega pleaded innocent today in federal court.
   Brian Alden Davidow, 26, a student at Florida International
University, had turned himself in to authorities last week, four
days after being indicted for racketeering and drug trafficking
along with Noriega and 14 other people.
   Davidow, free on a $500,000 bond, pleaded innocent to two
indictments in a brief hearing before U.S. Magistrate Linnea
Johnson.
   He could face up to 60 years in prison and fines of $750,000 if
convicted of conspiring with Noriega to smuggle drugs from Panama
to the United States for the Colombia-based Medellin Cartel, which
supplies up to 80 percent of this country's cociane imports.
   According to prosecutors, Davidow is a Miami-based cocaine
distributor who worked with Cesar Rodriguez, Ruben Diario Paredes
Jimenez and others. Davidow allegedly met with Noriega and others
in Panama to arrange transportation of cocaine to Florida, the
indictment says.
   The defendant also entered an innocent plea in a second
indictment accusing him of conspiracy and distribution of cocaine
in 1983 and 1984.
