<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SentencingReforms     02-19 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sentencing Reforms,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Judges Declare New Federal Rules Invalid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal guidelines intended to bring
consistency to sentencing for those who commit federal crimes have
been declared invalid by two U.S. district judges.
   Judge Rudi Brewster concurred Thursday with arguments that the
commission that issued the guidelines violated separation of powers
among government branches.
   Brewster found that the U.S. Sentencing Commission was
unconstitutional because it was placed under the wing of the
judicial branch of government, when the power of that branch is
limited to resolution of cases, not rule-making.
   Shortly after Brewster filed his opinion, Judge John Rhoades
issued a brief order adopting Brewster's findings.
   The rulings came one day after Brewster, Rhoades and six other
federal judges for the Southern District of California heard
arguments on the valididity of the commission created by the
Sentencing Reform Act of 1984.
   The act was intended to bring consistency to sentencings and
affects those who commit federal crimes after Nov. 1, 1987.
   Challenges to the new rules have been filed throughout the
country, but the San Diego hearing was the first to reach trial.
   ``I think it's a well-written opinion and I think it will be
influential,'' said Judy Clarke, executive director of Federal
Defenders of San Diego, which argued against the federal sentencing
mandates.
   It tells district court judges they are not alone in concluding
that an act of Congress is unconstitutional, she said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Roger Haines Jr. said he was
disappointed with the rulings, but predicted that when other judges
rule, the ``government's position will be vindicated.''
   Defense and government attorneys have agreed that constitutional
issues ultimately must be decided by the U.S. Supreme Court. Haines
said Thursday that the Justice Department is investigating the best
strategy for appeal.
   In the meantime, different judges may use different sentencing
standards. Haines said it will cause no practical problems, but
Clarke contends there will be ``chaos'' in the courts.
   The San Diego judges, who normally hear pretrial motions
individually, joined in a time-saving maneuver to hear arguments
raised in eight cases by 16 defendants awaiting trial on offenses
ranging from drug to immigration violations. Rulings from the other
judges are pending.
   The Justice Department and the commission sought to preserve the
new rules, but relied on different arguments.
   Attorney Kenneth Geller, representing the commission, said the
guidelines brought order to the inconsistent sentencing system and
defended the commission as independent of the executive branch.
   Douglass Letter, the Justice Department's appellate litigation
counsel, conceded that there could be constitutional problems
because of the commission's assignment to the judicial branch.
   He said it should have been placed in the executive branch,
under which it could legally execute laws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
