<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Shultz-MiddleEast     02-19 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Middle East,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz `Most Likely' To Visit Syria Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz ``most
likely'' will visit Syria when he goes to the Middle East next week
to weigh prospects for an Arab-Israeli negotiations, a U.S.
official said today.
   Shultz' purpose would be to discuss the situation with President
Hafez Assad, whose support for any long-term sattlement of the
Arab-Israeli dispute is considered essential by experts in the
State Department's Near East Bureau.
   A stop in Damascus would be a major prestige boost to Syria and
mark an improvement in its U.S. relations. The country is one of
six listed by the State Department as a supporter of terrorism. In
November 1986, President Reagan imposed sanctions against Syria.
   Among the punitive measures was a ban on high-level meetings
with Syrians. But Shultz sent Richard W. Murphy, the head of the
Near East bureau, to Damascus two weeks ago to confer with Assad.
   The U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said Shultz was
``most likely'' to schedule a stop in Syria on his trip to the
Middle East beginning next Thursday.
   Another U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said restrictions
on visas for Syrians to visit the United States are likely to be
lifted.
   Ambassador William Eagleton was sent back to his post in
Damascus last September, after a year's absence, and U.N.
Ambassador Vernon A. Walters also visited the country.
   Shultz's other stops will be Egypt, Jordan, Israel and probably
Saudi Arabia. He is trying to set up negotiations between Israel
and a mixed delegation of Jordanians and Palestinians to deal
especially with the troubled West Bank and Gaza.
   The immediate aim is some form of self-rule for the 1.5 million
Palestinian Arabs who have lived under Israeli control since Egypt
and Jordan lost the territories in the 1967 Six-Day war.
   The long-range goal is to hold a second stage of talks _
possibly in the format of an international peace conference _ by
the end of the year to consider an overall settlement.
   Shultz plans to be in the Middle East until March 2 when the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization holds a summit meeting in
Brussels. President Reagan will attend.
   He is making a separate trip to the Soviet Union, starting out
today for Helsinki, Finland. Shultz will be in Moscow for talks
Sunday and Monday, report to the NATO countries in Brussels on
Tuesday and return home for a brief rest before heading for the
Middle East.
</TEXT>
