<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Jews     02-19 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Jews,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Weekly Criticizes 1968 Anti-Semitic Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An influential Communist Party weekly
criticized the official anti-Semitic campaign in 1968 that led to
the flight of most of the country's surviving Jewish population.
   The article in the Feb. 20 issue of the weekly Polityka, seen
today, was the first in an official publication to offer a detailed
account reappraising the 1968 events and referring specifically to
an ``anti-Semitic'' campaign.
   Its publication comes before the 20th anniversary of March 1968
student protests against censorship, which sparked what authorities
then called an ``anti-Zionist'' campaign that led to the dismissal
of thousands of Jews from official posts.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban on Tuesday promised a
``detailed discussion'' of the 1968 crisis in official
publications. The government condemns ``any manifestations of
anti-Semitism, both in the past and at present,'' he said.
   A party source close to Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
said the Polityka article was the first in a series of reappraisals
that will appear in the press, radio and television, including a
major commentary planned for the party's official newspaper Trybuna
Ludu.
   ``This is the time of perestroika (reconstruction) and it is
time to liquidate the mistakes, the black points on the moral
side,'' said the source, requesting anonymity.
   Perestroika describes the social and economic reforms promoted
by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. The Soviet Union has been
re-evaluating its history in a more critical light.
   ``We will take a clear position against anti-Semitism,'' the
source said. ``We want to close this chapter, which was a very
unhappy chapter in our history.''
   In a front-page introduction to a chronology of events connected
with 1968, two Polityka staff members, Wieslaw Wladyka and Zbyslaw
Rykowski, wrote that ``March (1968) has been an embarrassing issue
for 20 years.''
   ``The legacy of March remains: the shame of the anti-Semitic
fuss, the reform of socialism buried for years, the intelligentsia
left at odds with the working class, human damage.''
   They wrote that the crisis was triggered by the failure of
then-Communist Party leader Wladyslaw Gomulka to make basic
political and economic reforms, partially under the influence of
conservative Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev. As the country
stagnated, Gomulka reacted with repressive measures against
reformers and dissident intellectuals.
   They said the ``anti-Semitic syndrome in political thinking''
was part of a power struggle within the party leadership aimed at
unseating Gomulka. His opponents tried to appeal for popular
support with nationalist slogans.
   The anti-Semitic campaign was ignited after the 1967
Arab-Israeli war when some Polish officials and army officers of
Jewish origin were accused of celebrating the Israeli victory over
the Soviet-backed Arab armies.
   But the campaign did not pick up momentum until after the March
1968 student riots, which authorities blamed on ``Zionist
traitors.'' About 9,000 Jews were dismissed from posts in the
party, party, government, army and other institutions.
   The campaign led to the emigration of most of the 30,000 Jews
living in Poland. Before the Nazi Holocaust of World War II, Poland
was home to about 3.5 million Jews, or 10 percent of the population.
   Polityka said the precise number of emigres is unknown, but
cited various estimates saying that 12,000 to 20,000 Jews left
Poland in 1967-69.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0113 </DOCNO>
