<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Portugal-US     02-19 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-US,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Prime Minister Expected To Call For Treaty Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva
likely will call for a review of a treaty allowing the United
States to use a mid-Atlantic air base if Washington refuses a large
increase in aid, a newspaper said today.
   Cavaco Silva planned to visit to Washington next week for talks
with U.S. leaders. The talks are expected to center on a 1983
bilateral accord that gives the United States use of the Lajes Air
Base in the Azores islands.
   Today, the left-of-center Lisbon weekly O Jornal reported
sources close to the government expect ``the Prime Minister will
officially call for a formal review of the (Lajes) agreement if
Washington refuses a substantial increase in aid'' during his U.S.
trip.
   Two weeks ago, U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci paid a
one-day visit to Lisbon to discuss Portuguese complaints over
recent drops in U.S. assistance.
   Carlucci and Portuguese Defense Minister Eurico de Melo
announced after intensive meetings in the Portuguese capital Feb. 3
that both sides had agreed to form a joint task force to study
alternative forms of U.S. aid to Portugal.
   Congressional cuts dropped Washington's military and economic
assistance totals to Portugal from $208 million in 1985 to $117
million for fiscal 1987.
   Carlucci's visit to Lisbon followed months of public complaints
by Cavaco Silva and other Portuguese leaders that the United States
had failed to live up to its pledge in the 1983 base accord to
provide increasing amounts of aid.
   The U.S. State Department announced Thursday the administration
would seek $163 million in aid to Portugal for fiscal 1988, which
begins Oct. 1.
   The United States first received base rights at Lajes in 1951,
and the U.S. presence at the Portuguese-run base on the Azores'
Terceira island has been extended in a series of subsequent accords.
   The latest extension agreement for use of the refuelling depot
and submarine reconnaissance facilities at Lajes was signed in
December 1983, and expires Feb. 4, 1991.
   In a major address Thursday night, Foreign Minister Joao de Deus
Pinheiro reiterated Portugal's strategic role in the Atlantic
alliance but signalled increasing concern in Lisbon over the cuts
in aid.
   ``Portugal proclaims itself the true connecting link between the
American and European pillars'' of NATO, the minister said in a
speech before students of the National Defense Institute at the
northern city of Oporto.
   But the minister said, ``it is only normal'' that Portugal and
the United States ``desire an update'' of their existing bilateral
defense accord in the wake of the recent U.S.-Soviet agreement
removing intermediate-range nuclear weapons from Europe.
   ``The upcoming Portuguese-American negotiations shouldn't be
dramatized,'' he said, because ``our common interests and views far
exceed any possible bilateral difficulties.''
</TEXT>
