<HEAD>Industrialist Axel Ax:son Johnson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ax:son is correct spelling</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Axel Ax:son Johnson, one of Sweden's
leading industrialists, died today in his vacation home in Naples,
Fla., a spokesman for his company said. He was 77.
   Johnson headed Sweden's biggest family-owned conglomerate, the
Axel Johnson Group and Nordstjernan AB, until he retired in 1979,
said the spokeswoman, Elisabeth Bergstrom.
   She said his health had been weak for the past few years, but
did not say why he died. Johnson lived in Stockholm.
   The two industrial groups, with operations in construction,
shipping, stainless steel and trading, have annual revenues of $5
billion and 22,000 employees.
   The Johnson empire was founded by Johnson's late grandfather,
Axel, who founded A. Johnson & Co. in 1873 as a trading company.
The company gradually diversified into two groups which are still
controlled by the family.
   Johnson's only child, Antonia Ax:son Johnson, owns 100 percent
of the Johnson Group, which consists of Axel Johnson AB in Sweden
and Johnson Inc. in the United States. Their combined annual
revenues are about $2.5 billion.
   Johnson's brother Bo Ax:son Johnson is Nordstjernan AB's board
chairman and several close relatives are on the board.
   The Johnson family maintains an old Swedish tradition of
spelling their middle name in an abbreviated form of Axelson.
</TEXT>
