<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeartSurgeons-Copeland     02-19 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heart Surgeons-Copeland,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artificial Heart Pioneer Says Donor Shortage May Lead to Permanent
Implants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The surgeon who pioneered use of the
artificial heart as a ``bridge'' until a human heart can be
obtained for transplant says he is re-examining the idea of
permanent implantation because of a shortage of donor hearts.
   ``I think the bridge-to-transplant scenario becomes less tenable
than it was, and if you're going to get into a bridge to transplant
it better be with a perfect candidate,'' Jack G. Copeland, head of
the University of Arizona's heart transplant and artificial heart
teams, said Thursday.
   In August 1985, Copeland became the first cardiac surgeon to use
an artificial heart successfully as a bridge to transplant. Michael
Drummond was kept alive for nine days on a Jarvik-7
plastic-and-metal pump before receiving a donor organ.
   Copeland has long held that such devices are unsuitable for
permanent implantation in their current state because of
complications, including development of potential stroke-causing
clots, and of infections that inevitably develop over time and
because the patient's lifestyle is hindered by constant tethering
to an immobile drive unit.
   But Copeland said he is rethinking his position because of the
shortage of human donors.
   His comments came during the first day of a three-day conference
on thoracic organ transplantation. Other surgeons attending said
that the more than 100 medical centers now performing heart
transplants in the United State are vying for a constant or even
declining number of donor hearts, estimated at no more than 1,500
annually.
   A candidate for an artificial heart as a bridge ``has to be
perfect in every way, before you commit that much of your resources
and before you put that guy on the top of the list ahead of the
five other people that are in ICU (intensive care unit) waiting for
a heart,'' Copeland said.
   He also said transplant surgeons are ``being pushed by the laws
of supply and demand,'' with the death of many young people from
heart disease, ``toward a relook'' at prolonged circulatory support
with mechanical devices.
   That is happening ``even though we don't have a device that's
really ready for permanent implantation,'' he said. ``I think we're
being pushed toward that as a solution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
