<HEAD>Ski Team Travels to Far North to Begin Trans-Polar Trek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Soviet and four Canadian skiers who plan to
cross the North Pole on skis are finishing up training on Dikson
Island in the far north of the Soviet Union and plan to depart
March 1, it was reported Friday.
   The official Tass news agency said the group arrived at Dikson
on Thursday and that final preparations for the 1,240-mile ski trip
were under way.
   Earlier this week, Laurie Dexter of the Canadian team said the
group's departure from Moscow had been delayed because some
equipment and food was lost. Tass did not indicate whether the
supplies had been found or replaced.
   The skiers will travel in about a week to Cape of the Arctic,
the northernmost point of the Severnaya Zemlya archipelago that
stretches into the Arctic Ocean.
   From there, they will set out on the trek, which is expected to
last 100 days.
   Tass said the skiers would carry 99-pound backpacks. The
expedition is to conclude at Cape Columbia in Canada.
</TEXT>
