<HEAD>Motley Crue Offers Sympathy To Boy Burned Trying To Copy Group's
Video Stunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy-metal rockers Motley Crue offered
condolences to the 12-year-old who set his legs on fire while
trying to imitate a stunt shown on one of the group's music videos.
   Bryan Tucker, who had burns over 10 percent of his body, was
reported in good condition Friday at Memorial Hospital.
   ``The members of Motley Crue are very sorry to learn that a
young fan was injured trying to copy the `human torch' stunt as
seen on the Live Wire video taped in 1982,'' said the statement
released Thursday by management firm McGhee Entertainment Inc. in
Los Angeles.
   ``Various of Motley Crue's show stunts require special
equipment, clothing and other materials ... and should not be
attempted at home. Fire stunts are especially dangerous,'' the
statement said.
   Bryan's mother, Wendy Tucker, said he was in great pain but that
Motley Crue was not to blame for her son's experiment at their home
Wednesday.
   ``In my day, my mom would not let me watch Superman, because he
jumped out of buildings,'' she said. ``It's just a different time.
If you think, some of these cartoons are really rough. It didn't
start with rock videos.''
   Tucker, who takes electric guitar lessons and wears an earring
in the shape of a cross, is known around Apollo Middle School as a
``headbanger,'' or heavy-metal rock fan, friends said.
   The boy poured rubbing alcohol on his jeans and torched them. He
put the flames out in a filled bathtub.
</TEXT>
