<HEAD>Man Linked To 5 Bank Robberies Found Dead After Siege</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought in five bank robberies in the San
Diego area, including three committed in one day, was tracked to an
apartment where he barricaded himself before apparently committing
suicide, the FBI said.
   The man, identified as William Patrick McGrovern, 43, was found
dead inside his San Diego apartment Thursday night, said FBI
special agent James Bolenbach.
   ``Apparently he had shot himself shortly after barricading
himself in the apartment,'' Bolenbach said. No hostages were taken,
and no one else was injured.
   FBI agents and police officers from San Diego and El Cajon
staked out McGrovern's apartment Thursday after tracing a license
plate number on a getaway car used in one of three robberies that
same day.
   A bank in El Cajon and two in San Diego were robbed within a
1{-hour period and police and FBI investigators found that the same
person was responsible, Bolenbach said.
   When the officers attempted to arrest McGrovern, he fired a shot
and fled into his apartment.
   ``Throughout the afternoon, further attempts to contact him and
negotiate received no response,'' Bolenbach said.
   Officers heard a single shot at about 5 p.m., and when they
entered about three hours later they found McGrovern dead of a
gunshot wound, he said. Several weapons, ammunition and an unknown
amount of money were found in the apartment.
   McGrovern also is suspected of robbing a bank in Escondido and
one in Poway last month, Bolenbach said.
   It is not believed that McGrovern had any accomplices, he said.
The FBI did not disclose the amount of money taken in the five
robberies.
