<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarriageFlap     02-19 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marriage Flap,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marriage Certificate Sparks Church-and-State Spat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traditional keepsake certificate that
McLean County has been giving to newlyweds is pitting clergy
against one another in a debate over the separation of church and
state.
   The controversy also has sparked an angry response from the
public, including threatening phone calls to public officials,
ministers and others involved.
   At issue is the religious nature of the elaborate certificates,
which declare a couple united in ``holy matrimony, ordained by
God.'' They also bear a Bible passage from the book of Matthew.
   ``I think it's inappropriate for the county to be distributing
religious materials,'' said David Robins, minister at the Unitarian
Church of Bloomington.
   Robins says the keepsake is a Christian document and that its
distribution by the county displays a lack of sensitivity toward
religious minorities who don't share the same beliefs.
   He said the county should leave such religious keepsakes to the
churches rather than involve government in the issue.
   ``I realize I'm a religious minority in a Christian society and
I'm sorry if this curtails the pleasure of the majority of the
people in the county,'' Robins said. ``But I just think this is an
inappropriate activity for the county to be involved in.''
   Robins enlisted the support of Rabbi Clifford Librach of the
Moses Montefiore Temple in Bloomington, and together they
complained to the county.
   McLean County Clerk Jeanette Barrett decided to end distribution
of the keepsakes on the advice of Eric Ruud, assistant state's
attorney.
   However, that brought about 50 angry phone calls to the clerk's
office, as well as several ``vicious, venomous'' calls to Ruud and
Robins, Librach said.
   ``We've decided to give them their choice,'' Mrs. Barrett said.
``I'm going to issue one without all the religious references. If
they don't want either one, they don't have to take one.
   ``I think people should have a choice. They don't think the
county should be in the religion business. But I don't think we've
done anything wrong.''
   Robins and Librach think Mrs. Barrett is missing the point. They
don't think it's proper for the county to hand out any religious
certificates, whether Christian, Unitarian or Jewish.
   ``If the majority of the people in McLean County were Jewish,
I'd be offended if the county issued a Jewish-style keepsake,''
Librach said.
   The Rev. Ron R. Lee, pastor of St. John's Lutheran Church, said
his church strongly supports the separation of church and state
government.
   ``Freedom of religion means each group is allowed to pursue its
own beliefs in a free and open environment,'' Lee said. ``The
government does not promote religion. Any document the government
produces should be free of religious statements.''
   Ralph E. Wingate, pastor at the Calvary Baptist Church,
disagreed with Robins, Librach and Lee.
   ``The whole thing is ridiculous to me,'' Wingate said. ``They
might have an argument about espousing the Bible, but I think it's
a non-issue.''
   Librach said the keepsakes go further than a simple ``In God We
Trust'' as appears on U.S. currency.
   ``These certificates contain excerpts from the Gospel of Matthew
and clearly are Christian documents,'' he said. ``It's a violation
of the Constitution. We may have to look to the courts, where I
have no doubt as to what the decision will be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
