<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RottenRow     02-19 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rotten Row,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Riding Path to Be Restored to Former Glory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rotten Row, which is said to be the world's oldest
urban horseriding path, may get back its bollards and railings 47
years after they were ripped out for the World War II effort.
   The Rotten Row Tercentenary Committee, set up to restore the
bridle path to its former glory by its 300th anniversary in 1991,
launched an appeal Friday for $260,000 to finance the fence.
   The mile-long sandy path through Hyde Park in central London
will be lined on each side with 1,000 cast-iron bollards linked by
metal railings.
   Major donors will have their names inscribed on the black,
3-foot high bollards, said committee chairman Neil Mitchell.
   Built by King William III and originally called the King's Road,
the path stretched four miles from Westminster to Kensington Palace
and was the first continuously lighted thoroughfare in Britain.
   Scholars have never agreed on the origin of the name Rotten Row.
   Some trace it to ``route du roi,'' French for king's road.
Others say it comes from ``rotteran,'' a German verb meaning to
muster, because it was used for military parades.
   Today it is open to any horserider free of charge and is part of
a network of bridle paths used as a basis for designing Central
Park in New York.
   Mitchell said he has invited the Claremont Riding Academy in New
York to join in the tercentenary ceremonies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
