<HEAD>NEWARK, N.J.: legal team.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Jan. 11 let stand a federal judge's
decision freeing Carter, who had served 19 years of a life term.
The judge found Carter's conviction was tainted by racism and by
prosecutors witholding information from the defense.
   The ruling left to the Passaic County prosecutor's office the
decision on whether to seek another trial for Carter and Artis,
whose convictions were first overturned by the New Jersey Supreme
court before a 1976 retrial.
   Defense attorneys had considered a third trial unlikely because
the eyewitness testimony had been so discredited during appeals.
   Goceljak made the decision on a third trial in consultation with
the state's director of criminal justice, Donald R. Belsole.
   Belsole had said the decision would be based in part on the
state of 22-year-old evidence and ``the impact of another trial on
society.''
