<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UCEnrollment     02-19 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UC Enrollment,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UC System Faces Admissions Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of California faces a
growing admissions crisis that threatens to set black, white,
Hispanic and Asian students competing against one another for
admission, officials said.
   Three years into the system's 15-year growth plan, enrollment
has already reached levels predicted for 1995, and the university
could be forced for the first time to turn away qualified high
school graduates, the Board of Regents said at a special meeting
Thursday.
   The university has 140,000 undergraduates on its nine campuses.
   Part of the reason for the soaring applications is the
university's success at recruiting minority applicants, said
university President David P. Gardner.
   ``There needs to be very strong leadership by the regents and
the administration to reduce the growing tension between
affirmative action and ... the concerns among white students over
their declining enrollment at the university,'' said Henry Der, a
member of the Asian-American Task Force on University Admissions.
   Der, one of a panel of educational leaders that addressed the
regents, has accused the Berkeley campus of setting informal quotas
denying admission to Asian students, who have been gaining entrance
in greater and greater numbers during the past decade.
   He predicted such policies will lead to ``political and social
wars'' if uniform admission standards are not adopted throughout
the system.
   ``We have to ask whether this university is ready to let Asian
and white students compete on a color-blind basis,'' said Der.
   The regents discussed raising entrance requirements but that
could further widen the gap between the percentages of black and
Hispanic students enrolled compared to whites, they said.
   Five percent of Hispanic high school graduates and about 4
percent of blacks meet entrance requirements consisting of a
combination of high school courses, a 3.3 grade point average and
Scholastic Aptitude test results. This compares to 15 percent of
white students and 32 percent of Asian graduates, according to
figures compiled by the California Post Secondary Education
Commission.
</TEXT>
