<1ST_LINE>r p AM-HomelessVoters     02-19 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Voters,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Not Sought as Voters Although They Make Up Large Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The homeless, a group of Americans with a
major stake in the outcome of this year's election, may find
themselves unable to exercise much political muscle at the polls.
   These cold and hungry people have attracted added attention this
year as their growing visibility on city streets has brought them
before both voters and those seeking votes.
   A recent survey by a coalition of national organizations found
that most voters believe helping the hungry and homeless should be
one of the top priorities of the next administration.
   But while the poll called on politicians to give some attention
to the homeless, the question remains whether the homeless can
return the attention on election day.
   Theoretically they could make up a significant bloc.
   Estimates of the number of homeless Americans vary widely, from
the 360,000 reported in a 1986 economic research study to up to 3
million claimed by some advocacy groups.
   ``It's a very difficult number to get at, because it's a
difficult population to count,'' said James Stimpson of the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Whatever their number, it's not likely that many will be able to
sign up and cast ballots.
   In general, registration and voting hinges on residence and the
rules vary widely from state to state, according to Craig Donsanto
of the Justice Department.
   In states such as Mississippi, the rules can be very strict,
while in some other parts of the country anyone who can show up at
the polls may be able to vote, Donsanto explained through a
department spokesman.
   In places like New York City, for example, the homeless can use
a shelter for an address, while others may even be able to list a
grate on a street corner as their usual place of residence, he said.
   The question for New York homeless was settled by a federal
court ruling in 1984, said Bill Kimberling of the Federal Election
Commission.
   He said the ruling requires the state to allow people to
register to vote even if homeless. They must list an address where
mail can be sent, he said, but that can be a shelter or some other
location where people agree to hold the mail for them.
   Their residence can then be listed as a separate place, wherever
they are usually to be found, he added.
   While that court case established the homeless' right to vote in
New York, Beth Gorey of that city's office of the National
Coalition for the Homeless, said she was unable to estimate how
many may have done so.
   ``We do take advantage of opportunities to encourage them to
register, at meetings and so forth, and we always provide voter
registration cards. But we don't know how many have'' registered,
she said.
   Tim Hager of the coalition's Washington office said voting
registration efforts also have been undertaken in Washington and
some other areas, but he had few details.
   Chris Sprowal of the Philadelphia-based National Union of the
Homeless said that outside of major cities such as New York,
Chicago, Philadelphia and a few others, homeless people generally
find themselves barred from voting.
   ``For the most part, if they would go in and say, `I stay on the
river' or `in a cardboard box' they would be denied the right to
vote. They have to lie and give a residence,'' he commented.
   Sprowal said his group is planning a meeting in Atlanta to
discuss launching a nationwide fight for voting for homeless people.
   An added problem is the near-homeless, pointed out Linda
Davidoff of the group Human Serve.
   Many people are doubled up in tight housing markets, living with
friends or relatives in violation of leases, she commented. If they
register and turn up on voter lists at the address where they are
living, the landlord could then evict them, she said, resulting in
these people being disenfranchised just like the homeless.
   Despite their reportedly large numbers, at least in major
cities, there are ``not a lot of aggressive efforts to organize''
the homeless into voting blocs, said Keith Summa of the Coalition
for the Homeless Atlanta Office.
   Deborah Livingston of the Churches Committee for Voter
Registration said a drive was conducted in New York and there have
been smaller efforts in other cities.
   But neither major political party and none of the presidential
campaigns is currently targeting formal registration drives at the
homeless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
