<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArtsEducation     02-19 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arts Education,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Center Honors Public School Superintendents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kennedy Center honored seven public school
superintendents Friday for outstanding arts education programs.
   The seven are: Donald S. Bruno of the Newport News, Va.,
schools; Ralph Downs of Putnam City School District in Oklahoma
City; LaRuth Gray of Abbott Union Free School District in
Irvington, N.Y.; Robert Henley of the Independence, Mo., schools;
Chris L. Huber of Independent School District No. 16 of Spring Lake
Park, Minn.; Thomas Marx of Maine School Administrative District
No. 28 in Camden, Maine., and Robert E. Walton of Fayette County
schools in Lexington, Ky.
   The awards were being presented Friday night to the
superintendents by the center's Alliance for Arts Education at the
American Association of School Administrators' convention in Las
Vegas.
   Among the highlights of arts education program in each of the
winning districts were:
   _Newport News has established a six-week summer enrichment
program in the arts, and an art magnet program for high school
students.
   _The Postal Service is considering drawings from two
first-graders at Tulakes Elementary School in a competition for a
future postage stamp, and another elementary student's drawing
served as the state's Christmas seal.
   _The Abbott Union schools use the arts to bolster instruction
for at-risk youngsters in primary and secondary schools.
   _The Independence, Mo., schools sponsor a Michelangelo Project
of art lessons for talented youngsters from low-income families and
also help expose students to ballet, theater, symphonies and
museums through a program called Art Partners.
   _District No. 16 in Spring Lake Park, Minn., employs a visual
arts curriculum for grades K-6 and an artist-in-residence.
   _District No. 28 in Camden, Me., has added staff to all arts
departments and given students in the rural area access to a
mini-theater, music facility, acoustically renovated gym and visual
arts facility.
   _The Fayette County schools in Lexington, Ky., have visual arts
specialists who instruct all elementary students one hour each
week; it also has an ``Arts in Basic Education'' program to
integrate music, drama, visual arts and movement with other
subjects.
</TEXT>
