<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathRowTestimony     02-19 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Row Testimony,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resentencing Jury Hears From Convicted Killers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convicted killers took the witness
stand today to testify that an inmate trying to escape the death
penalty had loaned them money and had been kind and friendly in
prison.
   Darrell Edwin Hoy and Arthur Rutherford were among eight current
or former death-row convicts brought from Florida State Prison near
Starke to testify about the character of James Ernest Hitchcock, 31.
   Hitchcock was convicted and sentenced to death 10 years ago for
the murder of his 13-year-old step-niece.
   The U.S. Supreme Court overturned his sentence and ordered the
circuit court to hold a new sentencing hearing to determine if he
will die in the electric chair or receive life in prison.
   Hoy and Rutherford were brought into court today singly in
handcuffs, shackles and blue prison uniforms. They were seated in
the witness stand before the jury was brought in.
   Prosecutors asked the inmates their feelings on the death
penalty.
   ``I feel that's wrong for certain reasons, if I may say so,''
said Hoy, whose death sentence for the 1975 slayings of two
teen-agers was changed to life in prison.
   Rutherford, who faces electrocution for a 1986 murder, agreed.
   ``I'm in Florida State Prison on hearsay, no evidence, no
nothing,'' said Rutherford. ``I'm against it.''
   Both described how Hitchcock had loaned them money for canteen
items. Hoy said the defendant had given him his own radio after
Hoy's was stolen. He also said Hitchcock helped him study for a
General Education Degree.
   Hitchcock spent more than a decade in a one-man cell just a few
feet from Florida's electric chair for the 1976 rape and
strangulation of Cynthia Driggers.
   The jury now is getting a shortened version of trial testimony
and hearing more than 20 witnesses testify for and against
Hitchcock in his effort to escape death.
   The jury recommendation _ life or death _ is only advisory to
Circuit Judge Gary L. Formet Sr.
   Extraordinary security was in force at the Orange County
Courthouse as a result of the appearance of the inmates. Six of
them are awaiting electrocution; two have had their sentences
reduced to life in prison.
   Defense attorneys, who argued successfully for their appearance,
pointed out that they knew Hitchcock well because they lived near
him for more than a third of his life.
   The jury also heard a tape-recorded confession by Hitchcock in
which he admitted the raping and killing. He later recanted,
claiming the confession was given under duress because he was held
for four days in solitary confinement.
</TEXT>
