<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap 6thLd-Writethru a0642 02-19 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0642,0928</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oppressed of Earth Faction Claims Kidnapping of U.S. Marine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that group accused Higgins of
using leadership to mask undercover work for CIA, sted `his'
undercover work. Pick up 3rd pvs, `U.S. State...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Iranian group said today it kidnapped
a U.S. Marine colonel serving with the U.N. peacekeeping force in
south Lebanon and released identity cards bearing his photograph.
   The Oppressed of the Earth accused Lt. Col. William R. Higgins,
43, of using his leadership of a group attached to the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon to mask undercover work for the CIA.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charles Redman denied Thursday
that Higgins had any links with the CIA.
   In a rescue attempt, Shiite Amal militiamen today seized six
activists of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the
southern port of Tyre. The Amal sealed off a 300-square-mile area.
   The Amal, the main Shiite militia in Lebanon, is headed by
Lebanese Justice Minister Nabih Berri. It has fighting Hezbollah
for control of southern Lebanon.
   The claim by Oppressed of the Earth was made in a typed
Arabic-language statement delivered to a Western news agency in
Beirut. It was accompanied by two identity cards, one in English
and one in Hebrew.
   Both bore photographs of Higgins, a native of Danville, Ky., and
what appeared to be his signature.
   It was the second claim of responsibility for Wednesday's
abduction. The first was made by a previously unknown group calling
itself the Islamic Revolutionary Brigades.
   ``William Higgins, agent of the Central Intelligence Agency who
uses his U.N. observer's work as a cover for his dangerous
espionage role, is in the hands of our heroic Mujahedeen (Holy
Warriors),'' the statement said.
   The group said it would release Higgins following a complete
Israeli withdrawal from its security zone in south Lebanon. It also
demanded the release of an estimated 300 Lebanese and Palestinian
prisoners held in Khiam detention camp in south Lebanon and the
immediate cessation of U.S. activity in Lebanon.
   Oppressed of the Earth is believed made up of Shiite Moslem
zealots loyal to Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   It has claimed responsibility for hijackings, bombings and and
kidnappings including the abduction of 12 Lebanese Jews in Moslem
west Beirut since 1984, eight of whom it said it killed.
   Oppressed of the Earth also claims to have staged the June 1985
hijacking of a TWA jetliner in which a U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   During the hijacking, the captors demanded Israel free several
hundred Arabs it held. Although Israel denied any deal was made,
prisoners were released in batches in the weeks that followed the
Americans' release.
   In Washington, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said today U.S.
officials are studying whether Americans should be withdrawn from
the U.N. observer group in light of Higgins' abduction.
   But later, President Reagan said Americans will not be
withdrawn. ``No. We are going to meet our obligations to the United
Nations,'' he said during a White House photo session.
   Carlucci, appearing on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, said
``everything possible'' is being done to secure Higgins' release.
   Higgins, a decorated Vietnam veteran, heads a 76-man observer
group that operates along the Lebanon-Israel border and has its
headquarters in Jerusalem.
   He was kidnapped by gunmen as he was driving from Tyre to UNIFIL
headquarters in the border town of Naqoura. At the time he was
violating U.N. rules for travel by Americans.
   An Amal spokesman said the Hezbollah fundamentalists were
rounded up in pre-dawn raids on houses in the port city.
   ``We suspect they were monitoring Higgins' movements in Tyre
before his abduction. They will be interrogated,'' said the
spokesman, who refused to be identified.
   ``We want Higgins back and we have no red line as far as his
case is concerned,'' Amal's military commander, Daoud Daoud, said
Thursday.
   Today, Daoud told reporters: ``We have clear clues about the
identity of the kidnappers. We're still optimistic.'' He did not
elaborate.
   The comment came after a 30-minute meeting between Amal's
military, security and political chiefs in Tyre and senior UNIFIL
commanders.
   The abduction brings the number of foreign hostages in Lebanon
to 25, including nine Americans. Most are believed held by
pro-Iranian Shiite extremists.
   On Thursday, a man speaking Arabic telephoned a Western news
agency in Beirut, said the Islamic Revolutionary Brigades had
kidnapped Higgins and accused him of being a CIA agent. He did not
identify himself.
   When Higgins was seized, he was violating U.N. rules for travel
by Americans in dangerous areas, UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel
said. But, the spokesman added, the colonel ``felt he couldn't
abide by these restrictions.
   ``Higgins felt that as chief, he should be out with his men and
know what they are doing.''
   American members of U.N. forces are restricted to the
headquarters area and are permitted to travel in Lebanon only with
a U.N. military escort, he said.
   Higgins was the third U.N. official kidnapped in Lebanon this
month.
   The other two, a Swede and Norwegian of the U.N. Relief and
Works Agency, were seized Feb. 5. After that abduction, the U.N.
put plans to revive a development program in Lebanon on hold.
   Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the longest held of all the hostages. He was
abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
