<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LungTransplants     02-19 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lung Transplants,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Specialists Say Lung Transplants Still Years Behind Heart
Replacements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The surgeon who has performed the largest
number of successful lung transplants says the procedure is at a
stage comparable to that of heart transplantation 10 years ago.
   Since 1983, Dr. Joel D. Cooper, chief of thoracic surgery at the
University of Toronto and Toronto General Hospital, has performed
15 single-lung and seven double-lung transplants.
   Of the single-lung patients, 11 are long-term survivors,
including the world's longest-living at 4{ years, and six of the
seven two-lung recipients are still living.
   About 10 or 11 other double-lung transplants and six single-lung
procedures have been attempted elsewhere during the same time, said
Cooper, who also has done heart-lung transplants.
   He said lung transplantation is no more difficult than heart
transplantation, ``just different.''
   ``The next five years will tell us how to use these transplants:
singles, doubles, heart-lungs,'' Cooper said Thursday, the first
day of a three-day international conference on thoracic organ
transplantation.
   Dr. Kathryn A. Hale, a pulmonologist at the University of
Minnesota, said she hopes the next three to five years will bring
lung transplantation ``to the stage where it is no longer
considered experimental.''
   Cooper said heart transplantation clearly has ``hit the end of
phase one. Clearly there will have to be more education'' to
increase the availability of donor organs.
   And ``there will have to be other strategies developed,''
including such approaches as the use of animal organ grafts, to
increase the number of transplants, he said.
   Dr. William A. Baumgartner of Johns Hopkins University, who last
year performed a ``domino donor'' transplant in which a cystic
fibrosis sufferer received the heart and lungs of a brain-dead
donor after his own heart was donated to a second recipient, said
that operation, and a second, have shown the procedure works.
   Part of the reason for the double-organ procedure was a belief
that a heart-lung transplant was easier and safer than a straight
lung transplant.
   ``As these transplants evolve, there's going to be a role for
all of these procedures,'' unilateral lung, double lung, heart-lung
and domino donor, he said.
   He said the domino donor procedure is one ``that can be done
with good results.''
   But Cooper said ``it's probably not good science'' in the sense
that lungs now can be transplanted without the heart being removed,
and the domino donor procedure ``may be a ripple of the past.''
   Cooper called the first Johns Hopkins domino donor procedure
last May ``high drama'' because of the news coverage it engendered,
but he said he feels it is best to leave the lung recipient with
his own heart whenever possible.
   Cooper said he was not trying to be critical of the Johns
Hopkins team, but that he viewed the procedure from his perspective
as a lung transplanter.
</TEXT>
