<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessSearch     02-19 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Search,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volunteers Search Alleys And Trash Bins For Homeless Census</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volunteers armed with flashlights, walkie-talkies
and, in some cases, police escorts combed the city's streets and
alleys early Friday in an effort to find out exactly how many
people have nowhere to call home.
   In the city's South End, a book and sweater in an alcove built
of discarded appliances alerted a volunteer to the presence of
life. A quick peek into the makeshift dwelling found two people
fast asleep.
   They were left undisturbed while three volunteers recorded them
by gender and approximate age.
   Similar groups throughout the city gathered such information to
be compiled into what the city believes is the country's only
hands-on homeless count. A similar attempt in January to quantify
the number of homeless in Pennsylvania tallied only those in
shelters.
   Boston's first such count, conducted last year, found about
2,860 homeless people.
   The volunteers took a census of shelter occupants Thursday
night, then headed into the streets at midnight to look for others
occupying makeshift accommodations.
   ``It's important to be able to speak with authority'' about the
extent of homelessness, Mayor Raymond Flynn told the 117 volunteers
before they set out in the freezing night.
   ``People rely on the city of Boston for these kinds of
figures,'' he said. ``When we start making statements about the
homeless population in America, we can speak about it with actual
statistics.''
   The city uses the statistics to help determine how much food,
beds, rescue vans and medical supplies are needed to care for the
homeless, said Ann Maquire, executive director of the city's
Emergency Shelter Commission, which organized the survey.
   The volunteers were given maps outlining their assigned search
areas.
   ``We just about walk every street in the city,'' said Allan
Stern, the city's director of data processing who is charged with
compiling the statistics. Rough numbers are expected this weekend
and a final analysis is expected in about one week, he said.
   ``It shows the concern for the issue to have so many people come
out here between the hours of 1 and 3'' in the morning, said
Richard Weintraub, 34, director of the 360-bed Long Island shelter.
   The Boston Fire Department donated two cars and two drivers.
Police in the downtown area introduced the census-takers at roll
call, alerting officers that people would be poking through the
district's nooks and crannies on a legitimate city mission.
   Most of the volunteers were people who regularly work with the
homeless and were recruited through word-of-mouth and posters.
Their experience proved an asset to the thoroughness of the count.
   One man walking slowly down a South End street hardly appeared
to be homeless, but Weintraub recognized him from one of the
shelters. He was included in the count.
   ``We still don't get all the homeless. There are people hidden
away in buildings we'll just never find,'' Weintraub said.
   The volunteers were told to be inconspicuous and not to disturb
people unless they needed help. At 3 a.m., a man was spotted
hobbling on crutches and the volunteers radioed for a rescue van,
which took him to shelter, Weintraub said.
   Weintraub's group finished searching its 30-block area in the
South End at 4 a.m., finding 10 men and one woman.
   ``If we don't find a lot of people on the street, that's
success,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
