<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CarterAppeal 1stLd-Writethru a0648-651-652 02-19 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carter Appeal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648-651-652,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Won't Try Rubin `Hurricane' Carter A Third Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines series, updating with new comments. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey has decided not to try Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter a third time for murder, ending the former
boxer's 22-year legal saga, a prosecutor said today.
   John Goceljak, acting prosecutor in Passaic County, said the
decision was based on the long period of time since the 1966
murders, the unavailability of witnesses, the likely exclusion of
the only eyewitness testimony and the decision by a federal judge
that Carter's conviction was racially tainted.
   Goceljak said his office today was filing a motion in Superior
Court in Paterson to dismiss the indictment against Carter and John
Artis, accused of being his accomplice.
   Goceljak said the decision was made in consultation with the
state's criminal justice director, Donald R. Belsole.
   ``It's not a relief,'' said Belsole, ``it's the way the system
works. It's the right thing to do. It's time now to close the book
on the case.''
   A judge must sign the motion to finalize dismissal of the
indictment, and attorney Myron Beldock, in a statement on behalf of
Carter and Artis, said he hoped for quick consideration by the
court.
   ``We are extremely pleased with the decision of the state of New
Jersey to dismiss the case against our clients, and hope that the
appropriate orders will be signed promptly,'' said Beldock.
   On Jan. 11, the U.S. Supreme Court let stand a federal judge's
ruling that cleared Carter. The lower-court judge found Carter's
conviction was tainted by racism and by prosecutors withholding
information from the defense. Carter had been free on bail pending
appeal after serving 19 years of a life prison term.
   The Supreme Court ruling left to the Passaic County prosecutor's
office the decision on whether to seek another trial for Carter and
his alleged accomplice, whose first convictions were overturned by
the New Jersey Supreme court before a 1976 retrial.
   Defense attorneys all along had considered a third trial
unlikely because the eyewitness testimony had been so discredited
during appeals.
   Carter, a former middleweight contender now 50, has been living
in seclusion since being freed by U.S. District Judge H. Lee
Sarokin in 1985.
   His cause was taken up by Bob Dylan, who wrote and sang ``The
Ballad of Hurricane'' in the 1970s, actress Ellen Burstyn, boxer
Muhammed Ali, singer Joan Baez and others who elevated Carter as a
symbol of racial injustice.'
   But after a few highly publicized fund-raising events _ some
touched by scandal _ Carter's all-star backing faded.
   The legal odyssey began on a hot night June 17, 1966, when two
black gunmen entered the Lafayette Bar and Grill in Paterson and
killed the bartender and two patrons. Hours earlier, a black
Paterson bartender had been shot to death by a white man.
   Carter and Artis were arrested three months later and convicted
by an all-white jury in May 1967.
   But two witnesses later recanted, saying they had been pressured
by detectives into giving false testimomny at the trial, and the
case was reopened in 1974. The state Supreme Court threw out the
first verdict in 1976.
   The state put Carter and Artis back on trial and they were
convicted again in 1976, in part with the testimony of one of the
recanting witnesses who retracted claims he was coerced. This time,
the state's highest court upheld the convictions by a 4-3 vote in
1982.
   The case went to federal court and Sarokin found that the 1976
convictions were tainted by ``racial stereotyping, fear and
prejudice,'' and by the defense not having the full results of a
lie detector test given to one of the recanting witnesses.
</TEXT>
