<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mofford 1stLd-Writethru a0538 02-19 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mofford, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham, Mofford Clash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 5th, `The Republican-controlled...' to
update with Rhodes announcing candidacy. Picks up 6th graf pvs,
`Mecham's letter...'
^By LARRY LOPEZ</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Impeached Gov. Evan Mecham says acting
Gov. Rose Mofford is replacing his administration before the Senate
can decide whether to remove him permanently, but a Mofford aide
said she has ``bent over backward'' to be fair.
   ``May I ask you to recognize that I have only been accused and
not convicted of any act,'' Mecham said Thursday in a letter to
Mofford. The embattled Republican also demanded that Mofford
forward all his mail unopened.
   ``I must convey my deep disappointment and surprise at the way
your people are turning a temporary acting governorship into a
complete disruption and replacement of my administration,'' Mecham
said.
   The Republican-controlled House impeached Mecham on charges he
concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 in state money
and obstructed justice. His impeachment trial in the Senate is
scheduled to start Feb. 29. He also faces a criminal trial in March
in connection with the campaign loan.
   Mecham also faces a recall election May 17, and today former
U.S. Rep. John Rhodes, a Republican, announced he would be a
candidate.
   ``Our state needs effective gubernatorial leadership to help our
legislators solve our problems,'' said Rhodes, 71, who retired from
Congress in 1982. ``We cannot afford continued paralysis.''
   Mecham is guaranteed a spot on the recall ballot, and the only
other major announced candidate is Carolyn Warner, a Democrat who
lost to Mecham in 1986 in a three-way race. About 80 people have
picked up packets to collect the 3,336 petition signatures that are
needed by March 18 to get on the ballot.
   Mecham's letter came as Mrs. Mofford, a Democratic secretary of
state who became acting governor upon Mecham's impeachment,
accepted the resignation of Washington lobbyist Fred Craft.
   Last week, Mecham urged Mrs. Mofford to retain Craft, who has
helped Arizona lobby for the federal superconducting super collider
and rented part of his law offices for use by Arizona. Craft
tendered his resignation Feb. 11.
   Mecham's efforts to use Craft on the superconducting super
collider and other issues were controversial and stirred
allegations that he had tried to get around the state procurement
code.
   Mrs. Mofford issued a statement Thursday, saying, ``Members of
the (Arizona) congressional delegation have promised to continue to
be especially vigilant with the issues facing Arizona, especially
the supercollider.''
   Mecham's letter criticized the way mail has been handled since
his impeachment.
   ``What I protest the most is the sudden ordering of the mail
room staff to vacate Tuesday afternoon,'' he wrote.
   ``I realize that your people said that mail marked PERSONAL OR
CONFIDENTIAL would not be opened but I insist that all mail
addressed to me is to be forwarded without opening,'' he wrote.
   Mrs. Mofford's chief of staff, Andy Hurwitz, confirmed that
state Department of Administration officials were brought in to
handle the mail but said he would be willing to work out further
compromises if needed.
   ``We have, I think, bent over backward to try and accommodate
him,'' Hurwitz said of Mecham, noting that only those who offered
resignations had actually been let go.
   Acting Mofford press secretary Athia Hardt said Mecham aide
Bonnie Simons and her aides were reassigned after Ms. Simons took
the position that any mail addressed to office of the governor
should go to Mecham first.
   Much of the mail requires immediate action and ``it would be
irresponsible for us to bundle it up and send it off to Glendale,''
Ms. Hardt said, referring to the suburban offices Mecham has
referred to as his government-in-exile.
</TEXT>
