<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     02-19 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Alliance Calls For Probe of Aquino Governemnt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist social action group on
Friday called for an international investigation of human rights
violations by President Corazon Aquino's government.
   The Philippine Alliance of Human Rights Advocates said it was
filing a petition Friday asking the Geneva-based United Nations
Human Rights Commission to investigate Mrs. Aquino's human rights
record.
   The petition, copies of which were released at a news
conference, alleges that ``human rights violations have increased
under the Aquino government.'' It asks that the commission condemn
the Aquino and U.S. governments for allegedly abetting them.
   There was no immediate comment from the Aquino government.
Military officials had earlier denied allegations of human rights
violations and said they were concocted by communist rebels and
their supporters.
   The Philippines' House of Representatives is investigating
charges that some of the 20 alleged rebel leaders arrested in raids
early this month had been tortured.
   The alliance is an umbrella organization of church-affiliated
human rights groups which the military claims are infiltrated by
members of the rebel New People's Army.
   In its petition, the alliance cited specific allegations of
abuses, including extra-judicial executions and torture of
suspected rebels, bombing of civilians, forced evacuation of rural
villagers and use of armed civilian anti-communist vigilantes.
   It said it included the United States in the petition because
the U.S. government ``has intensified its intervention in the
counter-insurgency program of the Aquino government.''
   Judge Maximiano Asuncion of the regional trial court in suburban
Quezon City said the trial of 20 alleged rebel leaders will begin
next month. Six of the defendants pleaded innocent to charges of
illegal possession of firearms.
   In a televised interview after the arraignment, Asuncion said he
supports a proposal that trials of rebels be conducted by military
tribunals instead of the civil courts because the military is in a
better position to handle possible reprisals.
   Also Friday, suspected communist rebels killed a police
informant in an ambush in Manila, and three men shot and killed a
major in the southern province of Zamboanga del Sur, police and
military officials said.
   Informant Petronilo Lim died in a Manila hospital a few hours
after suspected communist urban guerrillas gunned him down in the
capital's Tondo district, police said.
   In Zamboanga del Sur province on Mindanao island 500 miles
southeast of Manila, three unidentified men shot Maj. Carlos Pumano
after they called him out of his home after midnight Thursday,
military officials said. Pumano was operations chief of the
Philippine Constabulary command in the province.
</TEXT>
