<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     02-19 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flocks of pesky pigeons seem impossible to
scare away and killing them is messy, but some Oklahoma legislators
think they've hit on a way to limit the feathered population ...
birth control.
   State Sen. Leo Kingston introduced an amendment that would allow
game officials to use birth control-treated feed instead of poison
for pigeon control.
   His proposal was approved as an amendment to a House bill passed
by the Senate on Thursday that removes pigeons from the status of
game birds. Such status has meant they can't be shot except during
hunting season. The measure would allow pigeons to be eradicated or
removed from areas where they have become a nuisance.
   State Sen. Gilmer Capps raised one question about the birth
control idea that wasn't fully answered: what will happen to the
population of stray cats that catch and eat pigeons that are ``on
the pill?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Annette Himmelein only met Perri
Doughty of Australia one week ago, but on Saturday Doughty will
serve as bridesmaid at Himmelein's wedding.
   Six years ago, the young women became pen pals through a project
at Himmelein's high school and they later vowed to stand up for
each other when they married.
   Doughty arrived last Saturday to fulfill her part of the bargain
and one of the first things that struck her was the difference in
climate between her 21-year-old pen pal's home and her own native
city of Goondiwindi in the state of Queensland.
   ``I've never seen snow before,'' said Doughty. ``I left a nice
hot summer to come here.''
   Australia isn't the only foreign nation to be represented at the
wedding of Himmelein and Mark Shepherd.
   Also attending are Nanna Rintala, 20, of Kauhava, Finland, and
Patrick Coenen, 22, of Lamaken, Belgium. Both are former exchange
students who lived with the Himmelein family.
   ``My parents' house is sort of like the U.N. right now,'' said
Himmelein, an assistant nurse. ``I sent all of them invitations. It
was just the natural thing to do, because I consider all the
exchange students we've had here my brothers and sisters.''
   Doughty said she was flabbergasted by the scale of the wedding.
   ``I nearly fell over when she told me she was going to have 700
people there,'' Doughty said.
</TEXT>
