<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     02-19 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Tamil Militant Groups Applying to Become Political Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of two former Tamil rebel
groups that surrendered their weapons to peacekeeping troops said
Friday they have applied to have the groups recognized as political
parties.
   Spokesmen for the Tamil Eelam Liberation Organization and the
People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam said they supported
the peace accord signed in July to end the four-year war by
minority Tamils seeking an independent homeland.
   The Election Commission announced Wednesday that nominations for
nine provincial councils would be accepted March 2-9. The council
elections are a part of the peace accord.
   The commission has already granted political recognition to the
former militant group Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front.
   ``We have applied to the Election Commission for recognition as
a political party,'' said Subramanian Haridarraj, a politburo
member of the Tamil Eelam Liberation Organization. He said his
group fully backed the peace accord and wanted to turn its military
organization into a political movement.
   When asked what the once gun-wielding members are doing now,
Haridarraj said, ``We have got fairly large-scale poultry projects
going on in Mannar and Vavuniya in the north and east. Our members
are keen to develop this kind of self-employment.
   ``And right now chicken prices are good in Colombo,'' he added.
   A leader of the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam
said, ``We are not signatories to the peace accord, but we back it.
We are gearing ourselves to participate in the political process.''
   The leader identified himself by his military code name, Haran.
   The peace accord has been rejected by the largest and most
powerful Tamil militant group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   More than 45,000 Indian troops are in Sri Lanka to disarm the
Tigers and enforce the pact, which was mediated by India.
   India is Sri Lanka's northern neighbor and has a large Tamil
population of its own. In Sri Lanka, Tamils comprise 18 percent of
the 16 million population and claim they are discriminated against
by the majority Buddhist Sinhalese.
   The leaders of the less militant Tamil groups both demanded that
986 rebel suspects being held in Sri Lankan jails be released as
stipulated by the accord.
   ``We cannot afford to lose sight of our cadres yet behind bars.
This is the only sore point,'' Haridarraj said.
   The Sri Lankan government released hundreds of suspects
immediately after the accord was signed July 29 but later stopped
the process when the Tigers refused to surrender arms.
   Sri Lanka's largest opposition party, the Sri Lanka Freedom
Party, announced it would boycott provincial council elections,
saying general elections should be held before any local polls.
   The moderate Tamil political party Tamil United Liberation Front
also has said the elections be postponed because of the turbulence
in the north and east, the Tigers' stronghold.
</TEXT>
