<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     02-19 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Cabinet Lineup Unveiled; Hard-Liners Hold Security Posts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Roh Tae-woo announced
his new cabinet lineup Friday by retaining seven ministers from the
old cabinet and placing three hard-liners in top security posts.
   Roh, who takes office Feb. 25, has pledged to usher in full
democracy but political observers said the makeup of the cabinet
indicates Roh is favoring stability.
   Roh urged new ministers to maintain administrative continuity in
the face of legislative elections, economic problems and the
Olympic Games in Seoul.
   The former general demanded the next government establish a
fresh moral standard to gain public trust but opposition parties
said his cabinet lacked freshness in its character and background.
   The new lineup of 20 ministers plus a prime minister and deputy
prime minister contained many technocrats and academics. Five
figures with military backgrounds were appointed as ministers of
defense, labor, communications, transportation and government
administration.
   Opposition parties rejected an invitation to field candidates
for the cabinet, charging that Roh would continue the authoritarian
rule of outgoing President Chun Doo-hwan no matter what they did.
   The move obviously limited the opposition's effect on the
cabinet's formation. But it also removed the opposition from any
responsibility in the policies of the new government.
   Roh, who helped Chun seize power in 1980 with military backing,
won presidential elections last December after promising to end the
country's long tradition of military domination.
   He was opposed by two opposition candidates, Kim Young-sam and
Kim Dae-jung, who split the opposition ticket thereby allowing Roh
to win.
   Roh gave the top security posts to three hard-liners: new
Defense Minister Oh Ja-bock, Home Minister Lee Sang-hee and Justice
Minister Chung Hae-chang.
   Oh retired as chariman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in December
and retains considerable influence in the military. He is expected
to be Roh's link to the armed forces.
   Ahn Moo-hyuk was retained as head of the powerful intellignece
organization, the Agency for National Security Planning, whose
director works with the cabinet but is not a member.
   Roh stressed his desire to ensure sustained economic expansion
by filling economic posts with noted experts.
   His economic considerations were underlined Feb. 11 when he
named Lee Hyun-jae, a political moderate and noted economics
professor, as prime minister.
   Roh has said he would reduce presidential power and increase the
influence of the prime miniser and his cabinet. Ministers held
little power in the past, with most decisions being made by the
presidency.
   The top economic post went to a leading technocrat, Rha
Woong-bae, who was promoted from trade minister in the old cabinet
to deputy prime minister and economic planning minister.
   ``Right now, we are on the threshold of entering from a
developing country to an advanced country,'' Roh told the new
cabinet in calling for a renewed export drive.
   Economic ministers pledged to give top priority to ensuring
price stability. Roh has promised development projects but the new
government is expected to adopt a tight money policy with limited
spending.
   There has been growing concern that high inflation could damage
the economy. Another thorny economic issue is growing trade
friction with countries that have trade deficits with South Korea.
Seoul is under strong pressure from the United States to open its
markets wider to U.S. goods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
