<DOCNO> AP880219-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0610 02-19 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0610,580</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 8 grafs new with Statew Dept. denial, deletes last graf
as redundant; Picks up 4th graf pvs, Delvalle is</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department denied today reports that
the U.S. government has approached Panama about the possibility of
dropping charges against Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega if he and his military associates withdrew from politics.
   According to reports in Newsday and The New York Times,
Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams had discussed the
possibility of a deal during a meeting this week in Miami with
Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   But State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Abrams ``made
no deal, offered no deal and was not in a position to offer a deal''
   He said that in response to a Panamanian inquiry, Abrams told
Delvalle that it was legally possible for the United States to drop
the indictments against Noriega. Two Florida grand juries handed
down a series of drug-related indictment against Noriega earlier
this month.
   ``We have every intention of carrying through on the
indictments,'' Redman said.
   But Justice Department spokesman John K. Russell earlier today
did not dispute an account in today's New York Times that quoted
him as saying Abrams had notified senior department officials that
he would seek to have the indictments dropped if Noriega left the
country.
   ``We told him we would be against the idea,'' Russell told The
Times.
   Redman said Russell's account was ``slightly wrong.'' Redman
added that he stood by his own version of what happened.
   At the White House, President Reagan refused to discuss the
subject.
   ``This is a case before the courts and I am not going to
comment,'' the president said in response to a reporter's question
during a picture-taking ceremony in the Oval Office with West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Delvalle is Panama's titular leader, but political authority
rests largely with Noriega, the general who heads Panama's Defense
Forces.
   Noriega was indicted Feb. 5 by federal grand juries in Miami and
Tampa, Fla., on racketeering and other narcotics-related charges.
His extradition appears highly unlikely because a 1904 treaty
between the two countries does not oblige either state to extradite
its own nationals.
   The Times reported that Abrams had told Delvalle the charges
might be dropped if Noriega and his top associates withdrew from
politics and go into exile. Newsday published a similar report in
Thursday's editions.
   The Times said the Justice Department told Abrams it would
oppose any move to drop the indictments, and that any decision to
drop the indictments would have to be made by President Reagan.
   Newsday, quoting unidentified sources close to Delvalle, said
that Delvalle agreed to discuss the offer with Noriega in Panama.
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified State Department official
as saying that Abrams and Delvalle ``discussed the situation and
(Abrams) urged Delvalle to take a larger role as a civilian in a
move to get the military to step back.''
   ``The question of Noriega's indictment did come up in the
discussion,'' the newspaper quoted the official as saying. ``It is
not correct to say that deals are being made.''
   Newsday quoted a source as saying Abrams had asked Delvalle to
fly to Washington after the meeting and telephone Noriega with the
offer. Delvalle declined and returned to Panama.
   The Times said the proposal for a deal was initiated by
Delvalle, not by Abrams. Officials said Abrams had told Delvalle
that the State and Defense Departments probably would be receptive
to a dismissal of the indictments if Noriega left Panama, but that
the Justice Department would oppose it.
</TEXT>
