<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CookieRebellion     02-19 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cookie Rebellion,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislators Rebel; Services Committee Reverses `No Food' Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legislative committee beat a retreat Friday
after Republicans and Democrats alike threatened rebellion over a
policy to ban food from committee rooms and the House chamber.
   The four-member House Services Committee reversed itself on a
3-1 vote, allowing legislators to have their cake and eat it, too,
while working.
   The vote came early Friday morning after majority Republicans in
the House stalled work Thursday on dozens of major bills awaiting
action. Instead, the legislators went into caucus to argue over the
no-food policy.
   The lone holdout on the committee was Rep. Tom Ratterree, a
retired Air Force colonel who has strong feelings about the subject.
   ``When I came up here several years ago, before I was elected, I
was amazed at what I saw, people eating in committee meetings and
leaving a mess,'' he told a reporter Thursday.
   At that time Ratterree vowed not to change his position.
   ``I think it's a mess,'' he said. ``I don't know of any
businesses that allow that to happen.''
   No vote was taken in the caucus, but several members circulated
letters and gathered names in support of a reversal.
   Several hours after the caucus at least two lawmakers defiantly
munched cookies in a House committee room.
   Earlier this week, House Speaker Carl ``Bev'' Bledsoe proposed
the no-food policy when outside groups began offering legislators
breakfast in the Capitol before each morning's session. He said
crumbs and debris from the on-the-job meals had gotten out of hand.
   The policy forced minority Democrats to abandon their luncheon
caucus and move it into the office of Gov. Roy Romer.
</TEXT>
