<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Kidnap     02-19 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Kidnap,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Spokesman Says U.S. Marine Did Not Violate Travel Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. spokesman said Friday that a
kidnapped U.S. Marine serving with a peacekeeping force in Lebanon
was not violating travel restrictions when he was abducted,
contradicting an earlier U.N. report.
   U.N. spokesman Mario Zamorano said Lt. Col. William R. Higgins,
who disappeared Wednesday, was operating within U.N. guidelines
when he drove from Tyre to the headquarters of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon in the border town of Naqoura.
   Thursday UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel said that American
members of U.N. forces are restricted to the headquarters area and
are permitted to travel in Lebanon only with a U.N. military escort.
   Zamorano called Goksel's report ``totally inaccurate.''
   ``As all his predecessors, he travelled freely in the area
without escort,'' Zamorano said.
   Higgins, chief of the observer group, was the 10th American to
head the U.N. Truce Supervision Organization in Lebanon in the 40
years since it was formed. The 76-man group, with eight other
Americans besides Higgins, is attached to UNIFIL in south Lebanon.
   For 40 years, he said, U.N. observers in the Middle East have
had a ``categorical rule: They do not carry weapons or move with
armed escorts. That is something they want themselves.
   ``They believe their protection comes from being unarmed,'' he
said.
   In times of danger, it has been suggested that the observers
should have armed escorts,'' he said, but added, ``They always have
rejected this.''
   Zamorano said that U.N. Undersecretary-General Marrack Goulding
met Higgins' fellow officers Friday and was told ``even after the
abduction that they do not, repeat do not, want to be armed or have
armed escorts.''
   The U.N. spokesman said that on Thursday Higgins' U.N. observer
force was pulled out of the U.N. peacekeeping area in south Lebanon
and withdrawn to the headquarters near Naqoura.
   The U.N. spokesman in New York had no comment on claims of
kidnap responsibility by two groups. He said the matter was under
investigation.
   The spokesman said Higgins had gone to Tyre for a meeting with
Amal militia leaders as part of his official duties.
</TEXT>
