<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScottRetrial     02-19 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scott Retrial,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Corporal Awaits Verdict in Second Court-Martial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second court-martial of Marine Cpl.
Lindsey Scott on controversial charges of raping and trying to kill
a fellow Marine's wife went to a military jury Thursday as his
father predicted acquittal.
   ``I am very confident that we will win it,'' James Scott said
after deliberations began. ``I just think there's justice in the
world.''
   Scott, 32, of Louisville, Ky., was convicted of abduction, rape,
sodomy and attempted murder in an April 20, 1983, attack at the
Quantico Marine Base.
   That verdict was overturned in 1987 by the U.S. Military Court
of Appeals on grounds Scott had not received adequate counsel from
his first civilian attorney.
   Meanwhile, civil rights activists established a legal defense
fund for Scott, and CBS' ``60 Minutes'' broadcast a story on the
case. Jesse Jackson directed aides to lobby the Congressional Black
Caucus to pressure the Pentagon for a new trial for the black
serviceman.
   Scott had become a suspect almost immediately after the woman,
the 23-year-old wife of a military policeman who worked with him,
was found dazed and bleeding.
   She told investigators she had been lured from her apartment by
a telephone call from a man who said her husband had been in an
accident and who offered to take her to the hospital.
   Instead, the man drove her to a remote spot, raped her, choked
her, stabbed her in the neck and left her for dead, she said.
   The white woman picked Scott from a group of photographs and
then from a lineup, but each time she equivocated, saying other men
in the groups resembled him. Once she picked out Scott because she
said he ``scares me the most.''
   Investigators said she also identified his car.
   The 17-day retrial ended with civilian defense attorney John
Leino arguing there was a lack of evidence against his client.
   Leino repeated his charge that the Naval Investigative Service
used improper lineup techniques and led the victim to her
identification of Scott.
   The victim picked Scott because ``in her mind, someone has to
pay,'' he said.
   Lieno said the only bit of forensic evidence presented in the
case _ a hair taken from the victim's clothing _ did not belong to
Scott.
   ``We think that the motive in this case was sex ... and we
believe that the intent was murder,'' military prosecutor Maj. Ron
McNeil told the jury of seven Marines.
   ``Was there a conspiracy here to make this up? Absolutely not.
There's no conspiracy here.'' McNeil said.
   A crucial part of Scott's defense was the testimony of a
department store security guard who said she saw Scott in a store
at the time of the attack.
   The prosecution said the testimony of Cynthia Ausby was
``incredible.'' McNeil said Ms. Ausby did not firmly recall seeing
Scott until almost 10 months after the crime. She did not testify
in the first court-martial.
   The defense argued that Ms. Ausby's recollection was aided by
her checking of store arrest records.
</TEXT>
