<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleFamilies     02-19 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Families,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department To Steer Clear of Further Shuttle Settlement
Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Friday it is
declining to participate in any further settlements with families
of the seven astronauts killed in the Challenger shuttle crash.
   The department negotiated settlements with four of the seven
families in December 1986.
   The Justice Department's position is that it would be unfair to
contribute to any settlement higher than the amounts negotiated in
1986 and that the government has no legal liability in the
accident, said department spokeswoman Amelia Brown.
   Last week, the father and brother of mission specialist Judith
A. Resnik signed an agreement with shuttle contractor Morton
Thiokol Inc. for payment of from $1.5 million to $2.5 million. The
Justice Department declined to participate in the negotiations
leading to that settlement.
   Resnik's relatives weren't involved in the 1986 settlement.
   In addition to Resnik, the federal government didn't make
payments to the family of Ronald E. McNair, who also settled
separately with Thiokol.
   The widow of Challenger pilot Michael Smith has sued the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration and Thiokol.
   Brown said the Resnik family had rejected a ``generous'' offer
prior to the 1986 settlement, which was made on behalf of NASA and
Morton Thiokol.
   Brown said the offer took into account the different financial
needs in the families based on the number of dependents and also
took into account the requests from the families that they be
treated as similarly as possible in the settlement. Resnik was the
only Challenger crew member who was not survived by a spouse and
children.
   The Justice Department has never released the terms of the
settlements, citing the survivors' privacy, but Justice Department
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, have said the amount
was at least $1 million for each of the four families.
</TEXT>
