<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Bullets     02-19 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Bullets,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Political Leader Says Israel Using Dumdum Bullets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Israeli soldiers who confront Arab rioters
are firing soft-nosed dumdum bullets, which have an exploding
effect on impact and make large, tearing wounds, British opposition
leader Neil Kinnock said Friday.
   Kinnock, leader of Britain's Labor Party, said he saw an X-ray
taken of the wound that forced doctors to amputate the lower part
of a Palestinian's leg.
   He said it ``showed shattering of the bone and flesh consistent
with the use of an explosive bullet.'' At another point in the news
conference, he said the injury also was consistent with ``the wound
inflicted by a dumdum bullet.''
   Smaller caliber ammunition is being modified to make it more
dangerous, he said, and displayed two .22-caliber bullets that had
been filed to give them rough edges.
   ``The filed-down bullet with its extra effects of internal
wounding is deliberately done ... and that conforms to many of the
definitions of dumdum,'' Kinnock said the third day of his visit
here.
   Since November, Israeli snipers have used .22-caliber rifles
under supervision of their superiors to hit leaders of Palestinian
protests.
   Dumdum bullets are outlawed by the Geneva Conventions for use in
warfare.
   Israeli officials have denied the army uses them, but
Palestinian doctors have said for several weeks that only dumdums
could have caused some of the wounds they treat.
   Kinnock, who has met with Israel's top leaders during his visit,
said none denied such bullets were being used.
   ``On the occasions on which I've put the point, I've received
rationalizations and descriptions of the terrible pressures under
which the Israeli Defense Forces are operating, but no one has
attempted to deny that the bullets are used,'' he said.
   Kinnock added, however, that he believed such ammunition was
``being used without any form of permission or direction or
acceptance or endorsement by the Israeli army and the Israeli
authorities. Of that I have no doubt.''
   Kinnock also said there was ``clear evidence, irrefutable
evidence'' that Israeli soldiers had shot Arab protesters in the
back since Arab riots began Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   On visits to two hospitals in the occupied territories, Kinnock
said, he saw seven Palestinians hospitalized with bullet wounds in
the back.
   He said he expressed his concern about the use of modified
bullets and the back wounds to Israeli officials and ``it is
possible that these tactics may be adjusted, are indeed possibly in
the process of being adjusted now.''
   Kinnock arrived in Israel after visits to Jordan and Egypt, and
has toured both the West Bank and Gaza.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
