<FILEID>AP-PX-02-19-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HistoricalListing     02-19 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Historical Listing,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rundown Housing Project Is Added To National Register of Historic
Places</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rundown housing project that some critics say
should be razed has been placed on the National Register of
Historic Place, a move hailed by residents and other opponents of
demolition.
   ``Thank the Lord,'' Shirley Johnson, treasurer of the Allen
Parkway Village Residents Council, said after getting word of the
decision Wednesday.
   ``I just hope this helps to end all that demolishing business.
This is my home, and although a lot of the project is boarded-up
now, it could some day be home to a lot of the homeless who have no
shelter,'' she said.
   However, a Texas Historical Commission official said the
designation doesn't mean the project won't be demolished.
   The National Register's Austin office was notified Wednesday by
the National Parks Service, which makes the final determination,
that the project had been put on the register, said Marlene
Casarez, the office's administrator.
   The project was nominated for the designation by Stephen Fox of
the Anchorage Foundation of Texas, which backs architectural
preservation and architectural history projects.
   The project is architecturally significant because ``it is a
very fine example of modern architecture design in the field of
public housing,'' Fox said. The project was built in 1942 and 1944
as housing for war-industry workers and their families.
   Allen Parkway also met the state and national registers'
standards of being a significant example of community planning and
for social and humanitarian purposes, he said.
   About 130 mainly black and Vietnamese families live in the
1,000-unit project today.
   As other residents moved out, the city's Housing Authority
sealed the empty units in anticipation of federal approval of a
plan to raze the project and sell the prime 37.5-acre tract west of
downtown for development. This could still be done, officials said.
   ``Everyone has to understand that listing in the National
Register is no protection per se,'' said Jim Steely, director of
National Register Programs for the Texas Historical Commission.
   ``But it does ensure that documentation will exist for posterity
showing that Allen Parkway was here and that it was important in
the history of Houston, of Texas and of the nation.''
   Steely said Texas preservationists will work with the Advisory
Council on Historic Preservation, an independent agency set up by
the federal government, to monitor the spending of any federal
funds on Allen Parkway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
