<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WifeSlain     02-19 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wife Slain,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husband Held in Killing of Wife Who Once Requested Leniency for
Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been charged with shooting his wife to
death two months after she asked prosecutors to treat him leniently
on charges that he had wounded her, officials said.
   Linda Joyce Hubert, 26, was found dead in her apartment Thursday
shortly after neighbors heard several shots and saw a man get into
a car and speed away.
   Kenneth Leon Hubert, 27, surrendered to police a few hours later
and was charged with murder. He was ordered held without bond.
   Homicide Sgt. Jerry Novak said Hubert surrendered after hearing
he was being sought and that Hubert insisted he is innocent.
   Hubert had been free on $5,000 bond on an attempted murder
charge in the Dec. 18 wounding of his wife, and on $2,000 bond on a
charge of kidnapping his girlfriend in November.
   Ms. Hubert asked prosecutors for leniency and said she would not
testify against her husband about the Dec. 18 shooting.
   ``She wanted us to offer the guy probation,'' assistant Harris
County District Attorney Mike Anderson said. ``We contacted her and
she said: `Oh, no, he just needs help. I don't want to prosecute
unless he'll get help instead of prison time.'''
   ``She seemed very forgiving,'' he added.
   The Huberts had been separated for about three years. A neighbor
said Hubert often drove by the apartment where Ms. Hubert lived
with her two sons, ages 2 and 9.
   ``I thought the husband was a boyfriend trying to make up with
her, because he was always coming around harassing her,'' Ola
Aubrey said. ``He would come every day and stay in that car and
blow his horn. She would just stay inside. She would never let him
in her apartment.''
   Anderson said he had two other cases this week in which women
injured by their husbands refused to testify against them.
   Rhonda Gerson, director of Aid to Victims of Domestic Violence,
a non-profit agency in Houston that offers legal information and
services, said various things influence a woman's decision not to
testify against her husband.
   ``She may feel that she's the one sending him to jail, rather
than his own behavior,'' Ms. Gerson said. ``Or she doesn't want the
father of her children in prison.
   ``Sometimes, there is a lot of fear and intimidation'' from the
husband not to testify, she added. Or, a woman may be hoping to
reconcile with the husband and doesn't want to make matters worse
by testifying against him.
   ``Or she may be afraid of what's going to happen when he comes
out (of prison),'' said Ms. Gerson, who was not involved in Ms.
Hubert's case.
</TEXT>
