<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-DeficitAppointments     02-19 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Deficit Appointments,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger, Lewis Named to Deficit-Reduction Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan named former Cabinet
secretaries Caspar Weinberger and Drew Lewis on Friday to a
commission charged with seeking ways to reduce the federal budget
deficit.
   Completing the makeup of the bipartisan panel, Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole and House Republican Leader Robert Michel also
appointed members. Democrats announced their members late last year.
   Dole chose Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., ranking Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee, and Dean Kleckner, president of the
American Farm Bureau Federation.
   Michel selected Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn., a member of the
House Ways and Means Committee, and Donald Rumsfeld, a former
defense secretary and congressmen who also served as director of
the Office of Economic Oportunity and as White House chief of staff
under President Ford.
   The panel, known as the National Economic Commission, is
supposed to issue a report on March 1, 1989, after Reagan has left
office.
   Lewis, now the head of Union Pacific Corp., was Reagan's first
secretary of transportation. Weinberger was Reagan's secretary of
defense for seven years.
   In a statement announcing the appointments, the president said,
``I believe when all aspects of the budget are reviewed the primary
policy problem will be viewed not as a lack of revenues, but an
inexorable growth in spending.
   ``Over the last seven years, revenues have increased by $250
billion but spending has increased by $325 billion,'' he said.
   ``And while defense has necessarily grown, it accounted for only
$125 billion, or less than 40 percent of the increase.''
</TEXT>
