<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Economy Bjt   02-19 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Economy, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Defends Tax, Budget Policies in Report to Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan defended his tax and budget
policies Friday in an election-year economic report to Congress,
saying his administration had turned economic despair into hope.
   Reagan's seventh annual economic report brushed off accusations
by Democratic presidential candidates that a $2.4 trillion national
debt and record trade imbalances during the Reagan years had
hobbled the country and eventually would reduce Americans' standard
of living.
   Beryl Sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said the
new economic report was aimed at debunking ``myths'' that the
country had become a second-rate economic power.
   He said that in reality the United States had out-performed the
rest of the world, producing 2{ times the number of jobs as the
other top six industrialized countries combined since the end of
the 1981-82 recession.
   The president, in an eight-page introduction to this year's
report, said the country is in a lot better shape than when he took
office seven years ago.
   ``It is hard to believe that at the beginning of the 1980s, the
prevailing attitude toward the economy could best be described as
despair,'' the president said. ``Inflation and interest rates had
ratcheted higher with each successive business cycle and ... the
goal of sustainable growth appeared increasingly elusive.''
   In a theme sure to be sounded by the eventual Republican
presidential nominee, the report asserted, ``The past five years of
sustained and vigorous growth in production, income and employment
did not occur by accident. They were shaped by government policies
explicitly directed toward fostering the inherent dynamism of the
private sector.''
   The report sought to downplay any problems associated with the
doubling of the national debt under Reagan and the string of
foreign trade deficits that has transformed the United States from
the largest creditor country to the largest debtor nation.
   The country's debt to the rest of the world stands at around
$400 billion, the amount of foreign holdings in the United States
that exceed American investments in other countries.
   Sprinkel, in a briefing for reporters, said that the net
payments to foreigners needed to service the country's foreign debt
represented just 0.1 percent of the $4.6 trillion U.S. economy.
   ``Disaster does not loom in our future. This current level of
(international) indebtedness is not worrisome,'' he said. ``The
argument that we can't grow and make economic progress because we
are debt-ridden is wrong.''
   Sprinkel said that the recent string of three consecutive
declines in the Index of Leading Indicators was signaling slower
growth in the first half of 1988 but not a recession this year.
   He also discounted recent big declines in housing construction
in December and January, a key economic sector that is often the
first to turn down at the start of a new recession.
   Sprinkel blamed the housing declines on a too-restrictive
monetary policy being pursued by the Federal Reserve in the months
before the record collapse of stock prices that occured last Oct.
19.
   Sprinkel said by late spring construction should start rising
again in response to recent declines in mortgage rates, which have
now dipped back to single-digit levels, falling to 9.84 percent
last week.
   A draft version of the president's economic report was critical
of the Federal Reserve for tightening credit conditions in
December, after initially pumping money into the economy
immediately following the stock market crash.
   However, the final version of the report said that more recent
actions of the Fed this year indicate the central bank is again
promoting lower interest rates as a way of stimulating economic
growth.
   Sprinkel said he was now satisfied with the Fed's performance,
calling their action in the past six weeks ``quite appropriate.''
   The economic report claimed that significant progress has been
made in reducing both the budget and trade deficits and predicted
further gains on both fronts.
   Sprinkel predicted that an improving trade deficit would provide
about half of the country's overall economic growth this year,
which the administration is forecasting will slow to a 2.4 percent,
as measured by the gross national product. That is down from 3.8
percent in 1987.
   The president repeated his warnings that Congress should not try
to reduce the trade deficit by passing either of the omnibus trade
bills now being considered by a House-Senate conference committee.
   Reagan said unless the measures were substantially modified he
would veto the legislation because of objectionable protectionist
provisions.
   The president also repeated his pledge, made in his State of the
Union address, to veto another 11th-hour, catchall spending bill
such as the one passed by Congress last December.
   In a chapter on airline deregulation, the report maintained that
consumers are reaping a $15 billion annual windfall in lower fares.
It said that while a 28 percent increase in the number of flights
had raised concerns about safety, accidents had declined steadily
since 1978.
</TEXT>
