<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OhioLawyers     02-19 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ohio Lawyers,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Back to the Books for Ohio Lawyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN W. CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ohio Supreme Court unveiled a
continuing legal education program Thursday that would require some
35,000 attorneys in the state to head back to school to keep their
licenses.
   Chief Justice Thomas Moyer said the new rule, adopted
unanimously by the high court, requires every attorney to complete
24 hours of legal education every two years beginning in 1990.
   Lawyers who fail to comply could be faced with fines of up to
$500 and even suspension from practice.
   Ohio is the 30th state to adopt such a program, which Moyer said
would maintain and improve the quality of legal services.
   ``Let me say that this is not a panacea,'' Moyer said at a news
conference. ``... But what it means is that we are making a minimum
effort to assure people who use the services of lawyers that the
lawyer they employ has been required to stay current.''
   The rule was developed in cooperation with several state
attorney groups. Representatives of four of them who joined Moyer
at the briefing welcomed the court's action.
   Joseph Cook of Akron, president of the Ohio State Bar
Association, said the requirement would not be a burden to most
attorneys: ``Most laywers have already been getting more
(continuing education) than the rule requires.''
   He said attorneys probably could meet their yearly requirements
by attending seminars sponsored by the state bar at its annual
meeting.
   The rule establishes, effective July 1, a Supreme Court
Commission on Continuing Legal Education that will administer and
accredit the programs.
   The program will be financed by a $15 filing fee.
</TEXT>
