<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathRowTestimony     02-19 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Row Testimony,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Present, Former Death Row Inmates Testify on Behalf of Fellow
Prisoner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convicted killers testified Friday as
character witnesses for a fellow convict trying to avoid the death
penalty, telling the jury that the man lent them money and aided
them with other acts of kindness.
   James Ernest Hitchcock, 31, was convicted and sentenced to death
for the 1976 rape-murder of his 13-year-old stepniece, Cynthia
Driggers. The U.S. Supreme Court ordered a new sentencing hearing
last April.
   Inmates Darrell Edwin Hoy and Arthur Rutherford, wearing solid
blue prison uniforms, were brought into the courtroom in chains and
handcuffs that were removed before the jury was seated.
   The short, stocky Rutherford, 38, awaiting death in the electric
chair for a 1986 murder in Santa Rosa County, said Hitchcock helped
him upon Rutherford's arrival on death row by lending him money to
buy tobacco and other items.
   Hoy, soft-voiced and polite, said he and Hitchcock had
side-by-side cells on death row for three years in the early 1980s
and that Hitchcock had given him his radio after Hoy's was stolen,
that he had lent him money and had helped him study to get a
general education degree.
   On the death penalty, Hoy said, ``I feel that's wrong for
certain reasons, if I may say so.''
   Hoy was convicted in Pinellas County of raping a teen-ager in
front of her fiance and then shooting and killing them both. His
sentence was overturned, and he was removed from death row in 1984.
   Asked by Prosecutor Belvin Perry for his views on the death
penalty, Rutherford sat up straight, crossed his arms, raised his
voice and replied, ``I'm in Florida State Prison on hearsay _ no
evidence, no nothin' ... I'm against it.''
   Extraordinary security measures were in place at the Orange
County Courthouse, where a shootout several years ago left one
bailiff dead and three people wounded, including the gunman.
   Among the 50 courtroom spectators were 10 armed deputies in
civilian clothes. Another dozen uniformed and armed guards
accompanied the prisoners or were posted at the front and sides of
the courtroom.
   Defense lawyers had argued for the appearance of the present and
former death row prisoners because Hitchcock had spent a third of
his life on death row.
   Circuit Judge Gary Formet told attorneys he would not permit
them to disclose the nature of the prisoners' crimes.
   Hitchcock spent more than a decade in a cell just a few feet
from Florida's electric chair before his sentence was overturned.
   The 12 jurors are getting a shortened version of trial testimony
and then hearing more than 20 witnesses testify for and against
Hitchcock in his effort to escape the chair. The jury's
recommendation _ life or death _ is only advisory to the judge.
   One of Hitchcock's two public defenders, Robert Wesley, told the
jury in his opening remarks that the defendant's brother, Richard _
the victim's stepfather _ beat and strangled the girl after he
found Hitchcock and the girl having sex.
   Wesley said his client ``is not saying he is innocent. ... He
participated in the crime. But he asks to live his life in prison.''
   Richard Hitchcock took the witness stand earlier and denied that
he killed his stepdaughter.
   The jury also heard a tape-recorded confession by James
Hitchcock in which he admitted raping and killing the girl. He
later recanted the confession, claiming it was given under duress
because he was held for four days in solitary confinement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
