<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1537EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Missiles     02-19 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Missiles,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commentator Says U.S. Backtracking on `Star Wars'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Arms, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet news commentator on Friday accused U.S.
arms negotiators in Geneva of trying to make a ``massive
departure'' from an understanding on space defenses reached during
the superpower summit.
   Vladimir Bogachev blamed the United States for what he called a
worsening atmosphere at the Geneva talks. The commentary was
distributed by the official Tass news agency two days before the
arrival of Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Among other issues, Shultz is to discuss with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top officials efforts to cut the
superpowers' long-range missiles by 50 percent.
   The Soviet Union argues that an understanding on President
Reagan's ``Star Wars'' program for a space-based missile defense
must be a part of the agreement.
   They say Reagan and Gorbachev reached a basis for agreement on
strategic weapons and space defenses during their December summit
meeting in Washington.
   ``In recent weeks the situation at the talks has noticeably
worsened,'' Bogachev said. ``The U.S. side is trying to effect a
massive departure from the accords which are explicitly spelled out
in the joint statement at the summit level.''
   The Soviet Union claims the ``Star Wars'' program is a violation
of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   The U.S. delegation in Geneva is acting as though Reagan and
Gorbachev did not make any connection between strategic weapons and
space defenses in their talks in December, Bogachev said.
   ``The militarization of outer space according to the `Star Wars'
plans will lead to a sharp destabilization of the
military-political situation in the world,'' he said.
``Militarization of outer space and a cut in strategic offensive
weapons on Earth are incompatible.''
   He said the United States also was seeking to arm long-range
sea-based missiles with conventional warheads, even though the
non-nuclear warheads can be replaced quickly with nuclear charges.
</TEXT>
