<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MissingMillions     02-19 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Millions,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Rules Out Foreign Investigators From Case of Missing
Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police said Friday they
won't allow foreign investigators to join the search for $8 million
stolen from a commercial flight that originated in New York.
   Geovani Azevedo, federal police spokesman in Rio de Janeiro,
told The Associated Press, ``If we discover foreign investigators
working on this case, we will expell them. This includes FBI
agents.''
   On Thursday it was revealed that two canvas sacks containing $4
million each in U.S. currency were separated from a shipment of 13
such bags. The bags were being flown from New York to Buenos Aires,
Aregentina and contained a total of $52 million.
   Central Bank officials said the money was being sent by the
United States to help Argentina pay foreign bonds but that it was
insured and the loss wouldn't hurt Argentina.
   The bags were loaded as personal baggage on a Varig flight out
of Kennedy International Airport on Feb. 5 and arrived at Rio's
international airport, where they were to be transferred to another
Varig flight to Buenos Aires.
   Varig is Brazil's national carrier, but Brink's, the U.S.-based
security company, was imn charge of the shipment.
   Varig said a passenger known only as Mr. Denisco paid standard
overweight charges for the bags and that Brink's was in charge of
transfering them from one plane to another in the airplane parking
area at Rio's international airport.
   ``The baggage never entered the terminal. Brink's was entirely
responsible for the operation,'' a Varig communique said.
   Brazil's federal police chief, Romeu Tuma, said Thursday night,
``There obviously was a security failure.'' He said he also wanted
to know ``why we only heard about this disappearance two weeks
later.''
   The money came from the U.S. Federal Reserve Bank in New York.
The other $44 million arrived safely in Buenos Aires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
