<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Communists 1stLd-Writethru a0706 02-19 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Communists, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Leadership Unclear as 12th Party Congress Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf `Both Iglesias ...,' with 1 graf to clarify
description of Ibarruri.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish Communists opened their 12th
congress Friday amid uncertainty over who would lead the party out
of its worst crisis since it returned to legal political activity
11 years ago.
   Secretary General Gerardo Iglesias, a 43-year-old miner, has
made it clear he will step down this year as head of the party that
is fighting for its political life.
   Fierce internal squabbling and poor electoral showings have
caused a sharp decline in voter support and membership, party
spokesman and political analysts say.
   The Communist-oriented United Left coalition holds only seven of
the 350 seats in the Spanish parliament, down from the 20 seats the
Communists held nlone after general elections in 1979.
   The party suffered another defeat with the announcement by Julio
Anguita, leader of Communists in southern Andalucia, that he had
made ``an irrevocable decision'' not to accept Iglesia's job if
nominated.
   Both Iglesias and 92-year-old honorary party president Dolores
Ibarruri, the legendary ``La Pasionaria'' who became a symbol of
Loyalist resistance to Franco forces during the civil war in the
1930s, called on the 619 party delegates to work for greater unity
among Communists to face the current crisis.
   ``This congress should and can put an end to any hint of
confusion, confirming the political unity and internal democracy of
the Spanish Communist Party,'' Iglesias said in his opening speech
Friday.
   He $dded that the party had managed to overcome ``the most
difficult problems, including the real threat of disappearing
altogether.''
   Acco,ding to political scientist Ramon Garcia Cotarelo, the lack
of a clear-cut choice of a leader to replace Iglesias was a sign
that the party's top echelons had no confidence in the party's
future.
   He said it would not be clear who the new party chief would be
until Sunday when party delegates choose the new 90-member Central
Committee, and it elects a new secretary general.
   Data made public Friday showed that from its peak in 1979
through its sharp decline to 1983, the party lost 65 percent of its
membership or 120,000 people. As the crisis deepened after 1985,
membership has further declined from 67,400 to 62,300.
   In its heyday, the party was at the forefront of the
Eurocommunism movement, which advocated independence from the
Soviet Union and democratic elections.
   The current imbroglio stems from Iglesia's replacement of
historic Spanish Communist leader Santiago Carrillo at the 11th
Congress in December 1983, after Carrillo resigned following the
party's electoral debacle in 1982 general elections.
   Carrillo, 73, headed the party from 1960 to 1982 and was a main
proponent of Eurocommunism. He led the Spanish party in its
clandestine years from exile in Paris and after it was legalized in
1977, two years after the death of Gen. Francisco Franco ended the
36-year military dictatorship.
   The party reached its zenith in 1979 when it got 10 percent of
the vote. But in the 1982 general elections the Socialist party
headed by Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez swept into power with a
landslide victory, while the Communists got only 3.8 percent of the
ballots.
   The debacle led to Carrillo's resignation and the ascendance of
Iglesias, his young protege.
   But when Iglesias attempted to move the party away from its base
among the working class to weave together emerging non-Communist
social movements such as pacifists and ecologists, the two leaders
clashed.
   In 1985, the party ousted Carrillo and many of his followers.
   Attempts in the last two years to overcome their differences and
to bring Carillo and his supporters back into the fold have failed,
costing the party prestige and votes, Garcia Cotarelo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
