<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ClusterBoxSavings     02-19 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cluster Box Savings,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Postal Service Saves Money By Using Cluster Boxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delivering mail to cluster boxes instead of to
the door or a curbside mailbox saves the Postal Service more than
$11 million annually, the General Accounting Office reported Friday.
   Cluster boxes are centralized mailbox groupings used in many
apartment and townhouse developments, and some new residential
areas. They allow letter carriers to deliver mail for several homes
at one spot, saving time on their rounds.
   The GAO, which does investigations for Congress, studied the use
of the boxes at the request of Reps. William D. Ford, D-Mich.,
Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and Robert Garcia, D-N.Y.
   The report covered fiscal 1985, when about 1.9 million of the 53
million daily city mail deliveries involved cluster boxes.
   According to the study, in areas of detached homes, delivering
mail to a cluster box instead of to a curbside mailbox saved about
$10 per customer, for a saving of $4.5 million.
   In townhouse sections, the Postal Service saved about $11 per
customer by delivering to clusterboxes instead of to mailboxes
located by the door of the home. That netted a saving of $6.9
million, the report said.
   For low-rise apartment buildings, the cost of delivering to a
cluster box was about the same as bringing mail to a group of boxes
in the lobby.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1557EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Pollard Bjt   02-19 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pollard, Bjt,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spy's Parents Claim Navy Considered Prominent Jews as Suspects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of convicted spy Jonathan J.
Pollard said Friday that Navy investigators showed him a list of
names of 25 American Jews and asked him to identify those who
helped him commit espionage for Israel.
   ``They kept badgering him to indicate which of those on the list
was involved in the spy plot,'' said Morris Pollard, a professor of
microbiology at the University of Notre Dame.
   Both the senior Pollard and his son denied that Jonathan Pollard
had an accomplice in spying for Israel. Their statement came after
The Washington Post reported Friday that government investigators
had concluded that someone in the CIA or Defense Department also
had spied for Israel.
   Justice Department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said there are differing views within the department on the
question of whether there is another spy. While there appear to be
some solid indications that there was another operative, some
officials have doubts about whether that is the case, said the
sources.
   Neither the Navy nor the Justice Department or its Bureau of
Prisons had any immediate comment on the Pollards' charges.
   ``We can neither confirm nor deny this,'' said Lt. Janet Mescus,
a spokesman for the Navy. ``At this point, we have no comment.''
   Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland also declined
comment.
   The Post story, by reporters Bob Woodward and Walter Pincus,
quoted unidentified sources as saying government investigators have
dubbed the alleged second spy ``Mr. X.''
   But Jonathan Pollard, a former civilian intelligence analyst for
the Navy who was sentenced in March to life in prison, said he knew
of no ``Mr. X.'' He admitted selling American defense secrets to
Israel over a period of 15 months until his arrest in November 1985
outside the Israeli embassy in Washington.
   His wife, Anne Henderson-Pollard, was sentenced to five years in
prison for helping him.
   ``I gave no information suggesting the existence of a Mr. X in
government,'' Pollard said in a statement he telephoned from prison
to his mother, who conveyed it to The Associated Press. Under a
plea-bargaining agreement, Pollard is not allowed direct contact
with the news media.
   ``This was confirmed by nine months of polygraphing. Having said
that, I obviously have no knowledge of whether any other person or
persons was helping Israel,'' the statement said.
   Pollards' parents said their son had been held in a psychiatric
ward at the federal prison in Springfield, Mo., for 10 months as
Navy investigators tried to force him to implicate others.
   Pollard's parents said the authorities hoped to ``break'' their
son by surrounding him with mental patients. His attorney, Richard
Hibey, said, however, he believed the idea was to keep him in
protected surroundings to prevent him rom revealing national
security secrets.
   George Diffenbaucher, head of the penitentiary's social services
department, said Pollard was assigned to the Diagnostic and
Observation Unit, a psychological evaluation and treatment unit. He
said Pollard was not ``a mental patient'' but ``there are other
considerations for keeping him there.''
   Hibey said the prosecutors had told him they were satisfied that
Pollard had told them all he knew about the affair during nine
months of polygraph exams and debriefings.
   No evidence has been developed yet that points to the specific
identity of a second person, the Post said, citing unidentified
sources for its information.
   Pollard's mother, Molly Pollard, said that when a list of 25
names was shown to him and he was told they were prominent members
of the American Jewish community, he recognized only one name. She
did not know what that name was.
   In the prison mental ward, Pollard is ``surrounded by demented,
screaming people'' in a cell that measures six by nine feet, his
father charged. ``They hoped to break him,'' he said.
Diffenbaucher, asked if that charge was true, said, ``Of course
not. Break him of what?''
   The prison authorities ``told us they were upset with his being
in a mental ward. They said it was like KGB tactics,'' said the
father. ``But they also said they could not do anything about it
because they had orders from the Navy to keep him there.''
   Morris Pollard wrote to Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., asking him to
intercede on his son's behalf.
   An aide in Hamilton's office, who asked not to be identified,
said the congressman promised he would try to help. ``He felt
Pollard should not be discriminated against compared with other
prisoners,'' the aide said.
   In his statement, Pollard said the Post based its report on
claims by Justice Department officials ``who could not prove the
existence of such a person on the basis of fact. So now, they are
simply inventing him or her out of thin air and hoping to give
their spectral image an air of substance.''
   The Post said the belief that a Mr. X must exist grew out of a
massive debriefing and polygraphing of Pollard over many months.
   Pollard told authorities that his Israeli handlers often
specified by date and control number the highly sensitive U.S.
documents they wanted him to acquire, the newspaper said.
   The handlers once showed Pollard a top-secret U.S. document to
which he did not have access, the Post said. It identified the
document as an index or catalog that Pollard then could use to
obtain other documents from U.S. intelligence agencies.
   Investigators concluded that another American _ ``Mr. X'' _ had
provided that index and other specific information on U.S. secrets
that Pollard learned from his Israeli handlers, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
