<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MadameChiang     02-19 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Madame Chiang,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chiang Kai-Shek's Widow Pays Tribute to Husband, Stepson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madame Chiang Kai-shek made a brief visit
Friday to the mausoleum of President Chiang Ching-kuo, her stepson
who died last month at the age of 77, the official news agency
reported.
   The 86-year-old Madame Chiang, accompanied by unidentified
family members, prayed in silence before Chiang's bronze coffin at
the Tahsi Mausoleum in a small rural town 30 miles southwest of
Taipei, the Central News Agency reported.
   The news agency said Madame Chiang made her first visit to the
mausoleum shortly after she visited the mausoleum of Generalissimo
Chiang Kai-shek, the late president's father who died in 1975.
   The two mausoleums are a little more than a mile apart.
   Madame Chiang did not attend her stepson's funeral on Jan. 30,
three days after newspapers linked her to an unsuccessful
last-ditch effort to delay newly installed President Lee Teng-hui
from being appointed head of the ruling Nationalist Party.
   Chiang Ching-kuo had tapped Lee as his successor.
   Madame Chiang, who is chairman of the ruling party's Central
Advisory Committee, also did not appear at earlier memorial
services for Chiang Ching-kuo.
   She left Taiwan for a mansion on Long Island in New York soon
after her husband's death, reportedly because of difference in
opinion with her stepson. She returned in 1986 to attend ceremonies
marking the late generalissimo's 100th birthday.
</TEXT>
