<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1621EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0662 02-19 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Likely To Visit Syria In Search For Mideast Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs pvs 4th graf, ``The visit,'' with 3 grafs to update with
lifting of Syrian sanction; subs pvs 10th graf, ``Another U.S.,''
to delete outdated matter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz ``most
likely'' will visit Syria when he goes to the Middle East next week
and is leaving his options open for a return to the region after a
NATO summit meeting in early March, U.S. officials said Friday.
   As Shultz set out for Moscow on a trip in which he will seek
Soviet backing for his peace-making venture, his Mideast journey
was taking on dramatic new proportions.
   Shultz's purpose in going to Damascus would be to discuss the
U.S. drive for Arab-Israeli negotiations with President Hafez
Assad, whose support for any long-term settlement in the Middle
East is considered essential by specialists in the State
Department's Near East bureau.
   Reinforcing the impression that U.S.-Syrian relations are
warming was a disclosure Friday by State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley that one of several sanctions the United States has
imposed against Syria has been ended.
   She said security clearance requirements on Syrian applicants
for U.S. visas have been lifted. Under the sanction, all such
applicants had been subjected to lengthy background checks to
qualify for a visa.
   A visit by Shultz to Damascus would be a major prestige boost to
Syria and mark an improvement in its relations with the United
States. The country is one of six listed by the State Department as
a supporter of terrorism, and President Reagan imposed sanctions
against it in November 1986.
   In that action, Reagan banned the sale of sophisticated
technology, such as computers, aircraft and related spare parts;
ended the financing of exports to Syria by the U.S. Export-Import
Bank; canceled the U.S.-Syrian air transport agreement; reduced the
U.S. Embassy staff in Damascus and pressured American oil companies
to halt their operations in Syria.
   The State Department had linked Syria to some 40 incidents of
terrorism. Reagan said the sanctions were intended to express
``outrage'' at what he called Syria's involvement in international
terrorism _ charges the Syrians denied.
   Among the punitive measures was a ban on high-level meetings
with Syrians. But Shultz sent Richard W. Murphy, the head of the
Near East bureau, to Damascus two weeks ago to confer with Assad.
   U.S. Ambassador William Eagleton was sent back to his post in
Damascus last September, after a year's absence, and U.N.
Ambassador Vernon A. Walters also visited the country.
   A U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said Shultz was ``most
likely'' to schedule a stop in Syria on his trip to the Middle East
beginning next Thursday.
   Another official said Shultz was ``leaving his options open'' to
return to the area for a few days in early March.
   Shultz plans to be in Brussels with Reagan for a summit meeting
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization on March 2-3. But the
official said Shultz could go to the Middle East from there if
needed and then return to Washington in time to greet visiting the
Chinese foreign minister on March 7.
   Shultz's other stops next week will be Egypt, Jordan, Israel and
probably Saudi Arabia. He is trying to set up negotiations between
Israel and a mixed delegation of Jordanians and Palestinians to
deal especially with the troubled West Bank and Gaza.
   The immediate aim is some form of self-rule for the 1.5 million
Palestinian Arabs who have lived under Israeli control since Egypt
and Jordan lost the territories in the 1967 Six-Day war.
   The long-range goal is to hold a second stage of talks _
possibly in the format of an international peace conference _ by
the end of the year to consider an overall settlement.
   Shultz's separate trip to the Soviet Union began Friday with a
flight to Helsinki, Finland. He will be in Moscow for talks Sunday
with Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Monday with
Shevardnadze and General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Shultz is due to report to the NATO countries in Brussels on
Tuesday and return home for a brief rest before heading for the
Middle East.
   The Middle East is one topic on the Shultz's agenda for Moscow.
So is Afghanistan, where Gorbachev said he would begin a withdrawal
of the Red Army over 10 months, beginning May 15, if a settlement
is reached by March 15.
   Shultz said Thursday in a telecast to Asia that he would ask for
a timetable with ``definite proportions.'' He warned that U.S. aid
to the Afghan rebels would end only if the Soviets stopped helping
the Kabul government.
   The Afghan rebels have been at war with the Kabul government
since 1973. The Soviets sent about 120,000 troops into the country
to back the government in December 1979.
   Shultz supported the establishment of an interim government,
which Pakistan has demanded before an agreement on a Soviet troop
withdrawal is signed. That would mean a coalition government
acceptable to the guerrillas and to the Afghan refugees, about 3
million of whom are in Pakistan.
   In discussing the Middle East in a separate Voice of America
interview, Shultz indicated he was prepared to accept an active
role for the Soviets in the search for a settlement of the
Arab-Israeli dispute.
   ``Obviously, the Soviet Union is a major power, and we will have
to see how this whole process develops,'' he said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir is resisting an active
role in the Middle East for the Soviets, who do not have relations
with his country and regularly support Arab positions. Shultz said
on his last trip to Jerusalem last October that he agreed with
Shamir.
   Jordan and Egypt, however, are demanding an international peace
conference with the Soviets participating.
</TEXT>
