<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalBriefs     02-19 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson, Jackson Deserve Serious Consideration From Respective
Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic and Republican parties
will be forced to give serious consideration to the candidacies of
Jesse Jackson and Pat Robertson despite labels that they are
unelectable, says a former presidential candidate.
   ``People are saying that the candidates with the largest
following, Pat Robertson and Jesse Jackson, have the lowest
probability of success,'' Shirley Chisholm told a Black History
Month audience Thursday night.
   ``But whether you like them or not, their parties will just have
to deal with them when the time comes because they'll both bring a
large block of delegates to the convention,'' she said.
   Robertson finished second among the Republican candidates in the
Iowa caucuses and fifth in the New Hampshire primary. Jackson, a
Democrat, finished fourth in Iowa and New Hampshire.
   Ms. Chisholm, the first black woman ever to win a seat in the
House of Representatives, became known nationally for her fiery
speeches and 1972 campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   She drew a crowd of about 300 people to the University of
Missouri-Kansas City Black History Month activity on the campus.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Organizers Claim to Be Nervous About Massachusetts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of Vice President George Bush's
campaign said Friday they are confident of carrying Massachusetts
on Super Tuesday, but are running as if they're scared.
   ``I think it's important that the vice president win all of his
six home states,'' Ron Kaufman, the Bush political director for the
Northeast, told reporters in a wry reference to Bush's claim to his
Massachusetts birth and his links to other states.
   ``We feel he'll do well here,'' Kaufman said. But he said the
campaign has done no polling that would help define ``well,'' and
he refused to set a specific goal in the Republican voting on March
8.
   On that day, Republicans in 17 states _ most of them in the
South _ will vote on their presidential preferences. Fifty-two
delegates are at stake in Massachusetts.
   ``Political contests are always a challenge,'' said Andy Card,
who was Bush's campaign manager in New Hampshire, where the vice
president won the primary. ``We're going to compete as if we're
worried about Massachusetts.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tipper Gore on Stump in Alabama for Husband's Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tipper Gore told a group of Democratic
women Friday that her husband, Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.,
would open a day care center in the White House if elected
president.
   ``He must encourage corporations and businesses to respond to
this very critical need,'' Mrs. Gore said during a campaign stop in
Huntsville.
   She said the next president must address the issue of working
families and their children, and that means a day care center for
White House employees.
   Mrs. Gore said that because of the increasing number of families
with working parents, American society is currently ``placing a
burden on our work force and our children.''
   Addressing about 60 members of the Madison County Women's
Democratic Club in Huntsville, Mrs. Gore steered clear of her
crusade against pornographic rock lyrics and concentrated on family
issues.
   ``I love rock and roll,'' Mrs. Gore told reporters after her
speech. ``I grew up on it.''
</TEXT>
