<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarterAppeal     02-19 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carter Appeal,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Won't Try Rubin `Hurricane' Carter A Third Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey prosecutors announced Friday they
won't seek a third murder trial against Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter,
ending the former boxer's 22-year campaign for freedom that became
a popular celebrity cause.
   The passage of time, problems finding witnesses, court decisions
discrediting previous testimony and the burden posed by a third
prosecution were cited in legal motions seeking dismissal of the
indictment against Carter and his alleged accomplice, John Artis.
   Acting Passaic County Prosecutor John Goceljak, in papers filed
in Paterson, also said other reasons supporting dismissal were the
intense scrutiny given the case.
   ``It has received the attention of more courts and proceedings
than probably any other case in the history of this state and
possibly any other state,'' the court papers said.
   In addition, Goceljak noted that Carter served 19 years of a
life prison term before a federal judge ordered his release and
Artis has been paroled on the murder conviction. Artis is serving a
six-year term on an unrelated drug conviction.
   A federal judge's finding that their latest conviction was
racially tainted would likely exclude testimony about the motive
for the killings, Goceljak said.
   Three whites were shot by black men on June 17, 1966, hours
after a black man was slain by a white assailant. Carter and Artis
are black.
   Carter's cause was taken up in the 1970s by celebrities such as
Bob Dylan, who wrote and sang ``The Ballad of Hurricane,'' actress
Ellen Burstyn, boxer Muhammed Ali and singer Joan Baez.
   They lionized the former middleweight contender and elevated him
as a symbol of racial injustice. But after a few highly publicized
fund-raising events, some touched by scandal, Carter's all-star
backing faded.
   Goceljak's decision to seek dismissal was made in consultation
with the state's criminal justice director, Donald R. Belsole.
   ``It's time to say enough is enough,'' Belsole said. ``I think
society is served, the system is served and the defendants are
served.''
   A judge must sign the prosecutor's motion to finalize dismissal
of the indictment, and attorney Myron Beldock, in a statement on
behalf of Carter and Artis, said he hoped for quick consideration
by the court.
   ``We are extremely pleased with the decision of the state of New
Jersey to dismiss the case against our clients, and hope that the
appropriate orders will be signed promptly,'' said Beldock.
   Carter, now 50, has been living in seclusion since being freed
in November 1985 by U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin. His
whereabouts could not be determined Friday, and Beldock declined to
give out Carter's home phone number.
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Jan. 11 had let stand Sarokin's
finding that Carter's conviction was tainted because prosecutors
withheld information from the defense.
   Sarokin said the convictions were based on ``an appeal to racism
rather than reason, and concealment rather than disclosure.''
   Defense attorneys all along had considered a third trial
unlikely because testimony from the only eyewitness, Alfred Bello,
had been discredited during appeals.
   ``Resultingly, admission of any relevant testimony by him at a
new trial must be considered problematical at this point,''
Goceljak said in court papers.
   The case began when two black gunmen entered the Lafayette Bar
and Grill in Paterson and killed the bartender and two patrons.
Hours earlier, a black Paterson bartender had been shot to death by
a white man.
   Carter and Artis were arrested three months later and convicted
by an all-white jury in May 1967.
   But Bello and another witness later recanted, saying they had
been pressured by detectives into giving false testimony at the
trial, and the case was reopened in 1974. The New Jersey Supreme
Court reversed the convictions March 17, 1976.
   In a second trial, Carter and Artis were convicted again Dec.
21, 1976, in part with the testimony of Bello, who had retracted
his claims that he was coerced. This time, the state's highest
court upheld the convictions by a 4-3 vote in 1982.
   From there, the case went to federal court and Sarokin's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
