<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 2100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smoker'sSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0704 02-19 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoker's Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoker's Family Seeks Sanctions Against Tobacco Company for Jury
Tampering</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to clarify that people who talked to jurors were
not attorneys but other agents for the tobacco company. SUBS 11th
pvs, bgng, `At issue... with 4 grafs to UPDATE with attorney saying
he filed motion to force company to identify all paid agents. Picks
up 12th graf, `Carlton said ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for American Brands Inc. has
admitted that company representatives talked with jurors during the
trial of a $16.5 million damage suit against the cigarette
manufacturer, but he says the plaintiffs are wrong to call it jury
tampering.
   The family of deceased smoker Nathan Horton, of Durant, had
claimed American Brands should be held liable for his illness and
death. Horton, 50, died Jan. 29, 1987, of emphysema and lung cancer
after 35 years of smoking two packs a day of Pall Mall unfiltered
cigarettes, which are made by American Brands.
   The trial ended Jan. 29 with a hung jury.
   ``There's no question that it's a serious matter to file a
motion of this kind,'' said plaintiff's attorney Don Barrett. He
filed documents Thursday alleging improper jury contact by the
American Brands representatives and seeking a default judgment and
other sanctions against the defendant.
   But Ed Blackmon, one of several local attorneys hired by
American Brands, called the allegations of improper jury contact a
joke.
   ``What you have is a clear attempt by the plaintiff to keep us
from getting a fair trial,'' Blackmon said.
   Blackmon said the alleged improper contact with jurors was to
let jurors know there wouldn't be court that particular day because
the judge was ill.
   ``When you try to make that into a tampering argument, it's what
their case was about: Take what amounts to nothing and turn it into
something,'' he said.
   The Horton family's motion, filed Thursday in Holmes County
Circuit Court, is based on information contained in affidavits
given to District Attorney Frank Carlton.
   It seeks a judgment in the Hortons' behalf on the basis of
American Brand's alleged liability for Horton's lung cancer and
death, as well as attorneys' fees, court costs and expenses in
preparation of the case.
   At issue are allegations that two paid representatives of
American Brand contacted three jurors during the trial, said
Carlton.
   Barrett said Friday four affidavits filed with the court
indicate ``that more than one paid agent of the American Tobacco
Co. illegally and improperly contacted certain members of the
jury'' during the trial.
   ``This agent was not an attorney, but he was mighty well paid,''
said Barrett, declining to name the person.
   Barrett said he had also filed a motion asking the court to
force the tobacco company to provide names ``of each person known
or suspected by either defendant to have been hired or paid by
anybody as a `jury consultant' or otherwise to assist either
defendants or their attorneys in trial preparation or at the trial
... and to state the sums of money paid or owing to each person so
hired, including all persons paid simply to be present in the
courtroom during the trial.''
   Carlton said he picked up four affidavits Tuesday from Holmes
County Circuit Judge Gray Evans, who presided over the monthlong
trial.
   Jurors gave two of the sworn statements, in which they said an
individual contacted them one day during the trial about a
scheduling change in court, Carlton said. Two other affidavits were
made by people who heard an American Brands adviser bragging that
he had been paid $2,700. One of those people also said the adviser
was talking to a juror.
   ``You're not supposed to contact jurors,'' Carlton said.
``You're not even supposed to say, `Good morning.'''
</TEXT>
