<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SuperintendentofYear     02-19 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superintendent of Year,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norfolk Man Named Nation's Top School Superintendent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gene R. Carter, superintendent of the Norfolk,
Va., public schools, was named the first national Superintendent of
the Year on Friday by the American Association of School
Adminstrators.
   The award, announced at the educators' convention in Las Vegas,
includes a gold medallion and a $1,000 U.S. savings bond for Carter
and a $10,000 college scholarship that will go to Carter's hometown
high school.
   Carter attended Booker T. Washington High School in Staunton,
Va., which in those days of legal segregation was for blacks only.
It no longer exists.
   The scholarship will go instead to a student from Robert E. Lee
High School, which now serves all the youths of Staunton. The rules
for deciding who will win the scholarship have not been determined.
   A panel of business, government and education leaders chose
Carter from four finalists, who had been selected earlier from a
field of 38 state finalists.
   The runners-up were: Jack C. Dulaney of the Monongalia schools
in Morgantown, W.Va.; Scott N. Rose of the Pinellas County schools
in Clearwater, Fla., and Robert D. Tschirki of the Littleton,
Colo., schools. Each received a silver medallion and $500 U.S.
savings bond.
   Carter outlined his educational philosophy in this statement:
``Education is power. The belief that knowledge empowers people and
nations is the foundation upon which we must build our commitment
to education. Those of us who lead American public education must
safeguard what could be termed an educational bill of rights for
each student. We need to guarantee simultaneous equity and
excellence for every young person in our nation.''
   Carter said teachers and students need administrators ``who help
them learn. They also need leaders who create a positive and
constructive tone, a climate that will support educational
excellence.''
   The award, sponsored by the ServiceMaster Co. of Downers Grove,
Ill., is patterned after the long-established National Teacher of
the Year competition.
</TEXT>
