<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     02-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Opposition Daily Closed Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editors of the opposition daily
Extra said Friday that the government closed down their publication
again, three weeks after it reopened.
   Cristobal Sarmiento, Extra's publisher, said in an interview
that government officials arrived Thursday night and sealed the
door with an adhesive tape that read ``Closed by the Attorney
General of the Nation.''
   The paper had reopened in January, six months after it was
closed in a general crackdown by the government on opposition news
media after protests started against the leadership of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega, the nation's military chief, is considered the de facto
ruler of Panama, nominally governed by civilian President Eric
Arturo Delvalle.
   A document ordering Extra to be closed said this was done ``to
obtain elements that might serve to prove a punishable deed or to
uncover its authors and participants.''
   Editors said government officials confiscated material ready for
publication in Friday's editions before sealing the door.
   Extra is printed in the opposition daily La Prensa next door,
but is a separate publication. La Prensa reopened last month and
continues to publish.
   Besides Extra, the newspaper El Siglo and the radio stations KW
Continente, La Exitosa and Radio Chiriqui have been closed down by
the government this year.
   Sarmiento was accused last year of publishing information
against the interests of the national economy, but the case was
suspended as part of an amnesty ordered by the national legislature.
   Six news media that had been closed last July reopened as part
of that amnesty.
   The National Banking Commission meanwhile announced Friday that
nearly 50 percent of the local deposits withdrawn from banks in
Panama were returned in the past four months.
   People had withdrawn banking deposits since unrest started last
June with allegations that Noriega had been involved in a wide
range of illicit activities.
   The banking commission said about $103 million of the $208
million withdrawn up to last October had been recovered by private
Panamanian banks and that as a result they had ``strengthened their
liquidity.''
   The commission's statement said about 40 percent of the recovery
was registered during the past five weeks.
   ``By continuing in this way, or better yet, accelerating this
rhythm of recovery, the private Panamanian banks surely will be
able to reactivate soon their credit lending as much for commercial
purposes as for mortgage holders,'' the statement said.
   There are 20 Panamanian and 98 foreign institutions in Panama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
