<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     02-19 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Radio Issues Warnings After Report of Mine Sighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The marine radio in Qatar issued warnings
Friday to vessels in the Persian Gulf after a ship reported what
appeared to be a mine in the shallows off the sheikdom's west coast.
   The radio advised ships to stay clear of that area between
Qatar, which juts north into the gulf from the Arabian Peninsula,
and the island state of Bahrain.
   Shipping executives said a ship that did not identify itself
reported sighting an object that was ``black, with points,'' at
about 4 p.m. There was no confirmation that it was one of the
numerous mines sown in the gulf since the Iran-Iraq war began in
September 1980.
   Waters in that stretch are too shallow for major shipping and
unlikely to have been mined, but a few mines have been found off
Bahrain and Qatar, apparently after drifting down from the northern
gulf.
   Most sightings have turned out to be floating debris ranging
from oil drums to dead sheep with their feet sticking out of the
water.
   A French corvette, the Montcalm, used gunfire to destroy a
floating mine north of Bahrain on Thursday, according a report by
the Kuwaiti news agency that quoted French navy officials in Paris.
   The United States and five European countries are decreasing
their mine-sweeping forces in the gulf after declaring the threat
posed by Iranian mines to be under control.
   Iran said its navy intercepted five foreign ships Thursday in
the Strait of Hormuz, the gulf's narrow southern gate, but let all
of them go when it was found they contained no cargo bound for Iraq.
   Iranian frigates and armed speedboats patrol the strait, which
leads into the Gulf of Oman. They stop ships suspected of trading
with Iraq and sometimes attack neutral vessels in retaliation for
Iraqi air strikes on Iranian coastal shipping.
</TEXT>
