<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunnyvale Shooting,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funerals Begin for Shooting Spree Victims; Suicide Watch Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first of seven memorial services for
victims of the rampage at a Silicon Valley defense plant took place
Friday while officials maintained a suicide watch on the gunman
charged with their deaths.
   About 600 mourners jammed a funeral home for services for Glenda
Moritz, a 27-year-old planner at ESL Inc., the top-secret
electronics plant where police say Richard Wade Farley shot seven
workers to death and wounded three others, including a woman whose
rejection of Farley's advances apparently sparked the massacre.
   Jeanne Pilling, Moritz's roommate and best friend, said the two
spent the night before Tuesday's shooting talking about their
destinies.
   ``Glenda said, `We never know what the future holds for us.
Don't you wish you knew what the future holds?''' Pilling recalled.
``I still don't believe it really happened. She was my very best
friend. I've never been that close to a person in my life.''
   There was no casket; a private burial is planned. Mourners paid
their respects before a display of photos surrounded by dozens of
bouquets.
   ``You've Lost That Loving Feeling,'' by the Righteous Brothers,
was played during the service. Friends said it was one of Moritz's
favorite songs.
   Additional services are planned this weekend for the six others
killed before the computer expert surrendered after 5{ hours.
   Medical authorities said three ESL employees wounded in the
attack, and a fourth who broke her arm trying to escape, are all
recovering, including Laura Black, a 26-year-old technician whom
Farley had pursued relentlessly for four years.
   Farley, 39, was fired from the company 21 months ago for
harassing her, ESL officials said.
   He is being held without bail in solitary confinement in Santa
Clara County Jail, where he has requested a telephone and envelopes.
   He was being held in an isolation cell under a ``welfare
watch,'' which allows guards to maintain close supervision in case
he attempts to take his life and also protects him from attacks by
other inmates, said San Jose County Sheriff's Sgt. Cary Colla.
   ``He has been quiet. He's been polite to staff. As one officer
described it, he seemed to be going through a lot of
self-thought,'' said Colla.
   The docile and quiet portrait of Farley contrasts markedly with
the man police say tormented Black by following her, phoning her,
joining her aerobics class and sending her more than 300 letters.
   ``I want to warn you how far I'm willing to go if you continue
to push me,'' he wrote in one note. ``I once told you I will do
whatever is necessary to see you. Let's say you don't back down and
pretty soon I crack under the pressure and run amok destroying
everything in my path until the police catch me and kill me. ...''
   Black finally obtained a court order to prevent Farley from
bothering her further. The order was final on Wednesday, 12 hours
after Farley marched into the ESL plant carrying 98 pounds of
weaponry and opened fire with a repeating shotgun.
</TEXT>
