<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gingrich-Wright     02-19 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gingrich-Wright,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gingrich To Ask House Ethics Committee To Investigate Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said Friday he will
ask the House ethics committee next month to launch a formal
investigation into allegations of corruption that have been leveled
against Speaker Jim Wright in published reports over the past 10
years.
   Gingrich, a leader of Republican right in the House and a
frequent critic of the ethics of House Democratic leaders, said the
news accounts outline ``clear violations of House rules'' by
Wright, D-Texas, and deserve to be investigated.
   ``The problem that this House faces is that they now have a
speaker who has real problems,'' he said. ``We're going to have to
at least, at a minimum, insist that we find out what the truth is,
and on March 3 I intend to create that opportunity.''
   Neither Wright nor his spokesman were immediately available to
comment on Gingrich's plan to request an investigation.
   Under House rules, any member can ask the ethics committee _
formally called the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct _ to
investigate another member. The panel, composed of six Democrats
and six Republicans, can reject such a request only by a majority
vote.
   Gingrich said it would be ``inconceivable'' that the committee
would refuse to investigate the allegations. But if that happens,
he said he intends to force the issue on the House floor with a
series of privileged votes that could tie up the House for months.
   Gingrich, who lost a House vote last year on his proposal to
create an outside commission to investigate ethics complaints
against Wright and other Democratic leaders, said he was announcing
his intentions to seek an ethics committee investigation now so
other House members could familiarize themselves with the
allegations against Wright.
   He said he chose March 3 as the date to file his complaint
because he wants the committee to have time to complete at least a
preliminary investigation before Congress adjourns for the year.
   Gingrich cited two specific published reports which he said
provide clear evidence that Wright violated House rules. The first
involved Wrights's failure since 1980 to file the required
financial disclosure reports for a company in which he is a partner.
   The second involved 55 percent royalties Wright received for a
book published by a friend whose printing company worked for
Wright's campaign committee. Gingrich said House rules prohibit
members from receiving royalities in excess of ``the usual and
customary value for such services,'' and most authors receive
royalties of 6 percent to 8 percent.
   Gingrich and a political action committee he heads were accused
last month by the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee of
mail fraud for soliciting more than $200,000 in contributions for
conservative candidates through the mails and then providing only
$3,000 to such candidates.
   Gingrich denied the DCCC accusations Friday, characterizing them
as an attempt to discredit him politically so he could not pursue
the ethics complaints against Wright. He also denied that his
actions against Wright were politically motivated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
