<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Rebels     02-19 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Rebels,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Support Plebiscite For Reforming Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's largest leftist guerrilla
group said Friday it supports President Virgilio Barco's attempt to
combat violence by reforming the constitution so he will have more
power.
   The Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, known as the FARC,
said it believes ``a vast majority of the people'' support such a
plebiscite.
   The communique, from the FARC's chiefs of staff, was published
by Colombia's leading daily, El Tiempo, of Bogota.
   The Supreme Court has thwarted Barco's attempts to use state of
siege powers to move against drug traffickers, leftist guerrillas
and right-wing death squads. It found about half of his decrees
unconstitutional.
   Barco proposed last month that Colombia's 1886 Constitution be
reformed through a referendum.
   A 1957 amendment to the constitution prohibits referendums, so
there must first be a plebiscite to lift that ban. Once the ban was
lifted, a constituent assembly would be held to decide how the
constitution should be reformed.
   Barco has not spelled out the reforms he wants, but indicated he
wants to change Colombia's two-chamber congress to one chamber to
speed up legislation; to change the overburdened and corrupt court
system, and to get more power in issuing decrees under a state of
siege.
   A state of siege is on now in Colombia. There has been a state
of siege for all but a few months of the last 40 years.
   Barco belongs to the Liberal party. The opposition Conservative
Party refused to support a plebiscite. Barco has delayed setting a
voting date in hope of promoting national unity on the issue.
   The plebiscite could be as early as March 13, coinciding with
the nationwide election of mayors.
   The FARC said Barco should ignore the Conservatives and see ``if
the people want a new constitution or if they want to stay with the
anachronistic and feudal one of 1886.''
   The FARC is the largest of five guerrilla groups in Colombia.
The army says the FARC has about 5,000 members. FARC leaders claim
to have about 20,000 combatants.
   By reforming the constitution, Barco hopes to have the tools to
stop violence which has been wracking the country for four decades.
   The left has been particularly hurt. More than 400 members of
its Patriotic Union Party were killed in the last two years. Many
of the party's leaders and other members are former FARC guerrillas.
   The party says right-wing death squads run by the military are
behind the killings.
   About 100 members of the Liberal and Conservative parties also
have been killed in the last two years. In many of those cases the
military has blamed leftist guerrillas.
   Colombia also has been hit hard by drug trafficker violence.
   The government says that the traffickers killed a justice
minister, an attorney general, several judges, two newspaper
editors and many others who opposed them over the last four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
