<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 2136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-PLO     02-19 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. To Meet Over U.S. Move To Close PLO Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations plans to reconvene the
159-member General Assembly in an emergency session to consider the
U.S. move to close the Palestine Liberation Organization mission,
U.N. officials said Friday.
   The effort by the U.S. Congress has placed America on a
collision course with the world body. The PLO has formidable
support at the United Nations, which generally votes against the
United States and Israel on Middle East issues.
   Under the U.S. Anti-Terrorism Act of 1987, passed by Congress
and signed by President Reagan on Dec. 22, 1987, the PLO mission at
the United Nations was ordered closed by March 22.
   On Thursday, Arab nations demanded a resumed session to fight
the U.S. action which the United Nations and the U.S. State
Department say violates a legal agreement on the right of missions
to operate.
   In a letter to Peter Florin of East Germany, president of the
General Assembly, the Arab group requested reconvening of the
General Assembly as soon as possible and no later than Feb. 29.
   The 42nd General Assembly completed its agenda in December but
technically is still in session. It can be reconvened at any time
with a request by members and consent of the president.
   Reconvened sessions are not uncommon, but the PLO issue is one
of the most controversial and divisive to be considered.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar ``feels the request
for a resumed session is both timely and understandable,'' U.N.
press spokesman Mario Zamorano told reporters at a briefing Friday.
   Florin will return Wednesday from a visit to Egypt and will
consult with the Arab countries on reconvening the world body, his
spokeswoman, Nadia Youssef, told reporters Friday.
   The PLO and the Arab League previously said they might ask the
assembly to leave New York and meet in Geneva if the PLO Mission is
closed.
   After Congress passed the anti-terrorism measure, the General
Assembly overwhelmingly passed a resolution urging the United
States to leave the PLO mission open.
   The U.S. government itself is divided on the issue. The State
Department has said repeatedly that the treaty obliges the United
States to allow all U.N. missions, including the PLO, to function.
   It now is up to Attorney General Edwin Meese III to decide
whether the mission can remain open.
   Several members of Congress have said Meese told them he would
close the mission, despite the treaty.
   The treaty provides for binding arbitration of disputes between
the United States and the United Nations. Perez de Cuellar said the
United States has so far not agreed to arbitration.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat has said the PLO may take the dispute
to the International Court of Justice in The Hague.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
