<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AviationForecast     02-19 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aviation Forecast,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Sees Air Traffice Increasing Steadily Over Next Dozen Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic will increase steadily over the
next dozen years with air traffic controllers handling a third more
planes in 1999 than they do today, the Federal Aviation
Administration forecast Friday.
   The FAA forecast also shows that the number of people flying
commercial jetliners will grow from about 445 million passengers in
1987 to nearly 765 million in 1999.
   The commuter aircraft are expected to have an even sharper
passenger growth from carrying 27 million people last year to
carrying 58 million annually just before the turn of the century,
according to the FAA's latest aviation forecasts.
   ``What we see is a situation of growth, substantial growth, for
the industry and the FAA,'' John Rodgers, the agency's deputy
director for aviation policy and plans, told an aviation planning
conference.
   The conference focused on problems stemming from the expected
growth in aviation in the coming years. Most aviation experts have
predicted that either through government regulation or some form of
market incentives the nation's aviation system will have to be
constrained because of a shortage of airports and air traffic
control limitiations.
   In a speech, however, Robert Crandall, chairman of American
Airlines, told the group that more attention should be placed on
``how to avoid (air traffic) constraints rather than using up too
many resources talking about how to operate within constraints.''
   Crandall acknowledged that some limitations on aviation growth
might be necessary in the short term, but he said in the long run
``bold action'' is needed to increase airway and airport capacity.
   ``We should not become so focused on constraints that we lose
sight of the need to build an aviation system capable of operating
in the long term ... without the constraints which are increasingly
reducing the industry's efficiency, stifling its growth and
frustrating its customers,'' said Crandall.
   The FAA growth forecast was based on an assumption of an average
3 percent annual economic growth and the absence of intense fare
wars among the airlines. The growth likely would be dampened by
slower economic growth and likely be greater if the airlines were
to engage in a fare battle that would attract more travelers.
   According to the FAA forecast, the number of domestic
enplanements will increase 4.6 percent a year through the end of
this decade while the number of revenue passenger miles - a figure
that reflects a single passenger traveling one mile - will increase
4.8 percent a year.
   The number of flights, however, are expected to increase at a
slower rate, 2.3 percent annually, indicating that airlines will
fly with fewer empty seats and likely move somewhat to larger
aircraft, said the forecast.
   During the next dozen years there will be almost no increase in
the number of general aviation aircraft, although the number of
more sophisticated turbine-powered business aircraft is expected to
increase by about 50 percent, the FAA said.
   ``The demand for FAA operational services is anticipated to
increase over the forecast period as a result of continued strong
growth in aviation activity,'' predicted the FAA.
   The total number of aircraft operations - both commercial and
private -handled at FAA towers and at enroute air traffic control
centers will increase by about 2.4 percent a year, the agency said.
   FAA towers at airports will handle 81.4 million flight
operations by 1999, compared to 61 million last year, the forecast
predicted. The increase in operations handled by enroute air
traffic control centers will stem primarily from increased air
carrier and commuter traffic, the FAA said.
</TEXT>
