<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Satire     02-19 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Satire,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadcast Chief Bans Satire on Israeli Attitudes About Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Israel's government broadcasting
authority has banned a satirical song about alleged Israeli
indifference to the violence in the occupied Arab territories, a
spokeswoman said Friday.
   ``What's Burning'' is about members of a family who intently
watch the American television show ``Dynasty'' while their house
goes up in flames.
   The song is a satirical commentary on the way normal life has
continued for many Israelis during 10 weeks of violence in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. More than 50 Palestinians have
been killed by Israelis in the unrest, according to U.N. figures.
   It was to have been performed on the Friday night entertainment
show ``From Me, Manny,'' one of the highest-rated shows on state
television.
   Spokeswoman Sari Timerman said the song was banned by Uri Porat,
chief of the Israel Broadcasting Authority, who described it as
``maccabre anti-Israeli propaganda in the guise of social satire.
It is based on the lying thesis that the Israeli public is
indifferent ... to what happens here.''
   Several daily newspapers gave front-page coverage to the ban and
published the words of the song in full.
   Four well-known comedians, including Tuvia Zafir, whose
specialty is mimicking Israel's political leaders, act out the
lyrics.
   Zafir portrays the father in a family of four that includes a
wife, a son serving in the army and a younger boy.
   The father, determined to watch ``Dynasty,'' ignores the the
warnings of his younger son about the flames outside.
   Father: ``Don't worry. It won't last. It will be over in a few
minutes.''
   Verse: ``Nothing's burning. Nothing's burning. No reason to get
up. No reason to hurry.''
   Father: ``And as the mature, responsible and experienced one my
motto is: `Sit still and don't do anything.'''
   Even when his clothes catch fire the father doesn't worry. Zafir
sings:
   ``You're so silly, fire, so silly. What do you think, that just
because you're burning me I will think you're endangering my
health? Really now! Go ahead, spread as much as you like. We'll see
which one of us tires faster.''
   The house burns down.
   Father: ``The fire, as I said, will finally be extinguished and
of course time will be on our side.''
   Son: ``But father, we have burned the time.''
   Father: ``Shut up!'' (Slaps him.) ``And whoever takes a look
around''
   Mother: ``Will see that father, as always, is right.''
   Ms. Timerman said Porat was especially angered by a passage in
which the father tells his elder son to get up and put out the
flames, ``but try not to block `Dynasty.'''
   She quoted Porat as saying: ``This is an insult to every Israeli
family. It portrays them as not caring about their soldier-sons and
sending them to do their dirty work.''
</TEXT>
