<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Politics     02-19 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Politics,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goria Wins Vote Of Confidence In The Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Giovanni Goria won a vote of confidence in
the Senate on Friday that completed the resurrection of his shaky
coalition government.
   The Senate voted 170 to 91 to back Goria. The Chamber of
Deputies, the lower house of Parliament, voted 364-208 with four
abstentions on Thursday to support the return of the premier.
   Although the votes of confidence have supported Goria, the
problems that led to his resignation have not been resolved.
   Goria, a Christian Democrat, resigned Feb. 10 after defectors in
his party helped defeat the government 17 times in the Chamber
during secret votes on the proposed budget and spending for
government ministries.
   President Francesco Cossiga rejected the resignation and told
Goria to remain premier to get the budget passed by Parliament
before the April 30 deadline.
   Goria's five-party coalition, Italy's 47th postwar government,
has been shaky since he took office last July. The coalition
includes the Christian Democrats, the Socialists and three tiny
parties, the Social Democrats, Republicans and Liberals.
   The premier, who at 44 is the youngest to ever hold the post,
also resigned in November during a dispute with the Liberals.
However, Cossiga later persuaded him to withdraw his resignation.
</TEXT>
