<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Gays     02-19 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Gays,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Asks For Support From Lesbians, Gays</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson on Friday asked for the support
of homosexuals during a presidential campaign appearance at an
inner-city church led by a lesbian pastor.
   ``I stood with you,'' the Democratic candidate said. ``Now make
me a president.''
   The Rev. Arlene Ackerman, pastor of All God's Children
Metropolitan Community Church, said Jackson was the only
presidential candidate to join gays and lesbians when they marched
on Washington, D.C., in October.
   ``He's not afraid to dignify us by championing our causes,''
said Bill Dorn, a former Catholic priest who is gay.
   Jackson, who drew a capacity crowd of about 1,000 to the church,
said other candidates have avoided making appearances with gay and
lesbian groups.
   ``They were afraid that being close to you would make them look
unpresidential,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson said he supports legislation in Congress that calls for
an end to discrimination based on sexual orientation. He also said
he supports a massive, federally funded AIDS prevention and
education campaign.
   ``I hope you do consider me to be your friend,'' Jackson said.
``I affirm your humanity and your rights under the law.''
   Jackson urged the crowd to attend Minnesota's precinct caucuses
on Tuesday.
   ``Don't pull for me and vote for someone else,'' he said. ``Put
your oath and votes in the same trough.''
</TEXT>
