<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Violence     02-19 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Violence,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Die in Bombings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh separatists set off bombs near
courthouses in four major cities in Punjab state Friday, killing
nine people and injuring more than 60, police said.
   Three other people were shot to death in separate attacks in the
northern state, where militant Sikhs are waging a war for an
independent homeland. More than 230 people have been killed this
year in violence blamed on Sikhs.
   Police in New Delhi issued a ``red alert'' after the explosions
and asked people not to touch abandoned objects such as boxes, bags
and briefcases.
   Ravi Pawar, a police spokesman, said intelligence information
indicated that Sikh terrorists may be planning to explode bombs in
busy areas in the capital.
   The bombs in Punjab blew up in or near courthouse compounds in
the cities of Gurdaspur, Amritsar, Patiala and Hoshiarpur, killing
nine people. Fifty people were detained in the Sikh holy city of
Amritsar for questioning in connection with one explosion, police
reports said.
   In Patiala, a powerful bomb blew up in a soda water factory in
front of the district court building, killing three Hindus and
injuring one.
   The blast at a courthouse in Hoshiarpur killed three people,
including a woman, police said. Two others were injured.
   J.P. Birdhi, senior superintendent of police in Gurdaspur, said
two people died and 33 people were injured, six of them seriously,
in a blast there.
   In Amritsar, assailants lobbed a bomb over a wall into a crowd
outside the court. One person was killed and 19 others were
wounded, said Izhar Alam, the city police chief.
   He said a homemade bomb was discovered inside a liquor bottle
left in a cinema hall filled with 200 people. It was turned over to
bomb experts and no one was injured.
   Also Friday, four Sikh extremists gunned down a security guard
at a bank in Patiala, police said.
   Sikhs are a religious minority in India, representing 2 percent
of the 780 million population, but they are a majority in Punjab
state.
   The state has been under direct federal rule since Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi dismissed the moderate Sikh state government
last year for failing to curb terrorism.
   More than 1,000 people were killed last year in attacks blamed
on Sikhs.
</TEXT>
