<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Higgins-Weinberger 1stLd-Writethru a0815$aea3e</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Higgins-Weinberger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0815,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: New throughout with details of Higgins' background, quotes
from Pentagon officials</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon acknowledged late Friday that the
Marine officer kidnapped in Lebanon earlier this week was a former
military aide to the secretary of defense.
   A spokesman dismissed suggestions, however, that the capture of
Lt. Col. William ``Rich'' Higgins posed any type of major security
risk to the United States.
   Higgins was the junior military assistant to Defense Secretary
Caspar W. Weinberger for two years, said Dan Howard, the Pentagon's
chief spokesman. Weinberger resigned Nov. 5 and was succeeded by
Frank Carlucci.
   As Weinberger's assistant from June 1985 to June 1987, Higgins
had access to and handled a variety of classified documents, but
was only one of 36 individuals ``who worked in the immediate office
of the secretary handling administrative work,'' Howard said.
   Higgins was kidnapped on Wednesday in Lebanon, where he was
assigned to temporary duty with the United Nations heading a group
of observers attached to the U.N. Truce Supervision Organization.
   Howard provided a statement to reporters late Friday after Radio
Free Lebanon broadcast a story in Arabic quoting unnamed Amal
Shiite Moslems as saying Higgins had ``an association with
Weinberger.''
   The spokesman said the Pentagon had played down Higgins'
background over the past two days because it did not want to
aggravate the situation surrounding his kidnapping.
   But the United States does not believe he was kidnapped because
he once worked for Weinberger, Howard said, nor were any
restrictions violated in allowing him to leave a post in the
defense secretary's office for another assignment in a country like
Lebanon.
   ``There was no restriction that was broken by his accepting this
assignment,'' Howard said. ``He (previously) handled paperwork and
other administrative duties.
   ``There are no restrictions on where middle-grade officers like
Lt. Col. Higgins can be assigned following Pentagon duty. His
understanding of political-military affairs and his administrative
abilities made him well suited for the (U.N.) position.
   Howard said that ``for the moment, we prefer to focus our
attention on his prompt and safe return, rather than on
unproductive speculation on how and why this particular individual
found himself in this predicament.''
   Asked then if the administration equated Higgins' disappearance
to the kidnapping of William Buckley several years ago, Howard
replied: ``No.''
   Buckley was the CIA station chief in Lebanon and was later
tortured and murdered by his kidnappers.
   Higgins, 43, is a native of Danville, Ky., whose wife and
daughter now live in northern Virginia. His wife, Robin, is a major
in the Marine Corps.
   A decorated combat veteran of Vietnam, Higgins has alternated
between field positions and staff jobs in Washington through most
of his career. After graduating from the Air Force Command and
Staff College in 1980, Higgins assumed a post in the plans division
at Marine Corps headquarters.
   In June 1981, he was transferred to the Pentagon and to the
second-level staff serving the secretary and deputy secretary of
defense. In 1982, he became the military assistant for interagency
matters under the Pentagon's executive secretary, meaning he was
responsible for coordinating Weinberger's meetings with other
Cabinet officials and the National Security Council.
   After leaving that post and graduating from the National War
College in 1985, Higgins became the junior military assistant on
Weinberger's personal staff.
   The secretary of defense normally has two such personal military
aides _ one an admiral or general and the other a lower-ranking
officer such as Higgins.
   Higgins remained in the job with Weinberger until June 1987,
when he assumed the U.N. assigment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
