<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Kidnap 2ndLd-Writethru a0797 02-19 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Kidnap, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0797,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Americans Won't Be Pulled Out Of UN Observer Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 3 grafs after 4th graf bgng: Denying that ... to
UPDATE with Pentagon statement saying Higgins had worked for
Weinberger. Picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: Fewer than ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday that Americans
will not be pulled out of the U.N. observer group in Lebanon
despite the threat of terrorism and the kidnapping of Marine Lt.
Col. William R. Higgins.
   Reagan made his statement after Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci said in a television interview that U.S. officials were
studying whether Americans should be withdrawn from Lebanon because
of the abduction of Higgins by gunmen in southern Lebanon.
   The president said he was reluctant to answer questions during a
photo-taking session in the Oval Office, but that ``on this
particular subject, I feel I must straighten it out.''
   Denying that Americans would be pulled out, Reagan said, ``We
are going to meet our obligations to the United Nations.''
   Meanwhile, the Pentagon acknowledged Friday evening that Higgins
had been a military aide to the secretary of defense. A spokesman
dismissed suggestions that Higgins' capture posed a major security
risk to the United States, and said he did not believe Higgins'
capture had anything to do with the fact that he had been a junior
military assistant to Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon spokesman, said Higgins ``handled
paperwork and other administrative duties'' for Weinberger from
June 1985 to June 1987. He said the administration did not equate
Higgins' capture to that of William Buckley several years ago.
Buckley was the CIA station chief in Lebanon when he was captured,
tortured and murdered by his kidnappers.
   The Pentagon provided a statement on Higgins' background after
Radio Free Lebanon broadcast a story quoting unnamed Amal Shiite
Moslems as saying Higgins had ``an association with Weinberger.''
   Fewer than 20 Americans are assigned to U.N. duties along the
Lebanese-Israeli border, according to the State Department.
   Reagan said U.N. forces had been in Lebanon since 1949. ``We're
very definitely a part of the United Nations.''
   Speaking about the threat of terrorism, the president said, ``Of
course we worry because we know that terrorists around the world
targeted us as one of their targets.''
   As reporters left the room, Reagan turned to his guest, West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and said, ``They didn't ask the
question I wanted them to ask.'' Reagan indicated he wanted to
elaborate on his comment Thursday that he wanted to ``rescue''
Higgins.
   However, when reporters shouted a question about the ``rescue''
remark as the president left for a weekend at Camp David, he did
not respond.
   Administration officials already had clarified Reagan's remark,
saying he was referring to diplomatic efforts through the United
Nations and governments in the region. Reagan's comment to Kohl was
picked up by a boom microphone.
   Earlier in the day, Carlucci had said ``everything possible'' is
being done to secure the release of Higgins, the head of a 75-man,
multinational observer group attached to the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon.
   Higgins was abducted Wednesday in southern Lebanon.
   Asked on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show if other Americans assigned to
the effort would be withdrawn, Carlucci said: ``No decision has
been made. We are examining their security situation.''
   Carlucci said that while the Americans' safety is the
responsibility of the U.N., ``obviously we are concerned about our
people and will work with the U.N. on it.''
   Meanwhile, in Lebanon, a pro-Iranian group calling itself the
Oppressed of the Earth said it had kidnapped Higgins, and released
identity cards bearing his photograph.
   It claimed that Higgins was doing undercover work for the CIA.
However, the State Department has denied that Higgins had any links
with the CIA.
   The group said it would release Higgins following a complete
Israeli withdrawal from its security zone in south Lebanon. It also
demanded the release of an estimated 300 Lebanese and Palestinian
prisoners held in Khiam detention camp in south Lebanon and the
immediate cessation of U.S. activity in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
