<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0777,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede TAMPA, Fla.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs new with Lexington appearance; pick up 2nd pvs
bgng ``We decided...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole said Friday he is not shaken
by his loss in the New Hampshire presidential primary and will fare
well in South Dakota and Minnesota, adding ``we'll see who's
dispirited Wednesday morning next week.''
   Dole also predicted he would do well in the South on Super
Tuesday because many voters ``are last-minute Christmas shopping''
for a candidate.
   ``We would have liked to have won New Hampshire, but we didn't.
So you back off a couple of days and get charged up again,'' Dole
said.
   ``We're ready to go. We're ready for the next round in South
Dakota and Minnesota and we'll see who wins those two. We'll see
who's dispirited Wednesday morning next week.''
   The Bush campaign said Friday it was pulling out of South
Dakota, bowing to Dole's strength there.
   In Tampa, Fla., Dole said he decided 10 days ago to skip the
Friday night debate in Dallas, but he never tried to persuade
fellow Republican presidential candidate Pat Robertson to do the
same.
   ``We decided one Houston was enough,'' Dole said of his own
decision during a news conference. In Houston, he said the audience
was stacked with backers of rival GOP candidate Vice President
George Bush.
   Dole denied news reports that he tried to persuade Robertson to
join him in dropping out of Friday night's debate in Dallas, which
Dole has criticized as being stacked in favor of Bush.
   Dole said he and Robertson recently had a 20-minute talk and a
couple of brief hallway encounters in New Hampshire while they were
snowbound at the same hotel.
   ``We talked about the campaign. That's about it,'' Dole said. He
denied a report that he tried to influence Robertson to skip Dallas
during one of the hallway meetings.
   ``I just gave him the facts,'' said Dole, adding that he told
Robertson of the ticket allocation, which he has said favors Bush.
   Dole said it appeared he would get 60 tickets out of some 2,600
available. ``It didn't seem fair to us and there'd be other
opportunities for debate,'' Dole said.
   Burl Osborne, editor of the Dallas Morning News, one of the
debate's sponsors, rejected as untrue Dole's complaint that his
campaign didn't get as many tickets to the event as Bush's forces
did.
   Osborne said Friday it appeared Dole and Robertson ``made their
decision together.'' He said he asked both camps to reconsider, but
Robertson said he would attend only if Dole did.
   Dole labeled as incorrect published reports that he and
Robertson were teaming up to try to stop Bush in the South.
   A somber sounding Dole brought his campaign to Florida,
stressing themes of leadership and issues. He refrained from
attacking Bush, a formidable foe in the Sunshine State where son,
Jeb Bush, is state commerce secretary and Gov. Bob Martinez, a
Democrat-turned Republican, has publicly stated his support for the
vice president.
   ``Obviously Florida is a big cog. It's very important to all of
us,'' the Kansas senator said of Super Tuesday, the March 8 primary
in 20 states, including 14 in the South.
   ``In Florida, we'll discuss issues, issues of concern to the
people,'' including deficit reduction, trade, agriculture, drugs,
Medicare and Social Security, Dole said.
</TEXT>
