<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AFL-CIO-CentralAmerica     02-19 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AFL-CIO-Central America,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Federation Asks Honduras To Keep Contras Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO called Friday on Honduras
to deny use of its territory to Nicaraguan Contra rebels and said
it wants an investigation of allegations that high-ranking Honduran
military officers are involved in drug trafficking.
   In an intensely negotiated statement on Central America, the
U.S. labor federation also condemned what it called the Nicaraguan
government's continued political imprisonment of 16 trade union
leaders.
   After supporting the withdrawal of U.S. military aid to the
Contras for the first time at its convention in October, the
AFL-CIO said it is time to exert increased public pressure for
ending Soviet and Cuban military aid to Nicaragua.
   As usual, foreign policy issues proved to be the most
contentious among the labor leaders at the meeting of the AFL-CIO
executive council.
   Jack Sheinkman, president of the 300,000-member Amalgamated
Clothing and Textile Workers Union, wanted the AFL-CIO to call on
President Reagan to undertake negotiations with the Soviet Union on
withdrawal of all outside military involvement in Central America.
   The AFL-CIO council overwhelmingly rejected Sheinkman's
proposal, but it did include his language in a four-page policy
statement noting that the Sandinista government has ``belatedly
ended its state of siege'' in Nicaragua.
   Earlier this week, the federation criticized ``the use of
excessive force'' by Israeli military forces against Palestinian
civilians over the past two months in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   But at a reception Thursday night hosted by Israeli trade
unions, AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland complained that the
criticism _ the first ever by the federation of Israeli actions in
the Middle East _ had been misinterpreted as a condemnation of
Israel itself.
   He called the federation's statement ``one of the strongest
reaffirmations of AFL-CIO support for the democratic state of
Israel ... that we have ever made.''
</TEXT>
