<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LibelTrial     02-19 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libel Trial,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Man $1 Million In Libel Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was briefly jailed on
suspicion of rape but never charged was libeled by a newspaper that
reported his arrest, a jury found Friday in ordering the paper to
pay him $1 million.
   The verdict against the Battle Creek Enquirer came under a new
standard for libel set by Michigan's Supreme Court.
   ``I'm just so happy. It's been a long time coming,'' said the
plaintiff, David Rouch, 52. ``I just know it's going to help other
people, too.''
   The six-member Calhoun County jury deliberated nearly four hours
over two days before returning the verdict. Rouch, a mechanic for a
cereal company, had sought $500,000.
   The newspaper, which is owned by the Gannett Co., will appeal,
said Robert Bernius, attorney for the Battle Creek Enquirer.
   The suit claimed Rouch suffered humiliation, emotional distress
and damage to his reputation because the newspaper reported his
1979 arrest on suspicion of raping a 17-year-old baby sitter.
   The suit initially sought $1 million, but Judge Stephen Miller
on Thursday threw out the half of the suit asking for punitive
damages, which he said could not be awarded because Rouch had
failed to prove the paper acted with malice.
   But Rouch was able to seek actual damages under a new standard
for libel set by Michigan's Supreme Court, which ordered the case
to trial.
   The high court said libel could be found in cases in which a
publication was negligent, or in which it failed to exercise
reasonable care in publishing information.
   That ruling set aside an earlier standard that said the
information, to be libelous, had to be published with malice, or
with knowledge of its falsity.
   After his arrest in 1979, Rouch spent about seven hours in jail,
then was released on personal recognizance bond and ordered to
appear for arraignment, or formal charging.
   The case against against went no further, and police four months
later arrested and charged another man. Charges against the second
man later were dismissed.
   The newspaper printed a retraction one year later after
receiving complaints from Rouch and his attorney.
   Rouch wiped his eyes after the verdict was read and rushed to a
telephone to call his son with the news.
   ``About this retraction, if they had printed it three or four
days later, I wouldn't have sued,'' Rouch said at a tavern where he
celebrated with friends. ``I wouldn't have done anything.''
   Bernius and newspaper publisher Robert Miller Jr. declined
comment beyond saying there would be an appeal.
</TEXT>
