<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Char 2ndLd-Writethru a0845 02-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Char, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0845,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poet Rene Char Dies at 80</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to omit reference to Spanish Civil War. SUBS
11th pvs: `He fought ...' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rene Char, called ``the greatest French poet of the
20th century'' by Premier Jacques Chirac, died in Paris Friday,
according to the publishing company Gallimard. He was 80.
   Gallimard said he died at the military hospital of Val-de-Grace.
It did not disclose the cause of death.
   Among Char's most famous poems are ``Hammer Without a Master,''
written in 1934, and ``Return Uphill,'' written in 1966.
   ``Hammer Without a Master'' was later set to music by Pierre
Boulez.
   Char also wrote criticism and plays for nearly half a century.
   ``Rene Char was without doubt the greatest French poet of the
20th century,'' Chirac said in a statement.
   Char is to be buried Tuesday in Isle-sur-la-Sorgue, the
Provencal village where he was born on June 14, 1907.
   His poetry borrowed imagery from nature and from his childhood
in southern France.
   After completing his education at the university in
Aix-en-Provence, he moved to Paris where he became friendly with
the Surrealists Andre Breton and Paul Eluard.
   Char also was friends with the artists Pablo Picasso, Georges
Braque and Nicolas de Stael.
   He fought against the forces of rebel General Francisco Franco
in the Spanish Civil War and led a Resistance unit in the French
Alps during World War II under the nom de guerre ``Captain
Alexander.''
   He was later awarded the Medal of the Resistance and the Croix
de Guerre and was named to the Legion of Honor.
   In 1945, Char moved to the Luberon mountains, not far from his
birthplace.
   ``In our darkness, there is not a place for beauty,'' he once
said. ``Every place is for beauty.''
</TEXT>
