<2ND_LINE>AM-Cal Winds, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0767,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Ana Winds Bring Death, Widespread Damage and Power Outages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE number homeless to 56; SUBS 6th graf,
`The death ...' with tree dimension; SUBS 8th graf, `Falling trees
...' to UPDATE number of trees; INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf,
`Thirty utility ...' with quote; Picks up 10th graf, `Offshore,
Coast ...'; SUBS grafs 14-16, `About 25 ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
homeless numbers; Picks up 17th graf, `Fallen power ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second blast of fierce Santa Ana winds in
a week raked southern California, felling trees that killed a
child, downing dozens of power lines and fanning fires that left 56
people homeless Friday.
   Damage to campuses and danger from flying debris forced a school
district to cancel classes for 20,000 students, and the Coast Guard
searched the stormy ocean for a missing yachtsman.
   The latest blast of high wind hit late Thursday and before dawn
Friday and reached 70 mph at Monument Peak in San Diego County,
where Interstate 8 was temporarily closed, and 50 mph at Ontario
International Airport, the National Weather Service said.
   However, high wind warnings were canceled when the
wind-generating high pressure system over Nevada and Utah weakened.
The wind whistling over the mountains, deserts and coastal canyons
was expected to end by Saturday morning.
   Santa Ana winds are caused by high pressure areas over Utah and
Nevada which send air flowing down into California. Although they
are commonly associated with insufferable summer heat, Santa Anas
are very common in February, said weather service forecaster Bob
Grebe.
   The death toll for the week's winds reached five late Thursday
when gusts up to 60 mph hit Yosemite National Park, knocking down a
180-foot ponderosa pine that crushed 9-year-old Jasmine Bitts of
Garden Grove, Calif., when it fell on a cabin. The girl's mother
and a companion suffered minor injuries.
   Hundreds of campers were ordered from the area, but it was
reopened by midmorning, said park spokeswoman Lisa Dapprich.
   Twenty trees fell in the area, damaging five cabins and a number
of vehicles, she said.
   Thirty utility poles toppled in the morning in San Bernardino
County, blacking out 6,300 Southern California Edison customers in
the Rialto area, said spokeswoman Pat Messigian. The Los Angeles
Department of Water and Power reported 28,000 customers with
outages. In all, 112,000 customers lost power at one time or
another.
   SoCal Edison area manager Ray Gonzalez estimated gusts ranged
from 80 mph to 90 mph where the poles were downed. He said he came
across 22 downed poles on his way to work and saw other poles fall
when he went out on a survey.
   ``I heard a snap, looked behind me and noticed that six poles
just fell down,'' he said. No one was hurt.
   Offshore, Coast Guard aircraft and a cutter searched for Chris
Dodd, 28, of Los Altos, who was reported overdue Thursday. His
30-foot boat failed to show up Wednesday in San Pedro after setting
sail from Santa Catalina Island in high seas, said Petty Officer
James McPherson.
   The Fontana school district, below the San Gabriel Mountains 50
miles east of Los Angeles, gave 20,100 students the day off Friday
because of the wind, said Carl Coleman, a district planning
official.
   One school had roof damage and gusts destroyed covered walkways
at a high school, he said.
   In Los Angeles, six people were injured when an unfinished
apartment building caught fire shortly after midnight and
wind-swept embers spread the blaze to a 10-unit apartment complex
and four other structures.
   Twenty-four people were left homeless. Damage was put at
$345,000.
   In East Los Angeles, an early morning fire in a commercial
building spread to three houses before firefighters doused it, said
Los Angeles County fire spokesman Bob Haskell.
   Twenty-three people were left homeless by that fire, which was
caused when wind-blown electrical wires touched and created a short
circuit over a roofing company, sending sparks onto two propane
tanks. Damage was estimated at $500,000.
   Another fire in the Mount Washington area forced nine people
from their homes.
   Fallen power lines set a home ablaze in suburban La Canada
Flintridge but firefighters stopped the flames from spreading. A
family of four was treated for smoke inhalation.
   ``We were lucky. It could have been a major disaster,'' said
fire Battalion Chief Frank Reavis.
   Earlier in the week, the high wind caused four deaths.
   One man was electrocuted when a power line blew down and the
other three were killed in a highway accident triggered when a
truck buffeted by wind slewed off a highway and into two stopped
cars.
   An estimated 500,000 utility customers lost power during
Wednesday's wind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
