<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 2238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Soviets     02-19 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Soviets,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Fighter Planes Intercept Soviet Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Air Force fighters intercepted two Soviet
bombers off the east coast of Canada on Friday evening, according
to a brief statement issued by the Canadian Department of National
Defense.
   NORAD, the North American Air Defense Command, detected the
long-range Tupolev Bears by radar when they entered the Canadian
Air Defense Identification Zone without notification, the
department said.
   The incident marks the fifth time this year that Soviet military
aircraft have been intercepted. The interception was under
operational control of the Canadian NORAD Region Headquarters in
North Bay, Ontario, the statement said.
   Interceptor aircraft stand on 24-hour alert to be scrambled
within five minutes if an incoming aircraft is detected by radar
and cannot be correlated with a flight plan.
   The interceptor force carries out the NORAD task of controlling
access to sovereign Canadian and U.S. airspace in peacetime and, in
the event of hostilities, would provide defense against an attack
on North America from bombers and cruise missiles.
   NORAD, based in Cheyenne Mountain near Colorado Springs, Colo.,
controls Canadian and American air defense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
