<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Rocket 2ndLd-Writethru a0867 02-19 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rocket, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0867,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media Report Rocket Failed, Three Satellites Destroyed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-9 ``In Colorado...square feet.'' with 5 grafs to
UPDATE with largest piece of debris re-entering atmosphere, size of
smallest and largest pieces. CORRECTS agency to Space Command, sted
NORAD.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet rocket failed after its launch and
destroyed three satellites, and U.S. defense officials said Friday
the accident sent large chunks of debris hurtling to Earth.
   The official Tass news agency, in a rare report of mishap in the
Soviets' commercial space program, gave few details of the
accident. The untimely release of the satellites suggests the
unmanned Proton rocket exploded.
   Tass said in its dispatch Thursday that the destroyed satellites
_ named Cosmos 1917, 1918 and 1919 _ were designed to test elements
and equipment of a space navigation system.
   Kremlin officials have touted the Soviet space program as a
reliable means of deploying weather and navigation equipment for
foreign organizations in the wake of similar failures in the U.S.
space program.
   In Colorado Springs, Colo., U.S. Space Command officials said
debris believed to be from the blast landed off Australia and
somewhere between Saudi Arabia and Turkey.
   The largest chunk, believed to be the fourth stage and payload,
re-entered the earth's atmosphere Friday afternoon between Saudi
Arabia and Turkey, said spokesman Cmdr. Dugald Gillies.
   It was not known whether any of that debris, estimated to
measure about 100 square feet, actually hit the earth's surface,
said Gillies.
   Bob Hollie, another Space Command spokesman, said the portion of
rocket that landed near Australia measured about 72 square feet.
   ``We do have another piece up there but it is significantly
smaller and still orbiting with no predicted re-entry time. It is
maybe a meter (yard) by a meter'' in size, said Hollie.
   Tass said the Proton rocket was launched Wednesday, ``but
because of a malfunction in this unit the sputniks could not be
placed on the required orbit.''
   Tass said the rocket placed the separation unit holding the
satellites on an interim orbit, but the system then malfunctioned
and the satellites fell from orbit.
   ``On February 18 the sputniks entered dense layers of the
atmosphere and ceased their existence,'' it said.
   Soviet rockets each year carry dozens of satellites into orbit
for national use and for foreign contractors, primarily from
Kremlin-allied nations.
   Tass announced last August that a 10-ton satellite had failed to
reach orbit. The report apparently was the first time Soviets
announced beforehand that one of its satellites was dropping from
orbit.
   That satellite fell into the ocean without causing any damage or
injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
