<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Feb. 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>What Does Willard Want?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I'm the No. 1 attraction in every supermarket parkin' lot.
   ``I'm the king of Kansas City, no thanks, Omaha, thanks a lot.''
   _ Roger Miller.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willard Scott is a national version of Roger
Miller's ``Kansas City Star,'' the quintessential local celebrity
who turns down a better deal in a bigger city because, among other
things, ``I got credit down at the grocery story and my barber
tells me jokes.''
   ``I think about that a thousand times a day,'' Scott says with
customary exaggeration when reminded of the song. He loves
everyone. Every town is his favorite. Every organization the
greatest. His secret is that it's all true.
   ``I guard against being cynical or smart, I just don't like that
whole approach to life,'' he says, sitting in his small NBC office,
crammed full of memorabilia and gifts.
   In 1980, Scott moved to NBC in New York from the relative
small-towniness of the local affiliate in Washington, D.C., where
he had been Bozo the Clown on a kiddie show, and later the local
weatherman. In the big city, a lot of people thought he was a
phony, he said.
   ``In the beginning, I really ran into that, especially around
here. But that didn't last but about six months to a year. I have a
pretty good sense of what's going on.''
   He knocks on wood and adds, ``As soon as you say that you get
the slip. But in the first three months, the mail was tremendous.
Eight hundred letters a day, about half of 'em negative. But that
didn't bother me. Worse than gettin' bad mail is no mail.''
   Scott, who has made several appearances as neighbor Mr. Poole in
the hit NBC sitcom ``Valerie's Family'' this season, is negotiating
a new contract with ``Today.'' Executive producer Marty Ryan says
Scott is close to signing a new, long-term deal.
   Scott, who likes to tell how he once turned down an offer of
McDonald's stock now worth $7 million and passed up 3,000 acres of
prime Blue Ridge Mountain land worth $25 million, said he
nevertheless will stay with ``Today'' rather than take a new gamble
_ on his own sitcom.
   The producers of ``Valerie's Family,'' Tom Miller and Bob
Boyett, liked him as recurring character Peter Poole so much they
are considering a spinoff.
   Miller calls a spinoff of the Pooles a ``definite possibility.''
   Meanwhile, he said, ``we think he's a terrific addition to
`Valerie's Family.' He's a very hard person not to like. He has no
airs. He really is one of the most genuine and open and kind men
that I've ever met in this business.''
   Scott has appeared on the sitcom three times this season, and
one more appearance is in the works.
   One obstacle to a sitcom is Scott's insistence that he stay in
the East. He goes home to Virginia every weekend, usually doing his
``Today'' weather segments from Washington, D.C., on Friday and
Monday.
   ``What I'm saying is if I have a choice of doing a sitcom or
staying on the `Today' show, I'd rather stay on the `Today' show,''
Scott said.
   ``I'm 53. I mean, I get one cell or one heart muscle thump the
wrong way, and I'd be deader than hell, and I don't want to do that
and be out there (in California), I want to be home.''
   While it's an ``an effort for me to act,'' he says, the
``Today'' show routine is ``like water off a duck's back.''
   ``And besides,'' he says, ``it's all over at 9 o'clock. I can
hop on the plane and get out of there, go home. That's what I want.
I want time. But I don't want to give up the money, I don't want to
give up the ego, I don't want to give up the notoriety, the
publicity, you know, that's a very seductive force.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SHE WRITES `MURDER' ON CABLE _ USA Network has landed another
network series bound for syndication, CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,''
starring Angela Lansbury. The reruns will begin a run on the cable
network this fall. The show is still CBS' highest-rated prime-time
show. USA previously got a pre-syndication deal on NBC's ``Miami
Vice.'' ...
   YO, PAULI, DID YOU HEAR THAT? _ NBC's ``Crime Story'' will
explain how villain Ray Luca and hapless sidekick Pauli Taglia
managed to escape a nuclear explosion that concluded last season.
In plugging the March 1 episode, ``Pauli Taglia's Dream,'' NBC says
the pair's escape from the blast ``was almost equal to their
dealings afterwards with government agents who had other
experiments in mind.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Feb. 22</NOTE>
