<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Black&Decker Bjt   02-19 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black & Decker, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Standard Board Proposes Recapitalization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. is attempting to woo
shareholders away from a hostile $2.03 billion bid by Black &
Decker Corp. with a rival recapitalization plan offering a $1.9
billion payout plus a stake in the recapitalized company.
   American Standard's board of directors approved the proposal on
Thursday, just over a week after it rejected Black & Decker's
$65-a-share hostile tender offer.
   American Standard said its plan it would pay $59 in cash plus
high-yielding debt securities it valued at $5 for each of the
company's 31.1 million outstanding shares.
   Shareholders also would receive one common share of the
recapitalized company for each of the common shares they held
currently, although the total number of shares in the recapitalized
company would be greater.
   American Standard stock rose 50 cents to close at $67.50 a share
and Black & Decker dipped 12{ cents to $18.87{ on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Recapitalizations, in which a company realigns its levels of
debt and equity, have become a frequently used takeover defense
because the company often takes on a big debt load that makes it a
less attractive target.
   American Standard, for example, would see its long-term debt
jump to about $2.3 billion from roughly $412 million. The company
planned to pay off the debt with its cash flow rather than by
selling assets, according to sources familiar with the plan.
   American Standard did not estimate the impact of the plan on the
company's earnings. Last year, it earned $127.1 million on sales of
$3.4 billion. William Boyd, American Standard's chairman and chief
executive, said earlier this month estimated profits would rise by
about 20 percent this year, excluding the impact of a takeover.
   A Black & Decker spokeswoman at the company's Towson, Md.,
headquarters did not return a telephone call seeking comment
Thursday.
   ``The recapitalization not only gives the stockholders
significantly higher value than the $65 being offered in Black &
Decker's tender, but also enables them to retain a substantial
ongoing equity interest in a viable American Standard,'' Boyd said
in a statement.
   In addition to giving public shareholders new stock in the
recapitalized company, American Standard also would convert the
1.23 million of its shares held by an employee savings and stock
ownership plan into shares of the recapitalized company at a ratio
to be determined later.
   American Standard said that using the ratio of 10.15-to-one as
an example, the number of its outstanding common shares plus
equivalents such as stock options would more than double, to 65.4
million from 32.2 million.
   The plan must be approved by shareholders and is subject to
sufficient financing being arranged. A special shareholders meeting
is planned for April to consider the proposal, the company said.
   American Standard said it planned to finance the
recapitalization with $1.59 billion in bank borrowing and the sale
of $225 million in senior subordinated debentures.
   Separately, a federal judge in Delaware deferred a decision on
Black & Decker's constitutionality challenge to Delaware's new
takeover law.
   Attorneys said U.S. District Court Judge Joseph Longobardi
planned to rule in about a week on the Black & Decker lawsuit
against the state and American Standard, which is incorporated in
Delaware.
   The law severely limits a hostile buyer's ability to sell a
target company's assets to finance a takeover. Black & Decker has
indicated it planned several major divestitures of American
Standard property to help finance its buyout if successful.
   After American Standard last week rejected its $65-a-share
offer, Black & Decker said it would seek shareholder approval to
win control of the company's board of directors.
   Black & Decker, a maker of appliances and power tools, has said
it had commitments for $750 million in financing for its offer and
its banker was confident it could raise another $1.25 billion in
bank loans.
   American Standard manufactures plumbing and air conditioning
equipment, automotive brakes and mass-transit control devices.
</TEXT>
