<DOCNO> AP880219-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Disney-Meeting Bjt   02-19 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disney-Meeting, Bjt,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders Meet Where Walt Disney Started</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM CURRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Mouse turns 60 this year, and
Donald, Goofy and the rest of the Disney gang aren't far behind.
   The faces of the popular cartoon characters created by Walt
Disney are among the best known in the world, and one questioner at
Thursday's shareholders meeting wondered if Walt Disney Co.
executives ever worry about over-saturating the market with those
familiar images.
   ``Yes, we worry about it all the time,'' said Michael D. Eisner,
chairman and chief executive officer of the broad-based
entertainment company that evolved from Disney's cartoons. ``I
think what we've found is that as long as what you do is excellent,
as long as every single move you make in every part of the company
is based on a goal of complete excellence and quality, you only
enhance the image.
   ``If you do things just to do them and they're cheap or
inferior, you are going to hurt something else.''
   About 300 people attended the Disney shareholders meeting, the
first held away from the company's theme parks, Walt Disney World
in Florida and Disneyland in California. The company decided to
``come home'' to the place where Walt Disney started out.
   Born in Chicago, Disney grew up in Marceline, Mo., about 80
miles northeast of Kansas City. His family later moved to Kansas
City, where he attended art school and did his first commercial
cartooning. He headed for Hollywood 65 years ago with $40 in his
pocket.
   The shareholders heard glowing accounts of the company's
results, bolstered by a remarkable turnaround at movie box offices,
and prospects for future growth, headlined by plans for a European
Disneyland.
   During the 1987 fiscal year ending Sept. 30, revenues increased
33 percent to $2.8 billion and net income was up 80 percent to
$444.7 milllion, or $3.23 a share.
   And the quarter ending Jan. 31 was the best first quarter in the
company's history, with revenues of $734.6 million and net
operating income of $100.4 million.
   Eisner and Frank G. Wells, president and chief operating
officer, highlighted plans for upcoming film ventures. But their
most enthusiastic comments were about the prospects for Euro
Disneyland, scheduled to open in 1992 near Paris. They said they
have no doubt they will be as successful in Europe as they have
been with their Japanese Disneyland near Tokyo, five years old in
April, which will soon welcome its 50 millionth visitor.
   The European Disneyland site, about 18 miles east of Paris, is
near one of the major north-south highway routes, Wells said, and
the French government will extend rail transportation to the gate
of the newest Magic Kingdom.
   ``Everything seems to be set to make it one of the most
successful theme park ventures ever, even rivaling Walt Disney
World,'' said Eisner. ``We believe that Euro Disneyland will be the
single most important undertaking by the company in the decade of
the 1990s.''
   Shareholders applauded promotional film clips from ``Three Men
and A Baby,'' the comedy starring Tom Selleck which has brought in
$132 million at the box office since its release last year, and the
more recent Robin Williams hit, ``Good Morning Vietnam,'' which has
fetched $63 million.
   The animated classic ``Snow White'' brought in a record $46
million in its re-release last year, bringing its total over 50
years to more than $350 million. The company is starting to put
more emphasis on the animated films which first made its
reputation, including a modern version of the Dickens classic
``Oliver Twist,'' set in New York City instead of London.
   Eisner said the company will soon meet its goal of releasing one
animated film a year, ``a dream even Walt would have felt
ambitious.''
   The Disney executives cited strong expectations for the
just-released ``Shoot To Kill,'' bringing Sidney Poitier back to
the screen after a 10-year absence, which brought in $5.8 million
and ranked No. 2 in its first weekend.
   Among films coming out later this year will be ``Who Framed
Roger Rabbit,'' an animated feature in which Steven Spielberg is
co-producer, ``D.O.A.'' a thriller starring Dennis Quaid, ``Great
Big Business,'' a comedy with Bette Midler and Lily Tomlin,
``Cocktail'' with Tom Cruise, ``Fugitive'' with Nick Nolte and
Martin Short, and ``The Good Mother'' with Diane Keaton.
   Eisner was re-elected to the board of directors, along with
Stanley P. Gold, president of Shamrock Holdings Inc., Irwin
Russell, an attorney, and Raymond L. Watson, former chairman of the
company and now chairman of the board's executive committee.
   Shareholders also approved a stock incentive plan for employees
and retained Price Waterhouse as the company's accounting firm for
the 50th year.
</TEXT>
