<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated-Rich's Bjt   02-19 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated-Rich's, Bjt,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rich's Chain Key Part Of Federated's Operations</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rich's downtown department store once was more
than the flagship of a chain, it was a symbol of Atlanta, where
Southeastern shoppers came to browse and buy _ and return _
anything they wanted from the legendary family-operated institution.
   Today's version of the store retains the offices and selling
space, but the glitz has moved to the malls and the 121-year-old
chain is independent no more, purchased 12 years ago by Federated
Department Stores Inc. of Cincinnati. Federated is itself the
object of an ongoing $5.5 billion-plus takeover attempt by Campeau
Corp. of Toronto.
   Rich's was founded in 1867 by Morris Rich, a Hungarian immigrant
who borrowed $500 from his brother to start a small dry goods store
and had $5,000 in first-year sales.
   His grandson _ born Richard Rosenheim, but who changed his name
at age 19 to Richard Rich _ took over in the late 1940s and guided
the store until his death in 1975.
   The next year, the chain was sold to Federated in a stock swap,
prompting moans from Atlanta residents and resulting in full-page
newpaper ads from the company promising that Rich's would never
change.
   That promise has been broken, says Michael Rich, great-grandson
of the founder and the last family member to work for the chain.
   ``I think Rich's was a community leader in every aspect and now
it's a place to buy things,'' Rich said in a telephone interview
from his home in Vail, Colorado. Rich was vice president for public
relations, personnel and non-sales services when he left in 1983.
   In the years since the deal with Federated, Rich's has expanded
its mall operations, and recently completed a renovation of the
downtown store.
   However, in that renovation, four floors in one part of the
two-building complex were given over to leased office space,
significantly reducing selling space.
   And what was once unthinkable has happened: arch-rival Macy's of
New York is challenging Rich's hold on the Atlanta market.
   When Federated acquired Rich's in 1976, the chain had 12
department stores and 10 Richway discount stores, all but four in
the Atlanta area.
   Now, there are 20 Rich's stores, 14 in the Atlanta area, three
in Alabama, two in South Carolina and one in Augusta, Ga. The
Richway stores have been combined with Federated's Gold Circle
discount stores into a separate division.
   The Rich's division had $690.6 million in sales in 1986, more
than 6.5 percent of total Federated sales. Federated reported net
income of $287.6 million on sales of $10.5 billion for the 12
months ended Jan. 31, 1987.
   ``They're one of Federated's better operations,'' said Monroe
Greenstein, a retail analyst for Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc. in New
York. He estimated 1987 sales at more than $700 million.
   Although Rich's has a low ratio of sales per square foot at
$140, he said, its traditional dominance of the Atlanta market
makes it an attractive property.
   Federated has ``done a lot to improve and a lot to take away
from what it was,'' Michael Rich said. ``They've changed the
concept of merchandising. They do what they do well. ... They run
mediocre department stores everywhere they are.
   ``They appeal to the middle economic strata and we tried to be
something to everyone,'' he said.
   Rich said he never understood why Federated bought Rich's and
then, to his way of thinking, changed its character. If it was
worth buying, he reasoned, it must have been because it was
successful.
   Federated is resisting the Campeau offer, and the Ohio
legislature has passed a law giving the state authority to assess
the economic impact of the potential takeover.
   Legislators are worried that Campeau would break up the company
and cost Ohioans their jobs.
   But in fighting the takeover, Federated has said it might be
forced to sell one or more assets, including the discount
operation. The company's latest move involved a financial
restructuring that could include the sale of most assets other than
the department stores.
   Rich, although he admitted he ``probably'' would like to return
to the department store business, said he had had no serious
discussions about reacquiring the family's stores.
   In addition to Rich's, Federated's holdings include the New
York-based Bloomingdale's and Abraham and Straus, Filene's of
Boston, Burdines of Miami, Bullock's and Bullocks Wilshire in Los
Angeles, I. Magnin in San Francisco and Lazarus in Ohio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
