<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Britain-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru f0028 02-19 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Workers End Strike; Trouble At Land Rover, Vauxhall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT first name of employment secretary, to Norman,
sted Normal as sent, SUB 5th graf: The cost ... Thursday night. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers voted by a more than a 2-1 margin to
accept a new contract and end a strike at Ford's 22 British plants,
but new strife in the auto industry loomed when wage negotiations
broke down at Land Rover today.
   Ford Motor Co.'s hourly workers, on strike since Feb. 8, decided
by 16,060 votes to 6,759 in a union ballot Thursday to accept a new
two-year contract. Ford said it expects them back at work on Monday.
   The vote in the 70 percent turnout ended Britain's first major
industrial strike in three years, but the settlement is a
significant union victory, the first in seven years.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government is worried that,
because Ford made concessions, there could be new industrial unrest
and an inflationary explosion in wage demands.
   ``The cost of excessive pay settlements can only be damaging to
future prospects and jobs,'' Employment Secretary Norman Fowler
warned Thursday night.
   He said excessive pay settlements translated into an average
increase in earnings among all British workers of 8.5 percent over
the last 12 months.
   Britain's annual rate of inflation of 3.3 percent, the lowest
since October 1986, is largely the result of the Conservative
government's tight money policies.
   The government has argued that, as a result of low inflation,
many British workers have no right to expect annual pay hikes.
   In its settlement, Ford backed down on a demand for a three-year
contract and also agreed to a larger wage increase _ at least 14
percent over the life of the contract. Previously, it had offered
an increase of 7 percent in the first year and 2.5 percent above
the rate of inflation over the next two years.
   An average Ford worker now earns $327 a week.
   Ford won some changes in work practices to boost productivity,
but they must be agreed to at plant level, not imposed by
management.
   More than 9,700 workers were laid off because of the strike,
which disrupted production at Ford's Belgian plant at Genk and
threatened output at Ford factories in Spain and West Germany, all
of which rely on parts made in Britain.
   Ford said the strike cost it $350 million, at showroom prices,
in lost production.
   The walkout _ Ford's first in Britain for nearly a decade _ a
recent strike by English Channel ferry crews, and unrest in the
state-run National Health Service and in coal mines has prompted
concern about a new wave of industrial problems.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said a strike
by 6,000 hourly workers at Land Rover seems certain next week
following the breakdown of pay negotiations early today.
   Land Rover managing director Tony Gilroy said no further talks
were planned.
   Land Rover said it had offered a two-year pay package which it
said was worth an extra 14 percent and would give the average
production worker $22 a week more than the Ford workers settled
for. Union officials said it was not worth that much and that they
want more.
   Meanwhile, more than 4,000 hourly workers at Vauxhall Motors,
British subsidiary of General Motors Corp., have voted to strike if
they don't get a better pension deal from the company. No date for
the walkout has been announced.
   Widespread industrial strife erupted in Britain in the so-called
winter of discontent of 1978-79 but receded after Mrs. Thatcher
rose to power in 1979, a steep rise in unemployment and laws by her
government to curb unions.
   Unemployment is now falling again and stands at 2.56 million, or
9.2 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880219-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0829EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Allegis-Covia     02-19 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Allegis-Covia,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegis Negotiating With Four Overseas Airlines For Covia-Apollo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegis Corp., parent company of United Airlines,
says it is negotiating to sell up to 35 percent of its Covia-Apollo
automated reservations system to four European airlines for about
$350 million.
   Allegis spokesman Matt Gonring said Thursday that talks were
underway but no final agreement has been reached with British
Airways, KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, Swiss Air and Alitalia.
   Gonring said Allegis also is negotiating with a third party,
whom he identified only as ``one or more of the four'' European
airlines, for acquisition of an additional 15 percent of Covia.
   Analysts said the 15 percent stake would be worth about $150
million.
   Chicago-area based Allegis would retain a controlling interest
of 50 percent of Covia, under the deal, Gonring said.
   Covia operates the Apollo computer reservation system for
airlines and other companies.
   Allegis recently sold its Westin and Hilton International hotel
chains and Hertz Corp. car rental subsidiary.
   Rather than pay dividends to shareholders from the sales,
Allegis on Wednesday began a $2.8 billion cash offer to buy about
two-thirds, or up to 33.5 million, of its shares at $80 each.
   Allegis plans to keep its airline operation and revert back to
its old corporate name, United Airlines.
</TEXT>
