<DOCNO> AP880219-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0833EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChryslerPlant     02-19 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Plant,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler May Postpone Kenosha, Wisc., Plant Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca says he's
considering a ``modest, short'' postponement of the Sept. 30
shutdown of the company's auto assembly plant in Kenosha, Wis.
   Iacocca told reporters after a two-hour meeting Thursday with
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson and Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.: ``We
don't hold hopes too high, but they specifically asked if we could
have a modest, short extension ... at the plant.
   ``We're going to look and see if we can seriously do that. It
would help, a lot.''
   Meanwhile, Iacocca said the company, working with Aspin, who is
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, would explore the
possibility of bringing some of Chrysler's growing defense business
to the Kenosha plant.
   Participants in the meeting described it as productive, but
testy and loud at times. They said they would meet again in about a
month.
   ``It started out testy. In the middle of the conversation it got
testy and about a half-an-hour before we finished it was very
testy,'' said Thompson, who is threatening to sue the company for
breach of contract. He declined, however, to say what issues
sparked the outbursts.
   Wisconsin officials are angry because they appropriated $5
million to retrain workers at the aging plant after Chrysler
acquired it in a merger with American Motors Corp. They say company
officials promised to keep it operating into 1992.
   Iacocca, however, says company officials are guilty of nothing
more than being ``cockeyed optimists'' in originally planning to
keep the plant open for three to five years. Car sales have not
been sufficient to allow that, he said.
   Thompson said he was holding back on filing a breach-of-contract
suit being prepared by Wisconsin's attorney general, but he warned:
``The filing of the lawsuit depends upon what happens in the
negotiations.''
   About 5,500 workers could lose their jobs at the 86-year-old
factory, which is the nation's oldest auto plant. About 1,800
workers are eligible for pensions, leaving 3,700 facing
unemployment in Kenosha, an industrial city of about 75,000 on Lake
Michigan.
   Iacocca said Chrysler may be able to keep the plant operating
``a couple months'' beyond the scheduled closing on Sept. 30. But
Thompson said he hoped the extension would be longer than that.
   Aspin said the group is looking into transferring some of the
company's existing defense business to Kenosha and at securing new
business for it. He declined to offer specific details.
   Chrysler had $268 million in Pentagon business last year _
including electronics, small aircraft and some automotive sales _
and is looking to expand, according to Warren Nelson, an Aspin aide.
   ``Chrysler ought to give some thought to the fact that if they
have an interest in expanding their defense business, closing a
plant in Wisconsin isn't the way to go about it,'' Nelson said.
   He cautioned, however, ``There is no way Chrysler is going to
come up with 3,700 jobs no matter how much defense work they get.''
   Thompson said he and Aspin also asked Iacocca to negotiate with
the United Auto Workers union concerning the disposition of money
that workers had paid into a fund for improving the plant, and to
participate in a program to improve economic development in
southeast Wisconsin.
   On Tuesday, Iacocca announced in Milwaukee that the company
would dedicate all profits from new Chrysler cars sold in Wisconsin
to a fund to help laid-off workers pay their mortgages and rent.
Based on 1987 sales, the fund should amount to about $20 million,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
