<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     02-19 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0292</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today,
continuing its recent stalemate around the 2,000 level in the Dow
Jones industrial average.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips edged up .49 to 1,986.90 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 465 up, 507 down and 506
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.50 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Several analysts at major investment firms have lately grown a
bit more optimistic about the outlook for the market, citing signs
of strength in the manufacturing sector of the economy.
   Buying interest has been evident in some manufacturing stocks
and many of the smaller ``secondary'' issues.
   But investors have remained leery of doing much broad-scale
buying, with memories still fresh of the crash in October and talk
persisting of a recession this year or in 1989.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose \ to 112}; Ford Motor gained { to 42}; Chrysler
dropped [ to 24}, and Exxon was unchanged at 42.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.08 to 145.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .23 at 277.69.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 14.58 to
1,986.41, after closing slightly above 2,000 in the week's first
two sessions.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 6 on the
NYSE, with 678 up, 812 down and 470 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 151.43 million shares, against 176.83 million in the
previous session.
