<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coniston To Seek Four Seats On Gillette Board of Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners indicated today it would try
to place four representatives on the Gillette Co. board of
directors, escalating its strategy of pressuring the company into a
merger or restructuring.
   A group led by the investment partnership, which holds a 6
percent stake in Gillette, said it intended to solicit proxies from
Gillette shareholders to place candidates on the board of directors.
   In disclosing its Gillette stake last Thursday, Coniston
indicated it might seek representation on the board as part of a
strategy to force an increase in Gillette's share value.
   Coniston would be unable to take control of Gillette's board,
because only a third of the seats are up for election in any year.
But analysts say a Coniston victory in the proxy fight could
pressure the board to accede to the group's demands that it meet
with potential merger partners.
   Gillette stock rose 37{ cents to $39 a share in early trading
today on the New York Stock Exchange.
   A spokesman at the Boston-based consumer products company said
Gillette had not yet seen the Securities and Exchange Commission
filing outlining Coniston's plan, and would not comment until it
had.
   Coniston also has said it was attempting to meet with potential
acquirers of Gillette, which long has been a takeover target.
Gillette has resisted takeover overtures, and reiterated a desire
to remain independent last week after Coniston made its disclosures.
   The moves by Coniston, which successfully waged a similar
strategy against Allegis Corp. last year, were seen widely as an
attempt to force Gillette's board to meet with potential merger
partners such as Revlon Group Inc., which has had several buyout
offers rebuffed by Gillette over the past 18 months.
   Keith Gollust, a principal in the partnership, said Gillette's
takeover defenses essentially gave its board of directors
unilateral power to accept or reject any merger offers.
   ``Our position is that shareholders, who really own the company,
ought to have the right to make that decision,'' he said.
   Gollust said the group had a telephone conversation with
Gillette chairman Colman M. Mockler Jr. last week, but Mockler did
not change the company's prior statements that it wished to remain
independent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
