<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0232</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today,
continuing its recent stalemate around the 2,000 level in the Dow
Jones industrial average.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips slipped 1.33 to 1,985.08 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers held a narrow edge on gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 568 up, 590 down and 538
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 57.81 million shares at
midmorning.
   Several analysts at major investment firms have lately grown a
bit more optimistic about the outlook for the market, citing signs
of strength in the manufacturing sector of the economy.
   Buying interest has been evident in some manufacturing stocks
and many of the smaller ``secondary'' issues.
   But investors have remained leery of doing much broad-scale
buying, with memories still fresh of the crash in October and talk
persisting of a recession this year or in 1989.
   Texaco climbed 1~ to 42|. Financier T. Boone Pickens sought
regulatory approval to buy a stake in the company, in which another
prominent investor, Carl Icahn, already holds a 14.8 percent
interest.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.01 to 145.15. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .26 at 278.18.
</TEXT>
