<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Most of the markets were down only slightly, but wheat was off
as much as 5\ cents a bushel within a few minutes of the opening
bell.
   Demand for wheat typically weakens in late winter and early
spring, and the futures market is anticipating a corresponding drop
in prices, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York for Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``People are expecting the seasonal downturn in wheat,'' Spilka
said. ``They're looking for it and looking for it and when they see
signs of weakening, you get a kind of bandwagon effect.''
   Wheat futures prices have mostly advanced for the past eight
months. A down day today would mark the fourth straight day of
steady or lower wheat prices.
   In early trading, wheat was 3} cents to 5\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.16{ a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 1\ cents lower with March at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were
1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $6.27{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent lower to .30 cent higher with February
at 71.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .20
cent higher with March at 82.35 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent
lower to .18 cent higher with February at 46.00 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
