<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv22   02-19 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 22,0628</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Feb 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Wall Street, ``Rust Belt'' Takes On New Shine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock market investors face a quandary these
days when they look for ways to profit from the revival of American
manufacturing.
   Practically no one disputes that ``smokestack America'' _ makers
of steel, paper, chemicals, machinery and so forth _ has made an
impressive comeback from its woes of the early to mid-1980s.
   The dollar's decline in currency markets has improved the
competitive position of American manufacturers in world markets and
given a needed boost to U.S. exports.
   Furthermore, in the lean years many companies in this sector of
the economy cut costs, increased productivity and ``restructured''
themselves to concentrate on operations with the most promising
potential.
   While business was bad, there was little incentive to expand
capacity. So now that business is better, manufacturers often find
the facilities they have running at full tilt with order backlogs
growing.
   This, in turn, creates a climate in which a company can enjoy
what Wall Street analysts call ``pricing flexibility'' _ the
opportunity to increase prices and profits.
   All this adds up to what any experienced investor would regard
as a classic opportunity.
   While falling inflation and lower interest rates provided the
dominant themes of the 1982-87 bull market, many analysts say the
story today and for the future is manufacturing.
   There's one problem with that view, however. Manufacturing is by
long-standing tradition closely tied to the ups and downs of the
business cycle. And if there is going to be a recession, as so many
people are predicting right now, manufacturing would appear to be
standing directly in its path.
   In January, notes Rao Chalasani, an analyst at Prescott, Ball &
Turben Inc., a Cleveland-based investment firm, an index he
maintains of 31 manufacturing stocks fell 5.8 percent while the Dow
Jones industrial average gained about 1 percent.
   That action came amid other signs that recession fears were
increasing in the securities markets _ among them a drop in
interest rates and in the price of gold.
   Nevertheless, putting aside the question of where the economical
cycle stands, many analysts argue that there is a strong
``secular,'' or long-term, case for being bullish on American
manufacturing.
   ``Investment strategy decisions frequently key off of the
business cycle,'' said Robert Salomon at Salomon Brothers in a
commentary on the subject. ``Occasionally, however, a secular trend
takes hold.
   ``We believe that the revival of the U.S. manufacturing sector
represents the beginning of a secular trend of a proportion similar
to the disinflation trend experienced earlier in this decade.''
   Maintains Chalasani on a similar note: ``The fundamental secular
trend will remain for many years. Numerous factors can temporarily
check it, but it can be derailed only by cascading financial
accidents.''
   Salomon says that a recession is likely next year, but that the
forces in the economy emphasizing production and deemphasizing
consumption could shape it into something considerably different
from the typical down phase of the business cycle.
   ``If export growth partly offsets weakness in the domestic
economy, as we believe is likely, areas of the economy that are
typically weak during an economic contraction _ notably the
cyclical sectors _ may show surprising strength,'' he reasons.
   At the same time, he says, ``some consumption-oriented
industries _ traditionally perceived as defensive investments _ may
not be the safe havens that they have been in other times.
   ``On balance, the positive secular trend evident in the
manufacturing sector will, to some extent, offset (or at least
dampen) the near-term cyclical weakness.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Feb 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
