<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0324</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, continuing
its recent stalemate around the 2,000 level in the Dow Jones
industrial average.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips rose .82 to 1,987.23 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers held a narrow edge on losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 671 up, 598 down and 525
unchanged.
   Several analysts at major investment firms have lately grown a
bit more optimistic about the outlook for the market, citing signs
of strength in the manufacturing sector of the economy.
   Buying interest has been evident in some manufacturing stocks
and many of the smaller ``secondary'' issues.
   But investors have remained leery of doing much broad-scale
buying, with memories still fresh of the crash in October and talk
persisting of a recession this year or in 1989.
   In a market that has been closely tuned to news developments,
there were no major government reports or other economic data to
give prices a push in either direction today.
   Texaco climbed 2| to 43]. Financier T. Boone Pickens sought
regulatory approval to buy a stake in the company, in which another
prominent investor, Carl Icahn, already holds a 14.8 percent
interest.
   Among other actively traded blue chips, Ford Motor rose 1 to
43\, while General Electric dropped | to 42| and American Telephone
& Telegraph lost [ to 29[.
   Brockway jumped 11{ to 58. Owens-Illinois said a federal court
denied the Federal Trade Commission's request to block its
$60-a-share bid to acquire Brockway.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.25 to 145.39. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .41 at 278.33.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 80.38 million shares at
noontime, against 70.42 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
