<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-Ford 1stLd-Writethru   02-19 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Ford, 1st Ld-Writethru,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Earns Record 1987 Profits; Workers to Share</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf to UPDATE with amount of profit-sharing
checks.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has out-earned industry leader
General Motors Corp. for the second straight year, a boon to Ford
workers who will receive record profit-sharing checks early next
month.
   The No. 2 automaker's fourth-quarter earnings rose 19 percent
from a year earlier and full-year earnings jumped 41 percent over
1986, but some Wall Street analysts said they had expected Ford to
earn even more.
   For the final three months of 1987, Ford said it earned $932
million, or $1.87 a share, on revenue of $18.8 billion, up from
$785 million, or $1.50 a share, on revenue of $16.26 billion in the
final quarter of 1986.
   For the year, Ford earned $4.6 billion, or $9.05 a share, on
revenue of $71.6 billion, up from 1986 earnings of $3.29 billion,
or $6.16 a share, on revenue of $62.7 billion.
   Earnings for the fourth quarter and the year were both records,
Ford said.
   Per-share earnings in 1986 were readjusted to reflect a
two-for-one stock split on Dec. 10, 1987.
   Market expectations that Ford's earnings would be somewhat
higher for the year and for the quarter depressed the price of Ford
stock after the announcement, said Douglas Laughlin, industry
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   After the announcement, Ford stock fell, finishing down $2.25 a
share at $42.25 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``The stock's mostly down on a gut reaction to the number but
not on any real conclusive detail. It was a very respectable
quarter and the year has been excellent,'' Laughlin said.
   Thomas O'Grady, analyst with Integrated Automotive Resources
Inc. in Wayne, Pa., said the weaker-than-expected fourth quarter
may have been caused by incentive programs, which were unnecessary
a year earlier when buyers were flooding showrooms to beat 1988 tax
reforms.
   By the end of 1987, Ford's nest egg of cash and marketable
securities had grown to nearly $10.1 billion from $8.6 billion a
year earlier.
   Ford said today its workers will receive an average of more than
$3,700 each in profit-sharing checks. The checks, to be distributed
March 8, are up substantially from the average $2,100 payout that
workers received for 1986.
   GM workers received no share of 1986 or 1987 profits because the
company's U.S. auto earnings were too low.
   Ford's profit-sharing also is based on U.S. earnings, which
jumped nearly 40 percent to $3.44 billion in 1987 from $2.46
billion in 1986 due to higher car and truck sales and increased
production efficiency, Ford said.
   Ford was the only Big Three automaker to sell more cars and
trucks in 1987 than in 1986. Ford's F-series pickup truck was the
best-selling vehicle for the sixth consecutive year and its Escort
subcompact was the best-selling car, followed by the Ford Taurus.
   For 1987, earnings for industry leader GM rose to $3.6 billion,
or $10.06 a share. For Chrysler Corp., the No. 3 automaker, 1987
earnings fell slightly to $1.3 billion, or $5.90 a share.
   Ford attributed its record performance to improved sales
worldwide, strong earnings by subsidiaries and a comfortable
relationship with the United Auto Workers union.
   ``The joint effort by employees, suppliers and dealers in
bringing the consumer high-quality, value-for-the-money products
was the key to 1987 results,'' Ford Chairman Donald Petersen and
Vice Chairman Harold Poling said in a statement.
   Early in the fourth quarter, Ford signed a three-year,
job-protecting labor pact with the UAW that was negotiated without
a strike and helps the company improve production efficiency and
cut costs.
   Among Ford Financial Services Group subsidiaries, Ford Motor
Credit Co. earned a record $678.8 million for the year, up 11
percent, while First Nationwide Financial Corp.'s earnings fell 38
percent to $63 million.
   Together, the financial subsidiaries, including U.S. Leasing
International Inc. which Ford acquired in the fourth quarter,
contributed more than 18 percent of Ford's 1987 net earnings.
</TEXT>
