<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PacificExchange     02-19 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pacific Exchange,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pacific Exchange to Take Part in Feasibility Study of Honolulu
Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California-based Pacific Stock Exchange says
it will join a six-month feasibility study on opening an exchange
here.
   The Pacific Exchange has trading floors in San Francisco and Los
Angeles, and a Honolulu facility would allow greater involvement in
Pacific Basin financial markets, an exchange spokesman said
Thursday.
   The most likely expansion would mean adding a third trading
floor here, although a new exchange operation controlled by the
Pacific Exchange is also a possibility, said the spokesman, Don
Alexander.
   What makes Hawaii an attractive site is its mid-Pacific time
zone, he said. A Hawaii exchange could trade during the gap between
the close of exchanges in the mainland United States and the
beginning of trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The exchange could operate from 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. Hawaii
time, which is 5:30 p.m. to 9 p.m. EST, Alexander said.
</TEXT>
