<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 1554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ford-Pollution     02-19 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford-Pollution,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Could Pay $1.75 Million in Penalties in Air Pollution Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. would pay $1.75 million in
penalties and close two vinyl-coating production lines to settle an
air pollution case at a plant in Mount Clemens, Mich., the Justice
Department announced Friday.
   The government filed a proposed consent decree requiring Ford to
pay the penalties for discharging excessive amounts of volatile
organic compounds in violation of the Clean Air Act.
   The decree, filed in U.S. District Court in Detroit, would
settle a civil complaint filed in 1984 and would be the largest
penalty ever assessed against a company in a case brought by the
government involving volatile organic compounds.
   The complaint said the violations occurred at eight coating
lines where production printers applied coatings to vinyl products
used in construction of seats, door panels and vinyl roofs.
   Six of the lines were operated without any pollution control
equipment and the coatings contained solvents made of the volatile
compounds, which were released into the air and contributed to the
pollutant ozone, the government said. In significant
concentrations, ozone can reduce lung function and increase the
incidence of respiratory and heart diseases.
   The proposed decree will become final on entry by the court
following a 30-day public comment period.
   Ford closed six of the lines in 1984 and 1985, and the decree
requires the company to close the other two no later than 90 days
after the decree becomes final.
</TEXT>
