<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv20-21   02-19 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 20-21,0606</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Feb 20-21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Report Finds U.S. Treasuries Did Poorly Against Most Foreign
Securities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For those well-heeled investors who dabble in
foreign debt securities, the grass was a lot greener on the other
side during 1987.
   Weighed down by the sinking dollar, the U.S. Treasury bond
market performed dismally in comparison with other world markets,
although it appeared to be off to a better start this year.
   Salomon Brothers' World Government Bond Index showed that
Treasuries had a total rate of return of only 1.93 percent,
compared with an average return of 35.15 percent in dollar value
for eight other major world markets. Total return includes price
change, interest income and currency fluctuations.
   ``That's such a big difference. It's the widest margin in our
history'' of indexing global bond markets, said Carol A. Russo, a
Salomon Brothers research analyst.
   The domestic government bond market performed about half as well
as the others in 1986 _ 15.73 percent vs. 31.35 percent. In 1985,
the U.S. bond market provided a rate of return of 20.94 percent vs.
35.01 percent for the foreign markets, according to Salomon.
   Even the second-worst performer in 1987, the Canadian bond
market, had a rate of return eight times better than that of
domestic government bonds _ 10.01 percent in dollar value and 3.62
percent in local currency, Miss Russo said.
   The top performer was the British gilt market, which had a total
rate of return of 46.58 percent in dollar value and 15.51 percent
in local currency. The results reflected a coordinated effort to
drive down interest rates, as well as the dollar's decline against
the British pound, Miss Russo said.
   Other annual rankings, according to Salomon, included: Japan,
38.11 percent in dollar value, 5.96 percent in local currency;
Switzerland, 32.59 percent, 4.56 percent; the Netherlands, 32.11
percent, 7.55 percent; Germany, 29.38 percent, 5.80 percent;
Australia, 29 percent, 18.84 percent; and France, 26.6 percent,
5.84 percent.
   All this translated into some healthy returns for investors who
either purchased these foreign securities individually or got into
an international bond mutual fund.
   International funds had an average rate of return of 25.07
percent in 1987, second only to gold funds, whose rate of return
averaged 35.43 percent, according to Mutual Fund Values, a
Chicago-based publication that tracks nearly 800 mutual funds.
   During the same time, Treasury bond mutual funds had an average
return of negative 0.12 percent, the publication said.
Government-backed mortgage-related funds had a 0.57 percent return,
and general government bond funds, which include both types of
securities, had a return of 1.55 percent, it said.
   Economists blame the sharp drop in U.S. government bond prices _
and the accompanyingrise in interest rates prevalent through most
of last year _ on fears of higher inflation stemming from rising
oil prices and the dollar's weakness in foreign exchange.
   The market took a turn for the better after the Oct. 19 stock
market crash, when the Federal Reserve decided to ease its credit
policies to prevent a possible recession.
   The market's performance in Salomon's January index also showed
significant improvement.
   Treasuries ranked second in total investment returns, gaining
nearly 3.5 percent in value last month. First was the Canadian
market, which rose 6.7 percent in dollar value.
   Australia came in third, followed by France, Japan, Britain, the
Netherlands, West Germany and Switzerland, Salomon said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Feb 20-21</NOTE>
