<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BanksHurt Bjt   02-19 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banks Hurt, Bjt,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Crash Shifted Balance of Power in Banking Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The balance of power in the banking industry has
shifted dramatically since the October stock market crash, leaving
many of the nation's largest institutions vulnerable to takeovers,
a study released Friday said.
   The report by MAC Group, a Cambridge-based financial research
firm, rated 19 of the 50 largest U.S. banking institutions as
susceptible to takeover as of the end of last year, compared with
just four by Sept. 30.
   ``In effect there's a new group of very strong institutions
beyond the traditionally large institutions,'' said William T.
Gregor, a MAC Group senior vice president.
   The study measured the ratio of a bank's stock market value to
its book value _ its worth based on audited financial statements.
   Gregor said the ``market-to-book ratio'' is a ood predictor of a
bank's long-term performance capabilities. He said the lower an
institution's ratio, the more difficulty it has issuing new stock
to raise capital.
   ``When you're selling below the book value, you're selling for
below what the auditors are saying you're worth,'' Gregor said.
   Bank stocks were hard-hit by the Oct. 19 market crash. The
survey found that from October 31 to December 31, the stock price
of the surveyed banks fell 29 percents.
   The report concluded that:
   _A bank's ability to grow and acquire other companies has become
a critical feature of financial strength.
   _Banks most severly discounted by the crash are under
``unprecedented pressure'' to strengthen performance to stay
independent.
   _Competitive advantage among banks now is more a function of
market value and stock market performance than asset size.
   The 19 banks labeled as vulnerable to takeover all had
market-to-book ratios under 1.0 as of December 30. They included:
BankAmerica Corp., of San Francisco; Bank of Boston Corp., Boston;
Bank of New York Co., New York; Chase Manhattan Corp., New York;
First Chicago Corp., Chicago; Manufacturers Hanover Corp., New
York; Mellon Bank Corp., Pittsburgh; and Security Pacific Corp.,
Los Angeles.
   ``In effect their earning power wasn't severly disadvantaged but
their ability to issue equity and to make acquisitions certainly
was damaged,'' Gregor said.
   A core group of 17 banks that emerged from the crash in better
shape or with limited damage all had ratio's above 1.0, according
to the study. Most weren't large banks in terms of assets.
   They include ``new powerhouses,'' Gregor said, such as
Fleet@Norstar Financial, of Providence, R.I.; Sovran Financial,
Norfolk, Va.; NBD Bancorp Inc., of Detroit; Banc One Corp.,
Columbus, Ohio; and Corestates Financial of Philadelphia.
   ``Cleary we're not going to see tomorrow that Fleet has made an
offer for Manufacturers Hanover, but nevertheless its clinically
possible,'' Gregor said. ``I think what we will see is more
frequent acquisitions than in the past. In some cases those may be
for entire institutions or pieces of institutions.''
   New guidelines being considered by the Federal Reserve Board
also could compound problems for hard-hit banks, Gregor said. The
change would require banks to maintain 8 percent of total balance
sheets in capital, 4 percent of which would be in equity.
   ``A number of institutions are going to find it painful and
difficult to do that,'' Gregor said. ``There's going to be even
greater pressure on capital and therefore on earnings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
