<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher in late trading
today, continuing its recent flirtation with the 2,000 level in the
Dow Jones industrial average.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips rose 8.78 to 1,995.19 by 3
p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 4 to 3 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 815 up, 599
down and 504 unchanged.
   Several analysts at major investment firms have lately grown a
bit more optimistic about the outlook for the market, citing signs
of strength in the manufacturing sector of the economy.
   Buying interest has been evident in some manufacturing stocks
and many of the smaller ``secondary'' issues.
   But investors have remained leery of doing much broad-scale
buying, with memories still fresh of the crash in October and talk
persisting of a recession this year or in 1989.
   In a market that has been closely tuned to news developments,
there were no major government reports or other economic data to
give prices a push in either direction today.
   Texaco climbed 2[ to 42~. Financier T. Boone Pickens sought
regulatory approval to buy a stake in the company, in which another
prominent investor, Carl Icahn, already holds a 14.8 percent
interest.
   Brockway jumped 11[ to 57|. Owens-Illinois said a federal court
denied the Federal Trade Commission's request to block its
$60-a-share bid to acquire Brockway.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.66 to 145.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .78 at 278.70.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 137.27 million shares with an
hour to go.
