<HEAD>Paley Critical With Lung and Kidney Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Paley, the 86-year-old founder and
chairman of CBS, suffered lung and kidney failure after undergoing
emergency surgery last week and remained in critical condition
Friday at a Manhattan hospital.
   ``He's in critical but stable condition with pulmonary and
kidney failure in the ICU (intensive care unit) following emergency
surgery,'' said Elizabeth Erlanger, a spokeswoman for New York
Hospital-Cornell Medical Center. ``He is currently receiving kidney
dialysis.''
   Contrary to a report last Sunday by a hospital administrator
that Paley was in satisfactory condition, Ms. Erlanger said that he
had been in critical condition since undergoing gall bladder
surgery on Feb. 11.
   Paley built the Columbia Broadcasting System from a fledgling
radio network that he bought in 1928. He controlled it for more
than half a century before turning over the reins in 1983.
   When CBS's biggest stockholder, Loew's Corp., became unhappy
with his successor's policies, Paley teamed with Loew's chairman
Lawrence Tisch to retake control in 1986.
</TEXT>
