<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Minstar-Genmar     02-19 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minstar-Genmar,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minstar Revives Plans to Merge With Boating Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minstar Inc. has revived plans to merge with
its boating subsidiary, offering to acquire the Genmar Industries
Inc. shares it does not already own and some of the company's
outstanding debt for about $85 million.
   An earlier proposed $559 million acquisition of Minstar by
Genmar, both of which are controlled by Minneapolis financier Irwin
Jacobs, fell apart last year when the stocks of both companies
plummeted in the October market crash before shareholders were to
vote on the deal.
   Under terms of the latest transaction, Minstar would pay $11.50
each for the 4.8 million shares, or 16.5 percent, of Genmar that it
does not own. Minstar also would pay $29.4 million for Genmar
debentures with a principal amount of $35.4 million.
   Genmar traded at $10.75, up 12{ cents from Wednesday's close,
and Minstar traded at $22.75, unchanged from Wednesday, in national
over-the-counter trading Thursday.
   After the initial proposal was canceled, Jacobs had said Minstar
would sell its sporting equipment and energy services businesses,
leaving Minstar essentially a powerboat maker.
   Jacobs also had indicated that, after determining the prices
Minstar could get for those units, he would consider some other way
of combining Minstar and Genmar.
   Last month, Minstar said it had received bids for all the
sporting goods and energy businesses and estimated that they would
sell for $370 million to $400 million.
   Jacobs said Wednesday he expected to announce buyers for the
energy operations and the Ben Hogan golf equipment businesses next
week. He said negotiations for the other operations are continuing
with several possible buyers.
   With those divestitures complete, Minstar will be left with its
majority ownership of Genmar's boating operations. Jacobs said the
acquisition of Genmar would help boost Minstar's market value by
making it a ``pure play,'' a company that investors and analysts
can assess solely by its performance in the boat business.
   Jacobs heads an investment group that owns more than half of
Minstar's stock.
</TEXT>
