<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Maxwell     02-19 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Maxwell,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publisher Says His Fortune Will be Left to Charity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Robert Maxwell announced Friday that his
family fortune will be given away to worthy causes and he will
leave nothing for his children.
   The report in the Maxwell-owned Daily Mirror was the British
publisher's response to critics who have accused him of funneling
profits to Liechtenstein, a central European duchy and tax haven.
   The report, under Maxwell's byline, said the fortune held by the
family-owned Pergamon foundation in Liechtenstein ``is all to be
given away _ and nothing will go to his children.''
   ``Massive sums from the foundation, which is worth more than 1
billion bounds ($1.75 billion) and whose present income is
estimated at 25 million pounds, will go to medical research and to
help Israel's Jews and Arabs find peace,'' the report said.
   Funds would also go toward helping young entrepreneurs break
into the communications field, improving education and eliminating
conflicts and racial hostilities.
   The allegation that Maxwell's financial holdings are shrouded in
secrecy has sometimes been used against him by companies fighting
off takeover bids by the publisher.
   The Mirror said the planned fate of the fortune is revealed in a
forthcoming authorized biography of Maxwell by Joe Haines,
political editor of the Mirror newspapers group.
   It said Haines told Maxwell he wanted to include information
about ``the mystery of Liechtenstein,'' to which Maxwell is quoted
as replying: ``There is no mystery,'' and then detailing his plans
to give the money away.
   The report quoted Maxwell's son Ian as saying: ``I and all of my
sisters and brothers have always known that the wealth my father
helped to create would be returned for the benefit of science and
medicine. We are all delighted and welcome it.''
</TEXT>
