<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Black&Decker     02-19 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black & Decker,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loses Round in American Standard Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. has won a legal round in
its battle to escape a hostile $2.03 billion takeover attempt from
power-tool maker Black & Decker Corp.
   A Manhattan federal judge on Thursday rejected Black & Decker's
effort to stop American Standard from seeking court validation of
its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover plan in Delaware, where the
manufacturer is incorporated.
   Judge Robert Ward's action affirmed American Standard's position
that any litigation concerning the plan, designed to make an
unwanted takeover prohibitively expensive, should be heard in a
Delaware court.
   The legal wrangling was part of an increasingly complicated
battle between American Standard and Black & Decker, which
undertook the hostile takeover attempt in January.
   Last week, American Standard rejected a sweetened $65-a-share
offer from Black & Decker and said it was pursuing alternatives.
   On Thursday, American Standard Inc.'s board of directors
approved a multibillion-dollar recapitalization plan, which would
pay stockholders $64 a share in cash and junk bonds, along with
stock in the recapitalized company.
   That plan also would saddle the company with new debt to finance
the recapitalization, in which a company realigns its levels of
debt and equity. Such a strategy has become a common takeover
defense because the company often acquires a big debt load that
discourages potential acquirers.
</TEXT>
