<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Rise, Crude Up 25 Cents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices rose moderately late Friday, but
traders said the rally was largely based on internal market
influences and not linked to any outside news developments.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March-delivery contract
for key West Texas Intermediate crude closed at $16.70 per
42-gallon barrel, up 25 cents from the Thursday close.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline rose 0.46 cent a gallon to 46.43 cents, and
wholesale home heating oil rose 0.72 cent a gallon to 45.80 cents.
   Much of the action was attributed to short-covering, a
price-raising influence caused by traders who buy oil to replace
borrowed oil they had sold earlier. Short-covering can raise prices
sharply but it is generally a temporary trend.
</TEXT>
