<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BoeingFlight     02-19 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Flight,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Begins Test of 737-400</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest model of the best-selling Boeing 737
jetliner made its maiden flight Friday, the first step on the way
to Federal Aviation Administration certification later this year.
   About 450 hours of test flights will be done before
certification. The first three 737-400s are to be delivered to
Piedmont Airlines.
   The first 737-400 was rolled out at Boeing's Renton assembly
plant Jan. 26. Boeing made it a gala day, rolling out the first
747-400 the same day in Everett. That jetliner begins test flights
next month.
   The 737-400 is a stretch version of Boeing's workhorse jet. It
is slightly more than 119 feet long and can carry 146 to 168
passengers as far as 3,200 miles without refueling.
   With 1,925 orders as of Dec. 31, the 737 series is the world's
most popular jet.
   As with the smaller 737-300, which entered service in 1984, the
new plane features fuel-efficient engines, advanced avionics and
instruments and improvements in aerodynamics.
   Nine customers have ordered 88 of the 737-400s and hold options
for another 35.
</TEXT>
