<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-19 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned in a mixed performance against
major foreign currencies Friday, failing to hold gains made late in
the previous trading session.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York reported a
late bid of $445 for a troy ounce of gold, up from $442.80 late
Thursday.
   In the absence of significant news, the dollar finished the day
higher than it had been Thursday in Europe, but lower than the
levels attained in Thursday's late rally in New York.
   Thursday's rally was attributed to technical factors and
President Reagan's statement that he wanted to rescue a kidnap
victim in Lebanon. International tension tends to increase interest
in dollars as a safe haven.
   The dollar dropped Friday in Europe against the Swiss franc
after Swiss National Bank President Pierre Languetin said he hoped
central banks would sell dollars if the American currency rose too
sharply, dealers said.
   Otherwise, ``U.S. dollar trading was actually non-existent
today,'' said Rod Fowler, foreign-exchange manager for Wood Gundy
Inc. in Toronto.
   ``At the moment we're in a stalemate situation'' between bulls
and bears on the dollar, said David Godwin, chief currency dealer
for Union Bank of Switzerland in New York.
   The British pound fell to $1.7505 from $1.7508 in London. Later
in New York the pound finished at $1.7495, down from earlier in the
day but up from its price of $1.7418 late Thursday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 130.53 Japanese yen from
130.00 yen on Thursday. In later London trading, the dollar slipped
to 130.02 yen. By the end of the trading day in New York, the
dollar stood at 130.05 yen, down from 130.38 yen late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Thursday, included: 1.7080 West German marks, down from 1.7123;
1.3980 Swiss francs, down from 1.4098; 5.7755 French francs, down
from 5.7870; 1,256.75 Italian lire, down from 1,261.00; and 1.2737
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2706.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.7075 West German marks, up from 1.7040; 1.3985
Swiss francs, down from 1.4010; 5.7675 French francs, up from
5.7555; 1.9150 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9130; 1,257.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,254.63; and 1.2702 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2690.
   Gold bullion dropped to $441 in early trading in Europe, then
rallied somewhat when traders bought dollars either to limit losses
or trade in on the metal's earlier decline.
   In London, gold fell to a late bid price of $442.90 a troy
ounce, down from $444 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, it fell to $443 bid from $447.50 bid late Thursday.
   Hong Kong markets were closed for the Chinese New Year.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold was bid late at
$445.10 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $442.80.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid of $6.37 a troy
ounce, down from $6.43 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex,
silver for current delivery was bid at $6.385 a troy ounce, down
from $6.43 late Thursday.
