<HEAD>Wall Street Trader Charged In Alleged Plot Against Boesky</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead, adds 7 grafs additional details at end.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``extremely upset'' Wall Street trader
was charged with weapons possession and witness intimidation Friday
after authorities alleged he plotted an attack on convicted
financier Ivan F. Boesky with a loaded semi-automatic rifle.
   The arrest of John A. Mulheren marked the first public
indication of potential violence in a financial scandal surrounding
Boesky and suggested that government investigators are closer to
making new arrests.
   Mulheren, a general partner in the firm Jamie Securities Co.,
was seized near his Rumson, N.J. home Thursday in possession of an
Israeli-made semi-automatic rifle, said Monmouth County Assistant
Prosecutor Alton Kenney.
   Mulheren was ordered held in lieu of $17,500 bail after a
hearing Friday.
   A complaint filed against Mulheren in Freehold alleged the
weapon was to be used ``unlawfully against the person or property''
of Boesky, a former financier whose downfall more than a year ago
shook the financial world.
   The complaint also mentioned a possible attack against Michael
Davidoff, a former head trader for Boesky who is cooperating in a
government investigation of the financial scandal.
   Authorities declined to say why they believed Mulheren was
plotting against Boesky and Davidoff, but Mulheren once was a close
associate of Boesky and reportedly has been implicated in the
government's investigation.
   Meanwhile in Manhattan, federal prosecutors charged Mulheren in
a two-count criminal complaint with attempting to intimidate a
cooperating witness, who was identified only as Witness X, formerly
employed by Boesky. They refused to confirm or deny that Witness X
is Davidoff.
   The federal complaint quoted Mulheren's wife as telling police
he had been ``extremely upset by the Boesky situation'' and ``was
armed and was going to get'' Witness X.
   The complaint said when police seized Mulheren, they found the
loaded rifle as well as Army fatigue-type clothing in a bag in his
car.
   Boesky's whereabouts weren't immediately clear and he could not
be reached for comment. His attorney Harvey L. Pitt did not return
two telephone calls seeking comment. A secretary said he was out of
the office.
   In November 1986 Boesky paid a record $100 million to settle a
Securities and Exchange Commission complaint of insider trading,
the misuse of private information to profit in securities
transactions. He was banished from the securities business for life.
   Last April, Boesky pleaded guilty to a criminal charge of
conspiracy to lie to the SEC, for which he was sentenced to a
three-year prison term in December. He's scheduled to start serving
the sentence next month.
   Boesky has been the government's chief source of information in
a probe of other Wall Street professionals.
   Last September, the Wall Street Journal quoted unidentified
people it said were familiar with the investigation as saying
Mulheren was cooperating with the government as a result of
Boesky's disclosures.
   The newspaper also said without attribution that the
investigation could lead to civil and criminal charges against
Mulheren.
   Fred M. Stone, a lawyer for Jamie, said the company's partners
are discussing a course of action in the wake of Mulheren's arrest.
Stone declined to say how many partners were involved in Jamie.
   Stone also released a statement from Mulheren's New York
attorney Otto Obermaier.
   ``It is known that John Mulheren has been upset by the
investigation by regulatory authorities of securities activities
and by the rumors and publicity which developed which he felt
unfairly impugned his honesty and integrity,'' Obermaier said.
   ``The important thing now is for him to get help and support to
permit him to resume a normal and constructive life. He is in the
process of seeking required medical assistance,'' said Obermaier's
statement.
   The New Jersey complaint named Mulheren on charges of unlawful
possession of weapon and intent to use the weapon unlawfully, said
Kenney.
   The possession charge carries a maximum sentence of five years
in prison and $7,500 in fines, while the other charge carries a
maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and $100,000 in fines upon
conviction, the prosecutor said.
   Kenny said federal authorities in Manhattan had filed papers to
arrest Mulheren if he posted the local bail.
   Kenney said Rumson police went to Mulheren's home Thursday and
received permission from his wife to search the family car, where
police seized a 9mm pistol, a .357-caliber Magnum revolver and a
shotgun. But Mulheren was not arrested then because he was licensed
for the weapons.
   Police began watching Mulheren afterward and later Thursday
stopped him in his car after he left home.
   Kenney said police found a satchel in the car containing the
semi-automatic rifle.
   The prosecutor said Mulheren was then arrested because the rifle
was ``clearly not a sportsmen's weapon'' and, although such
firearms can be owned in New Jersey, a permit is needed to carry
them off private property.
</TEXT>
