<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 2344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-KodakBatteries     02-19 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kodak Batteries,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Says 10-Year Batteries Won't Make It to the Finish Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Friday its
innovative 9-volt lithium batteries, which were supposed to have a
shelf life of 10 years, don't last that long.
   ``Until the problem is corrected, they won't have a storage life
of 10 years,'' said Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska. ``But I don't
think the average consumer is going to run into any difficulty.''
   The company said the problem does not affect the use life of the
batteries, only the amount of time they can sit on store shelves.
   The news prompted Black & Decker Corp. to announce immediate
plans Friday to stop selling mini-flashlights that were designed to
exclusively use Kodak's 9-volt lithium batteries.
   ``We're very concerned with selling the best possible product
and we relied on Kodak's word,'' said Barbara Lucas, a spokeswoman
for the Baltimore-based company. ``We can't very well continue to
be associated with something like this.''
   She said the company planned to notify dealers and ask them to
pull the Lite Years flashlights, introduced last year, and the
recently-announced Just-For-Me line off the shelves immediately.
   She didn't know how many products would have to be pulled off
the shelves, but said the Lite Years line had been selling well.
   When the unique batteries were introduced last year, Kodak
touted them as lasting twice as long as 9-volt alkaline batterie
and having a 10-year shelf life.
   However, routine testing last week by Kodak determined the
batteries don't last that long on store shelves or in car glove
compartments, especially when they're used in ``high-drain''
products such as flashlights, Kaska said.
   Kodak officials, who told Black & Decker about the problem, said
the shortened shelf life is caused by a buildup of resistance
inside the battery that prevents full current from being
transmitted.
   The problem is much more noticeable in products where a great
deal of current is needed, rather than ``medium drain'' products,
like smoke detectors or calculators.
   Kaska said the problem would be corrected, however, within a few
weeks, and the claim of 10 years of shelf life would be accurate
once again.
   ``We understand the problem. We know how to fix it and will do
so quickly,'' said James Moxley, president of Ultra Technologies,
the Kodak subsidiary that makes and sells batteries.
   He said the problem, which was discovered last week in ongoing
storage-life tests, does not affect how long the batteries can be
used, only the amount of time they can be stored.
   The less-than-predicted storage life will be corrected by
changing the electrolytic chemical used in the batteries, Moxley
said.
   ``As a matter of good business ethics, we reported the results
of our tests to Black & Decker,'' he said. ``Obviously, we are
disappointed by the company's action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
